"{\n    \"[1, 3]\": [\n        [\n            68804,\n            \"But, Lor\\u2019love yer\\u2019art, now that the old\\u2019ooman has stuck a chunk of her tea-cake in me, an\\u2019rinsed me out with her bloomin\\u2019old teapot, and I\\u2019ve lit hup, you may scratch my ears for all you\\u2019re worth, and won\\u2019t git even a growl out of me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68969,\n            \"That\\u2019ere wolf what we called Bersicker was one of three grey ones that came from Norway to Jamrach\\u2019s, which we bought off him four years ago.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70191,\n            \"\\u201cYe\\u2019ll excoose me, I know, for a-chaffin\\u2019of ye, but the old woman here winked at me, which was as much as telling me to go on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            70368,\n            \"But, Lor\\u2019bless you, in real life a wolf is only a low creature, not half so clever or bold as a good dog;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 4]\": [\n        [\n            28816,\n            \"No, I don\\u2019t, for there was Mr. Morris telling us his stories, and Arthur never told any, and yet-- My dear, I am somewhat previous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28907,\n            \"I must tell you beforehand that Mr. Morris doesn\\u2019t always speak slang-that is to say, he never does so to strangers or before them, for he is really well educated and has exquisite manners-but he found out that it amused me to hear him talk American slang, and whenever I was present, and there was no one to be shocked, he said such funny things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28985,\n            \"I am afraid, my dear, he has to invent it all, for it fits exactly into whatever else he has to say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29051,\n            \"Well, Mr. Morris sat down beside me and looked as happy and jolly as he could, but I could see all the same that he was very nervous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29083,\n            \"He took my hand in his, and said ever so sweetly:-\\u201c\\u2018 Miss Lucy, I know I ain\\u2019t good enough to regulate the fixin\\u2019s of your little shoes, but I guess if you wait till you find a man that is you will go join them seven young women with the lamps when you quit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29149,\n            \"Won\\u2019t you just hitch up alongside of me and let us go down the long road together, driving in double harness?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29174,\n            \"\\u2019 \\u201cWell, he did look so good-humoured and so jolly that it didn\\u2019t seem half so hard to refuse him as it did poor Dr. Seward;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29240,\n            \"Then he said that he had spoken in a light manner, and he hoped that if he had made a mistake in doing so on so grave, so momentous, an occasion for him, I would forgive him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29282,\n            \"He really did look serious when he was saying it, and I couldn\\u2019t help feeling a bit serious too-I know, Mina, you will think me a horrid flirt-though I couldn\\u2019t help feeling a sort of exultation that he was number two in one day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29338,\n            \"And then, my dear, before I could say a word he began pouring out a perfect torrent of love-making, laying his very heart and soul at my feet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29372,\n            \"He looked so earnest over it that I shall never again think that a man must be playful always, and never earnest, because he is merry at times.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29403,\n            \"I suppose he saw something in my face which checked him, for he suddenly stopped, and said with a sort of manly fervour that I could have loved him for if I had been free:-\\u201c\\u2018 Lucy, you are an honest-hearted girl, I know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29457,\n            \"I should not be here speaking to you as I am now if I did not believe you clean grit, right through to the very depths of your soul.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29488,\n            \"Tell me, like one good fellow to another, is there any one else that you care for?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29508,\n            \"And if there is I\\u2019ll never trouble you a hair\\u2019s breadth again, but will be, if you will let me, a very faithful friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29561,\n            \"Here was I almost making fun of this great-hearted, true gentleman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29646,\n            \"I am glad to say that, though I was crying, I was able to look into Mr. Morris\\u2019 s brave eyes, and I told him out straight:-\\u201c\\u2018 Yes, there is some one I love, though he has not told me yet that he even loves me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29704,\n            \"\\u2019 I was right to speak to him so frankly, for quite a light came into his face, and he put out both his hands and took mine-I think I put them into his-and said in a hearty way:-\\u201c\\u2018 That\\u2019s my brave girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30525,\n            \"I seemed to wish to keep him to the point of his madness-a thing which I avoid with the patients as I would the mouth of hell.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31012,\n            \"\\u201d Telegram from Arthur Holmwood to Quincey P.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115531,\n            \"- Lord Godalming and Mr. Morris arrived earlier than we expected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115592,\n            \"Of course they had heard Lucy speak of me, and it seemed that Dr. Van Helsing, too, has been quite \\u201cblowing my trumpet,\\u201das Mr. Morris expressed it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117024,\n            \"\\\"-the very words he had used to Lucy, and oh, but he proved himself a friend!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117056,\n            \"- I got home at five o\\u2019clock, and found that Godalming and Morris had not only arrived, but had already studied the transcript of the various diaries and letters which Harker and his wonderful wife had made and arranged.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120430,\n            \"Jonathan held my right with his left and stretched across to Mr. Morris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122121,\n            \"\\u201d Whilst they were talking Mr. Morris was looking steadily at the window, and he now got up quietly, and went out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122367,\n            \"As he did so we heard Mr. Morris\\u2019 s voice without:-\\u201cSorry!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122385,\n            \"I fear I have alarmed you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122392,\n            \"I shall come in and tell you about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122402,\n            \"\\u201d A minute later he came in and said:-\\u201cIt was an idiotic thing of me to do, and I ask your pardon, Mrs. Harker, most sincerely;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122437,\n            \"I fear I must have frightened you terribly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122513,\n            \"You used to laugh at me for it then, Art.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122558,\n            \"\\u201d Without saying any more he took his seat, and the Professor began to resume his statement:-\\u201cWe must trace each of these boxes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122831,\n            \"Mr. Morris resumed the discussion:-\\u201cAs there is no time to lose, I vote we have a look at his house right now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122977,\n            \"I shall lie down and pretend to sleep, lest Jonathan have added anxiety about me when he returns.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127644,\n            \"A few minutes later I saw Morris step suddenly back from a corner, which he was examining.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            127663,\n            \"We all followed his movements with our eyes, for undoubtedly some nervousness was growing on us, and we saw a whole mass of phosphorescence, which twinkled like stars.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145231,\n            \"I did not see him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145253,\n            \"I expected to see him in some shape go back to Carfax;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145305,\n            \"\\u201d He said the latter words through his shut teeth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149665,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cLook here, old fellow,\\u201dsaid Morris, \\u201cit is a capital idea to have all ready in case we want to go horsebacking;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149728,\n            \"It seems to me that we ought to take cabs when we go south or east;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149770,\n            \"\\u201cHis head is what you call in plane with the horizon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152298,\n            \"Godalming and Morris hurried off in a cab, we following in another.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152455,\n            \"Morris paid the cabman, who touched his hat and drove away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153233,\n            \"When we had examined this last find, Lord Godalming and Quincey Morris taking accurate notes of the various addresses of the houses in the East and the South, took with them the keys in a great bunch, and set out to destroy the boxes in these places.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153318,\n            \"- The time seemed terrible long whilst we were waiting for the coming of Godalming and Quincey Morris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154945,\n            \"The gladness of our hearts must have shown upon our faces when on the step, close to the door, we saw Lord Godalming and Quincey Morris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156395,\n            \"Godalming and Morris had rushed out into the yard, and Harker had lowered himself from the window to follow the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166925,\n            \"We went to his room, and within a minute Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, and Mr. Morris were with us also.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170745,\n            \"Morris and Godalming and I shall prevent interference, even if we have to use the arms which we shall have ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181628,\n            \"I felt so thankful that Lord Godalming is rich, and that both he and Mr. Morris, who also has plenty of money, are willing to spend it so freely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181733,\n            \"Dr. Seward and Mr. Morris have half a dozen good horses, well appointed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182279,\n            \"Mr. Morris and Dr. Seward were off on their long ride before we started;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183071,\n            \"I wonder how Dr. Seward and Mr. Morris are getting on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188100,\n            \"Oh, if only Morris and Seward were with us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191507,\n            \"Instinctively they reined in, and at the instant Lord Godalming and Jonathan dashed up at one side and Dr. Seward and Mr. Morris on the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191840,\n            \"In the midst of this I could see that Jonathan on one side of the ring of men, and Quincey on the other, were forcing a way to the cart;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192066,\n            \"He had parried with his great bowie knife, and at first I thought that he too had come through in safety;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192089,\n            \"but as he sprang beside Jonathan, who had by now jumped from the cart, I could see that with his left hand he was clutching at his side, and that the blood was spurting through his fingers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192364,\n            \"whilst at the same moment Mr. Morris\\u2019 s bowie knife plunged into the heart.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 5]\": [\n        [\n            56402,\n            \"I have asked him to come over, and as you told me that all things were to be at your charge, I have mentioned to him who you are and your relations to Miss Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56469,\n            \"Van Helsing would, I know, do anything for me for a personal reason, so, no matter on what ground he comes, we must accept his wishes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56501,\n            \"He is a seemingly arbitrary man, but this is because he knows what he is talking about better than any one else.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56525,\n            \"He is a philosopher and a metaphysician, and one of the most advanced scientists of his day;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56544,\n            \"and he has, I believe, an absolutely open mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56556,\n            \"This, with an iron nerve, a temper of the ice-brook, an indomitable resolution, self-command, and toleration exalted from virtues to blessings, and the kindliest and truest heart that beats-these form his equipment for the noble work that he is doing for mankind-work both in theory and practice, for his views are as wide as his all-embracing sympathy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56631,\n            \"I tell you these facts that you may know why I have such confidence in him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56648,\n            \"I have asked him to come at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56990,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear Art,-\\u201cVan Helsing has come and gone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57004,\n            \"He came on with me to Hillingham, and found that, by Lucy\\u2019s discretion, her mother was lunching out, so that we were alone with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57036,\n            \"Van Helsing made a very careful examination of the patient.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57047,\n            \"He is to report to me, and I shall advise you, for of course I was not present all the time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57071,\n            \"He is, I fear, much concerned, but says he must think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57086,\n            \"When I told him of our friendship and how you trust to me in the matter, he said: \\u2018 You must tell him all you think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57115,\n            \"Tell him what I think, if you can guess it, if you will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57151,\n            \"\\u2019 I asked what he meant by that, for he was very serious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57166,\n            \"This was when we had come back to town, and he was having a cup of tea before starting on his return to Amsterdam.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57192,\n            \"He would not give me any further clue.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57201,\n            \"You must not be angry with me, Art, because his very reticence means that all his brains are working for her good.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57268,\n            \"He seemed not to notice, but remarked that the smuts in London were not quite so bad as they used to be when he was a student here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57369,\n            \"She was very sweet to the professor (as she always is), and tried to make him feel at ease;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57408,\n            \"I believe Van Helsing saw it, too, for I saw the quick look under his bushy brows that I knew of old.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59320,\n            \"I took advantage of the opportunity, and told her that my old master, Van Helsing, the great specialist, was coming to stay with me, and that I would put her in his charge conjointly with myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59479,\n            \"- The first thing Van Helsing said to me when we met at Liverpool Street was:-\\u201cHave you said anything to our young friend the lover of her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59535,\n            \"I wrote him a letter simply telling him that you were coming, as Miss Westenra was not so well, and that I should let him know if need be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59567,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cRight, my friend,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cquite right!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59611,\n            \"And, my good friend John, let me caution you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59713,\n            \"You and I shall keep as yet what we know here, and here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59728,\n            \"\\u201d He touched me on the heart and on the forehead, and then touched himself the same way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59789,\n            \"\\u201d He stopped and looked at me, and said:-\\u201cMy friend John, when the corn is grown, even before it has ripened-while the milk of its mother-earth is in him, and the sunshine has not yet begun to paint him with his gold, the husbandman he pull the ear and rub him between his rough hands, and blow away the green chaff, and say to you: \\u2018 Look!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59889,\n            \"\\u2019 \\u201cI did not see the application, and told him so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59903,\n            \"For reply he reached over and took my ear in his hand and pulled it playfully, as he used long ago to do at lectures, and said: \\u201cThe good husbandman tell you so then because he knows, but not till then.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60041,\n            \"\\u201d He broke off, for he evidently saw that I understood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60054,\n            \"Then he went on, and very gravely:-\\u201cYou were always a careful student, and your case-book was ever more full than the rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60528,\n            \"Van Helsing and I were shown up to Lucy\\u2019s room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60646,\n            \"Then Van Helsing beckoned to me, and we went gently out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60662,\n            \"The instant we had closed the door he stepped quickly along the passage to the next door, which was open.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60684,\n            \"Then he pulled me quickly in with him and closed the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60747,\n            \"Is it you or me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61155,\n            \"Van Helsing slapped him on the shoulder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61346,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur turned to him and said:-\\u201cIf you only knew how gladly I would die for her you would understand--\\u201dHe stopped, with a sort of choke in his voice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61709,\n            \"Friend John, help to me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61716,\n            \"\\u201d So neither of us looked whilst he bent over her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61728,\n            \"Van Helsing turning to me, said: \\u201cHe is so young and strong and of blood so pure that we need not defibrinate it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61938,\n            \"I dressed the wound and took his arm to bring him away, when Van Helsing spoke without turning round-the man seems to have eyes in the back of his head:-\\u201cThe brave lover, I think, deserve another kiss, which he shall have presently.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62012,\n            \"As he did so the narrow black velvet band which she seems always to wear round her throat, buckled with an old diamond buckle which her lover had given her, was dragged a little up, and showed a red mark on her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62059,\n            \"Arthur did not notice it, but I could hear the deep hiss of indrawn breath which is one of Van Helsing\\u2019s ways of betraying emotion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62088,\n            \"He said nothing at the moment, but turned to me, saying: \\u201cNow take down our brave young lover, give him of the port wine, and let him lie down a while.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62301,\n            \"I asked the Professor in a whisper:-\\u201cWhat do you make of that mark on her throat?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62653,\n            \"He came back a moment later and put his head inside the door and said with warning finger held up:-\\u201cRemember, she is your charge.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62777,\n            \"When I told Mrs. Westenra that Dr. Van Helsing had directed that I should sit up with her she almost pooh-poohed the idea, pointing out her daughter\\u2019s renewed strength and excellent spirits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63272,\n            \"I sent a short wire to Van Helsing and to Arthur, telling them of the excellent result of the operation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63342,\n            \"A telegram came from Van Helsing at Amsterdam whilst I was at dinner, suggesting that I should be at Hillingham to-night, as it might be well to be at hand, and stating that he was leaving by the night mail and would join me early in the morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63856,\n            \"How I slept, with that dear, good Dr. Seward watching me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63871,\n            \"And to-night I shall not fear to sleep, since he is close at hand and within call.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63920,\n            \"- I was conscious of the Professor\\u2019s hand on my head, and started awake all in a second.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63986,\n            \"\\u201cCome, let us see,\\u201dhe said.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64005,\n            \"The blind was down, and I went over to raise it gently, whilst Van Helsing stepped, with his soft, cat-like tread, over to the bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64038,\n            \"As I raised the blind, and the morning sunlight flooded the room, I heard the Professor\\u2019s low hiss of inspiration, and knowing its rarity, a deadly fear shot through my heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64076,\n            \"As I passed over he moved back, and his exclamation of horror, \\u201cGott in Himmel!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64248,\n            \"He wetted the poor white lips with it, and together we rubbed palm and wrist and heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64393,\n            \"After a time-it did not seem a short time either, for the draining away of one\\u2019s blood, no matter how willingly it be given, is a terrible feeling-Van Helsing held up a warning finger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64575,\n            \"The Professor watched me critically.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64607,\n            \"\\u201d To which he smiled a sad sort of smile as he replied:-\\u201cHe is her lover, her fianc\\u00e9.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64652,\n            \"\\u201d When we stopped the operation, he attended to Lucy, whilst I applied digital pressure to my own incision.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64674,\n            \"I laid down, whilst I waited his leisure to attend to me, for I felt faint and a little sick.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64697,\n            \"By-and-by he bound up my wound, and sent me downstairs to get a glass of wine for myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64721,\n            \"As I was leaving the room, he came after me, and half whispered:-\\u201cMind, nothing must be said of this.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64784,\n            \"\\u201d When I came back he looked at me carefully, and then said:-\\u201cYou are not much the worse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64834,\n            \"\\u201d I followed out his orders, for I knew how right and wise they were.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65005,\n            \"When Van Helsing had seen her, he went out for a walk, leaving me in charge, with strict injunctions that I was not to leave her for a moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65038,\n            \"I could hear his voice in the hall, asking the way to the nearest telegraph office.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65229,\n            \"Van Helsing returned in a couple of hours, and presently said to me: \\u201cNow you go home, and eat much and drink enough.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65278,\n            \"You and I must watch the case, and we must have none other to know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65363,\n            \"and when I said it was Dr. Van Helsing\\u2019s wish that either he or I should sit up, they asked me quite piteously to intercede with the \\u201cforeign gentleman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65505,\n            \"Shortly after I had arrived, a big parcel from abroad came for the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65542,\n            \"\\u201cThese are for you, Miss Lucy,\\u201dhe said.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65593,\n            \"\\u201cNay, but they are not to take in a decoction or in nauseous form, so you need not snub that so charming nose, or I shall point out to my friend Arthur what woes he may have to endure in seeing so much beauty that he so loves so much distort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65676,\n            \"I put him in your window, I make pretty wreath, and hang him round your neck, so that you sleep well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65763,\n            \"Now she threw them down, saying, with half-laughter, and half-disgust:-\\u201cOh, Professor, I believe you are only putting up a joke on me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65808,\n            \"\\u201d To my surprise, Van Helsing rose up and said with all his sternness, his iron jaw set and his bushy eyebrows meeting:-\\u201cNo trifling with me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65854,\n            \"and I warn you that you do not thwart me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65879,\n            \"\\u201d Then seeing poor Lucy scared, as she might well be, he went on more gently: \\u201cOh, little miss, my dear, do not fear me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65912,\n            \"I only do for your good;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65932,\n            \"See, I place them myself in your room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65942,\n            \"I make myself the wreath that you are to wear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66000,\n            \"Come with me, friend John, and you shall help me deck the room with my garlic, which is all the way from Haarlem, where my friend Vanderpool raise herb in his glass-houses all the year.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66069,\n            \"The Professor\\u2019s actions were certainly odd and not to be found in any pharmacop\\u0153ia that I ever heard of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66172,\n            \"It all seemed grotesque to me, and presently I said:-\\u201cWell, Professor, I know you always have a reason for what you do, but this certainly puzzles me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66208,\n            \"It is well we have no sceptic here, or he would say that you were working some spell to keep out an evil spirit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66260,\n            \"We then waited whilst Lucy made her toilet for the night, and when she was in bed he came and himself fixed the wreath of garlic round her neck.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66367,\n            \"\\u201d As we left the house in my fly, which was waiting, Van Helsing said:-\\u201cTo-night I can sleep in peace, and sleep I want-two nights of travel, much reading in the day between, and much anxiety on the day to follow, and a night to sit up, without to wink.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66433,\n            \"To-morrow in the morning early you call for me, and we come together to see our pretty miss, so much more strong for my \\u2018 spell\\u2019which I have work.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66473,\n            \"\\u201d He seemed so confident that I, remembering my own confidence two nights before and with the baneful result, felt awe and vague terror.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66500,\n            \"It must have been my weakness that made me hesitate to tell it to my friend, but I felt it all the more, like unshed tears.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66549,\n            \"I quite love that dear Dr. Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66559,\n            \"I wonder why he was so anxious about these flowers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66570,\n            \"He positively frightened me, he was so fierce.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66580,\n            \"And yet he must have been right, for I feel comfort from them already.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66820,\n            \"Van Helsing and I arrived at Hillingham at eight o\\u2019clock.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67266,\n            \"Then, for the first time in my life, I saw Van Helsing break down.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67556,\n            \"Once again I drew up the blind, whilst Van Helsing went towards the bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67749,\n            \"This time I watched whilst Van Helsing recruited himself and rested.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68013,\n            \"Since, however, Dr. Van Helsing has been with me, all this bad dreaming seems to have passed away;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71382,\n            \"Happily Van Helsing has not summoned me, so I need not forego my sleep;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71512,\n            \"The arrival of Van Helsing\\u2019s telegram filled me with dismay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71680,\n            \"I went to bed as usual, taking care that the flowers were placed as Dr. Van Helsing directed, and soon fell asleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71742,\n            \"I was not afraid, but I did wish that Dr. Seward was in the next room-as Dr. Van Helsing said he would be-so that I might have called him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73272,\n            \"They stopped at the gate, and a few seconds later I met Van Helsing running up the avenue.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73292,\n            \"When he saw me, he gasped out:-\\u201cThen it was you, and just arrived.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73321,\n            \"Did you not get my telegram?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73328,\n            \"\\u201d I answered as quickly and coherently as I could that I had only got his telegram early in the morning, and had not lost a minute in coming here, and that I could not make any one in the house hear me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73374,\n            \"He paused and raised his hat as he said solemnly:-\\u201cThen I fear we are too late.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73458,\n            \"The Professor took a small surgical saw from his case, and handing it to me, pointed to the iron bars which guarded the window.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73520,\n            \"I helped the Professor in, and followed him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73617,\n            \"Van Helsing and I looked at each other, and as we moved away he said: \\u201cWe can attend to them later.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73835,\n            \"then he gave a quick turn of his head, as of one who listens, and leaping to his feet, he cried out to me:-\\u201cIt is not yet too late!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73936,\n            \"I did not stay to make sure, but returned to Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73976,\n            \"He said to me:-\\u201cI can do this, all that can be at the present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74317,\n            \"I never saw in all my experience the Professor work in such deadly earnest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74332,\n            \"I knew-as he knew-that it was a stand-up fight with death, and in a pause told him so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74358,\n            \"He answered me in a way that I did not understand, but with the sternest look that his face could wear:-\\u201cIf that were all, I would stop here where we are now, and let her fade away into peace, for I see no light in life over her horizon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74473,\n            \"Van Helsing\\u2019s face almost beamed, and as we lifted her from the bath and rolled her in a hot sheet to dry her he said to me:-\\u201cThe first gain is ours!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74548,\n            \"I noticed that Van Helsing tied a soft silk handkerchief round her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74585,\n            \"Van Helsing called in one of the women, and told her to stay with her and not to take her eyes off her till we returned, and then beckoned me out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74622,\n            \"\\u201cWe must consult as to what is to be done,\\u201dhe said as we descended the stairs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74643,\n            \"In the hall he opened the dining-room door, and we passed in, he closing the door carefully behind him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74734,\n            \"He was evidently torturing his mind about something, so I waited for an instant, and he spoke:-\\u201cWhat are we to do now?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74811,\n            \"I fear to trust those women, even if they would have courage to submit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74885,\n            \"Van Helsing started angrily at the first sound, but his face softened and a glad look came into his eyes as I cried out: \\u201cQuincey Morris!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74946,\n            \"\\u201d He handed me a telegram:-\\u201cHave not heard from Seward for three days, and am terribly anxious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75005,\n            \"You know you have only to tell me what to do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75017,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing strode forward, and took his hand, looking him straight in the eyes as he said:-\\u201cA brave man\\u2019s blood is the best thing on this earth when a woman is in trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75206,\n            \"The Professor watched whilst I went downstairs with Quincey Morris, and sent one of the maids to pay off one of the cabmen who were waiting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75275,\n            \"When I came softly in, I found Van Helsing with a sheet or two of note-paper in his hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75319,\n            \"There was a look of grim satisfaction in his face, as of one who has had a doubt solved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75340,\n            \"He handed me the paper saying only: \\u201cIt dropped from Lucy\\u2019s breast when we carried her to the bath.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75364,\n            \"\\u201d When I had read it, I stood looking at the Professor, and after a pause asked him: \\u201cIn God\\u2019s name, what does it all mean?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75431,\n            \"Van Helsing put out his hand and took the paper, saying:-\\u201cDo not trouble about it now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75476,\n            \"And now what is it that you came to me to say?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75566,\n            \"I know, and you know, and the other doctor who attended her knows, that Mrs. Westenra had disease of the heart, and we can certify that she died of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75666,\n            \"One, two, three, all open their veins for her, besides one old man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75684,\n            \"Ah yes, I know, friend John;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75698,\n            \"I love you all the more for it!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75747,\n            \"and that Van Helsing and I were with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75888,\n            \"From his putting his finger to his lips, I gathered that he expected her to wake before long and was afraid of forestalling nature.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76139,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThat\\u2019s so,\\u201dI said, and he went on:-\\u201cI take it that both you and Van Helsing had done already what I did to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76199,\n            \"When I saw him four days ago down at his own place he looked queer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76397,\n            \"I paused before answering, for I felt that I must not betray anything which the Professor wished kept secret;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76418,\n            \"but already he knew so much, and guessed so much, that there could be no reason for not answering, so I answered in the same phrase: \\u201cThat\\u2019s so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76520,\n            \"\\u201d Then, coming close to me, he spoke in a fierce half-whisper: \\u201cWhat took it out?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76561,\n            \"Van Helsing is simply frantic about it, and I am at my wits\\u2019 end.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76627,\n            \"\\u201d Quincey held out his hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76662,\n            \"\\u201d When she woke late in the afternoon, Lucy\\u2019s first movement was to feel in her breast, and, to my surprise, produced the paper which Van Helsing had given me to read.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76721,\n            \"Her eye then lit on Van Helsing and on me too, and gladdened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76975,\n            \"The Professor and I took it in turns to watch, and we never left her for a moment unattended.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77061,\n            \"At times she slept, and both Van Helsing and I noticed the difference in her, between sleeping and waking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79157,\n            \"They are as follows:-Jack Smollet, of Dudding\\u2019s Rents, King George\\u2019s Road, Great Walworth, and Thomas Snelling, Peter Farley\\u2019s Row, Guide Court, Bethnal Green.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79809,\n            \"I duly relieved Van Helsing in his watch over Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79969,\n            \"You shall lie on one, and I on the other, and our sympathy will be comfort to each other, even though we do not speak, and even if we sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80004,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur went off with him, casting back a longing look on Lucy\\u2019s face, which lay in her pillow, almost whiter than the lawn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80055,\n            \"I could see that the Professor had carried out in this room, as in the other, his purpose of using the garlic;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80080,\n            \"the whole of the window-sashes reeked with it, and round Lucy\\u2019s neck, over the silk handkerchief which Van Helsing made her keep on, was a rough chaplet of the same odorous flowers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80319,\n            \"Presently she woke, and I gave her food, as Van Helsing had prescribed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80523,\n            \"\\u201d Then he bent down, and, with his face almost touching Lucy\\u2019s, examined her carefully.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80544,\n            \"He removed the flowers and lifted the silk handkerchief from her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80613,\n            \"For fully five minutes Van Helsing stood looking at her, with his face at its sternest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80631,\n            \"Then he turned to me and said calmly:-\\u201cShe is dying.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80653,\n            \"It will be much difference, mark me, whether she dies conscious or in her sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80847,\n            \"\\u201d When we came into Lucy\\u2019s room I could see that Van Helsing had, with his usual forethought, been putting matters straight and making everything look as pleasing as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80939,\n            \"\\u201d He was stooping to kiss her, when Van Helsing motioned him back.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81156,\n            \"but at that instant Van Helsing, who, like me, had been startled by her voice, swooped upon him, and catching him by the neck with both hands, dragged him back with a fury of strength which I never thought he could have possessed, and actually hurled him almost across the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81234,\n            \"\\u201d And he stood between them like a lion at bay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81288,\n            \"I kept my eyes fixed on Lucy, as did Van Helsing, and we saw a spasm as of rage flit like a shadow over her face;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81333,\n            \"Very shortly after she opened her eyes in all their softness, and putting out her poor, pale, thin hand, took Van Helsing\\u2019s great brown one;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81374,\n            \"\\u201cMy true friend,\\u201dshe said, in a faint voice, but with untellable pathos, \\u201cMy true friend, and his!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81417,\n            \"\\u201d he said solemnly, kneeling beside her and holding up his hand, as one who registers an oath.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81438,\n            \"Then he turned to Arthur, and said to him: \\u201cCome, my child, take her hand in yours, and kiss her on the forehead, and only once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81699,\n            \"\\u201d I stood beside Van Helsing, and said:-\\u201cAh, well, poor girl, there is peace for her at last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81759,\n            \"\\u201d When I asked him what he meant, he only shook his head and answered:-\\u201cWe can do nothing as yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81822,\n            \"I attended to all the ghastly formalities, and the urbane undertaker proved that his staff were afflicted-or blessed-with something of his own obsequious suavity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81989,\n            \"Under the circumstances, Van Helsing and I took it upon ourselves to examine papers, etc.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82018,\n            \"I asked him why, for I feared that he, being a foreigner, might not be quite aware of English legal requirements, and so might in ignorance make some unnecessary trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82065,\n            \"You forget that I am a lawyer as well as a doctor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82097,\n            \"I have more than him to avoid.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82382,\n            \"But I have them here, and we shall for the present say nothing of them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82399,\n            \"I shall see that poor lad to-morrow evening, and, with his sanction, I shall use some.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82421,\n            \"\\u201d When we had finished the work in hand, he said to me:-\\u201cAnd now, friend John, I think we may to bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82451,\n            \"We want sleep, both you and I, and rest to recuperate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82555,\n            \"when the Professor bent over and turned it gently back, we both started at the beauty before us, the tall wax candles showing a sufficient light to note it well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82651,\n            \"He had not loved her as I had, and there was no need for tears in his eyes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82748,\n            \"He restored the sheet to its place, and we came away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82761,\n            \"I was undressing in my own room, when, with a premonitory tap at the door, he entered, and at once began to speak:-\\u201cTo-morrow I want you to bring me, before night, a set of post-mortem knives.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83098,\n            \"\\u201d For answer he put his hand on my shoulder, and said, with infinite tenderness:-\\u201cFriend John, I pity your poor bleeding heart;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83654,\n            \"I must have slept long and soundly, for it was broad daylight when Van Helsing waked me by coming into my room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83678,\n            \"He came over to my bedside and said:-\\u201cYou need not trouble about the knives;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83712,\n            \"For his solemnity of the night before had greatly impressed me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83762,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cHow, stolen,\\u201dI asked in wonder, \\u201csince you have it now?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83781,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBecause I get it back from the worthless wretch who stole it, from the woman who robbed the dead and the living.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83807,\n            \"Her punishment will surely come, but not through me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83838,\n            \"\\u201d He went away on the word, leaving me with a new mystery to think of, a new puzzle to grapple with.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84448,\n            \"Van Helsing ordered the former arrangement to be adhered to, explaining that, as Lord Godalming was coming very soon, it would be less harrowing to his feelings to see all that was left of his fianc\\u00e9e quite alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84596,\n            \"With me he was warm as ever, and to Van Helsing he was sweetly courteous;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84627,\n            \"The Professor noticed it, too, and motioned me to bring him upstairs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85911,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur spoke out heartily, like his old self:-\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, you may do what you will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87342,\n            \"and now a telegram from Van Helsing, whoever he may be:-\\u201cYou will be grieved to hear that Mrs. Westenra died five days ago, and that Lucy died the day before yesterday.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87583,\n            \"He is to stop with me then, if he can;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87615,\n            \"I fear that the strain of the past week has broken down even his iron strength.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87632,\n            \"All the time of the burial he was, I could see, putting some terrible restraint on himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87751,\n            \"Arthur and Quincey went away together to the station, and Van Helsing and I came on here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87770,\n            \"The moment we were alone in the carriage he gave way to a regular fit of hysterics.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87788,\n            \"He has denied to me since that it was hysterics, and insisted that it was only his sense of humour asserting itself under very terrible conditions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90312,\n            \"Letter, Van Helsing to Mrs. Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90593,\n            \"\\u201d Telegram, Mrs. Harker to Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90624,\n            \"Can see you any time you call.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90646,\n            \"- I cannot help feeling terribly excited as the time draws near for the visit of Dr. Van Helsing, for somehow I expect that it will throw some light upon Jonathan\\u2019s sad experience;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90684,\n            \"and as he attended poor dear Lucy in her last illness, he can tell me all about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90803,\n            \"She must have told him of her sleep-walking adventure on the cliff, and that I knew all about it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90826,\n            \"and now he wants me to tell him what she knows, so that he may understand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91030,\n            \"I am so glad I have type-written out my own journal, so that, in case he asks about Lucy, I can hand it to him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91260,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing must be a good man as well as a clever one if he is Arthur\\u2019s friend and Dr. Seward\\u2019s, and if they brought him all the way from Holland to look after Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91304,\n            \"I feel from having seen him that he is good and kind and of a noble nature.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91322,\n            \"When he comes to-morrow I shall ask him about Jonathan;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91447,\n            \"In a few minutes Mary opened the door, and announced \\u201cDr. Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91464,\n            \"\\u201d I rose and bowed, and he came towards me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91670,\n            \"He said to me:-\\u201cMrs. Harker, is it not?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91702,\n            \"\\u201cIt is Mina Murray that I came to see that was friend of that poor dear child Lucy Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91723,\n            \"Madam Mina, it is on account of the dead I come.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91736,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cSir,\\u201dI said, \\u201cyou could have no better claim on me than that you were a friend and helper of Lucy Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91773,\n            \"He took it and said tenderly:-\\u201cOh, Madam Mina, I knew that the friend of that poor lily girl must be good, but I had yet to learn--\\u201dHe finished his speech with a courtly bow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91819,\n            \"I asked him what it was that he wanted to see me about, so he at once began:-\\u201cI have read your letters to Miss Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91869,\n            \"I know that you were with her at Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91934,\n            \"In great perplexity then I come to you, and ask you out of your so much kindness to tell me all of it that you can remember.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91963,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI can tell you, I think, Dr. Van Helsing, all about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92006,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo, doctor, but I wrote it all down at the time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92022,\n            \"I can show it to you if you like.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92032,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cOh, Madam Mina, I will be grateful;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92044,\n            \"you will do me much favour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92051,\n            \"\\u201d I could not resist the temptation of mystifying him a bit-I suppose it is some of the taste of the original apple that remains still in our mouths-so I handed him the shorthand diary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92109,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIf you wish,\\u201dI answered as demurely as I could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92155,\n            \"\\u201cI knew long that Mr. Jonathan was a man of much thankfulness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92181,\n            \"And will you not so much honour me and so help me as to read it for me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92224,\n            \"so I took the typewritten copy from my workbasket and handed it to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92254,\n            \"but I had been thinking that it was of dear Lucy that you wished to ask, and so that you might not have time to wait-not on my account, but because I know your time must be precious-I have written it out on the typewriter for you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92317,\n            \"\\u201cYou are so good,\\u201dhe said.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92335,\n            \"I may want to ask you some things when I have read.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92419,\n            \"When I came back, I found him walking hurriedly up and down the room, his face all ablaze with excitement.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92442,\n            \"He rushed up to me and took me by both hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92454,\n            \"\\u201cOh, Madam Mina,\\u201dhe said, \\u201chow can I say what I owe to you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92522,\n            \"Oh, but I am grateful to you, you so clever woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92536,\n            \"Madam \\\"-he said this very solemnly-\\\" if ever Abraham Van Helsing can do anything for you or yours, I trust you will let me know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92567,\n            \"It will be pleasure and delight if I may serve you as a friend;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92582,\n            \"as a friend, but all I have ever learned, all I can ever do, shall be for you and those you love.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92644,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut, doctor, you praise me too much, and-and you do not know me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92665,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNot know you-I, who am old, and who have studied all my life men and women;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92688,\n            \"I, who have made my specialty the brain and all that belongs to him and all that follow from him!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92710,\n            \"And I have read your diary that you have so goodly written for me, and which breathes out truth in every line.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92855,\n            \"\\u201d I saw here an opening to ask him about Jonathan, so I said:-\\u201cHe was almost recovered, but he has been greatly upset by Mr. Hawkins\\u2019 s death.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92908,\n            \"I have read your last two letters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93042,\n            \"I suppose I was hysterical, for I threw myself on my knees and held up my hands to him, and implored him to make my husband well again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93073,\n            \"He took my hands and raised me up, and made me sit on the sofa, and sat by me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93095,\n            \"he held my hand in his, and said to me with, oh, such infinite sweetness:-\\u201cMy life is a barren and lonely one, and so full of work that I have not had much time for friendships;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93140,\n            \"but since I have been summoned to here by my friend John Seward I have known so many good people and seen such nobility that I feel more than ever-and it has grown with my advancing years-the loneliness of my life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93186,\n            \"Believe, me, then, that I come here full of respect for you, and you have given me hope-hope, not in what I am seeking of, but that there are good women still left to make life happy-good women, whose lives and whose truths may make good lesson for the children that are to be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93252,\n            \"I am glad, glad, that I may here be of some use to you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93286,\n            \"I promise you that I will gladly do all for him that I can-all to make his life strong and manly, and your life a happy one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93367,\n            \"You have told me all about Lucy, and so now we shall not speak of it, lest it distress.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93389,\n            \"I shall stay in Exeter to-night, for I want to think much over what you have told me, and when I have thought I will ask you questions, if I may.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93426,\n            \"And then, too, you will tell me of husband Jonathan\\u2019s trouble so far as you can, but not yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93456,\n            \"afterwards you shall tell me all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93463,\n            \"\\u201d After lunch, when we went back to the drawing-room, he said to me:-\\u201cAnd now tell me all about him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93492,\n            \"\\u201d When it came to speaking to this great learned man, I began to fear that he would think me a weak fool, and Jonathan a madman-that journal is all so strange-and I hesitated to go on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93536,\n            \"But he was so sweet and kind, and he had promised to help, and I trusted him, so I said:-\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, what I have to tell you is so queer that you must not laugh at me or at my husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93601,\n            \"you must be kind to me, and not think me foolish that I have even half believed some very strange things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93624,\n            \"\\u201d He reassured me by his manner as well as his words when he said:-\\u201cOh, my dear, if you only know how strange is the matter regarding which I am here, it is you who would laugh.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93669,\n            \"I have learned not to think little of any one\\u2019s belief, no matter how strange it be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93845,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI promise,\\u201dhe said as I gave him the papers;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93860,\n            \"\\u201cI shall in the morning, so soon as I can, come to see you and your husband, if I may.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93929,\n            \"\\u201d He was surprised at my knowledge of the trains off-hand, but he does not know that I have made up all the trains to and from Exeter, so that I may help Jonathan in case he is in a hurry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93975,\n            \"So he took the papers with him and went away, and I sit here thinking-thinking I don\\u2019t know what.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94000,\n            \"Letter (by hand), Van Helsing to Mrs. Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94022,\n            \"\\u201cDear Madam Mina,-\\u201cI have read your husband\\u2019s so wonderful diary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94088,\n            \"and let me tell you from experience of men, that one who would do as he did in going down that wall and to that room-ay, and going a second time-is not one to be injured in permanence by a shock.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94172,\n            \"I am blessed that to-day I come to see you, for I have learn all at once so much that again I am dazzle-dazzle more than ever, and I must think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94221,\n            \"\\u201d Letter, Mrs. Harker to Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94483,\n            \"When I got home last night Mina had supper ready, and when we had supped she told me of Van Helsing\\u2019s visit, and of her having given him the two diaries copied out, and of how anxious she has been about me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94588,\n            \"But, now that I know, I am not afraid, even of the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94636,\n            \"Van Helsing is the man to unmask him and hunt him out, if he is anything like what Mina says.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95253,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cLook here, sir,\\u201dI said, \\u201cdoes what you have to do concern the Count?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95795,\n            \"I have an idea that Van Helsing thinks he knows, too, but he will only let out enough at a time to whet curiosity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95834,\n            \"To-day he came back, and almost bounded into the room at about half-past five o\\u2019clock, and thrust last night\\u2019s \\u201cWestminster Gazette\\u201dinto my hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95891,\n            \"I looked over the paper, for I really did not know what he meant;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95907,\n            \"but he took it from me and pointed out a paragraph about children being decoyed away at Hampstead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96006,\n            \"\\u201d I did not quite understand his answer:-\\u201cThat is true indirectly, but not directly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97598,\n            \"\\u201d He stood up and said solemnly:-\\u201cThen you are wrong.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97634,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cIn God\\u2019s name, Professor Van Helsing, what do you mean?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97728,\n            \"I smote the table hard and rose up as I said to him:-\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, are you mad?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97753,\n            \"\\u201d He raised his head and looked at me, and somehow the tenderness of his face calmed me at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98176,\n            \"He will let two scientists see his case, if he will not let two friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98193,\n            \"We shall tell him nothing, but only that we wish to learn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98634,\n            \"\\u2019 \\u201c\\u201cI hope,\\u201dsaid Van Helsing, \\u201cthat when you are sending the child home you will caution its parents to keep strict watch over it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98858,\n            \"The Professor had evidently noted the road we were to go, for he went on unhesitatingly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99213,\n            \"Van Helsing went about his work systematically.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99991,\n            \"I was chilled and unnerved, and angry with the Professor for taking me on such an errand and with myself for coming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100195,\n            \"I heard the rustle of actual movement where I had first seen the white figure, and coming over, found the Professor holding in his arms a tiny child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100296,\n            \"\\u201cWe shall see,\\u201dsaid the Professor, and with one impulse we took our way out of the churchyard, he carrying the sleeping child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100377,\n            \"\\u201cWe were just in time,\\u201dsaid the Professor thankfully.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100590,\n            \"But I must try to get a few hours\\u2019 sleep, as Van Helsing is to call for me at noon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100613,\n            \"He insists that I shall go with him on another expedition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100704,\n            \"but the Professor told me that we should not want more than an hour at most.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100826,\n            \"I shrugged my shoulders, however, and rested silent, for Van Helsing had a way of going on his own road, no matter who remonstrated.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100896,\n            \"Van Helsing walked over to Lucy\\u2019s coffin, and I followed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101009,\n            \"\\u201d said the Professor in response, and as he spoke he put over his hand, and in a way that made me shudder, pulled back the dead lips and showed the white teeth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101212,\n            \"Van Helsing did not seem to notice my silence;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101463,\n            \"\\u201d This turned my blood cold, and it began to dawn upon me that I was accepting Van Helsing\\u2019s theories;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101622,\n            \"I was, in fact, beginning to shudder at the presence of this being, this Un-Dead, as Van Helsing called it, and to loathe it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101667,\n            \"I waited a considerable time for Van Helsing to begin, but he stood as if wrapped in thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102838,\n            \"Yesterday I was almost willing to accept Van Helsing\\u2019s monstrous ideas;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102868,\n            \"I have no doubt that he believes it all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102878,\n            \"I wonder if his mind can have become in any way unhinged.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102945,\n            \"I am loath to think it, and indeed it would be almost as great a marvel as the other to find that Van Helsing was mad;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102973,\n            \"but anyhow I shall watch him carefully.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103022,\n            \"he told us all that he wanted us to do, but especially addressing himself to Arthur, as if all our wills were centred in his.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103050,\n            \"He began by saying that he hoped we would all come with him too, \\u201cfor,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cthere is a grave duty to be done there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103132,\n            \"I have been curious, too, as to what you mean.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103197,\n            \"\\u201cOh,\\u201dsaid the Professor, \\u201cthen you are nearer the beginning, both of you, than friend John here, who has to go a long way back before he can even get so far as to begin.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103241,\n            \"\\u201d It was evident that he recognised my return to my old doubting frame of mind without my saying a word.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103263,\n            \"Then, turning to the other two, he said with intense gravity:-\\u201cI want your permission to do what I think good this night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103302,\n            \"and when you know what it is I propose to do you will know, and only then, how much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103324,\n            \"Therefore may I ask that you promise me in the dark, so that afterwards, though you may be angry with me for a time-I must not disguise from myself the possibility that such may be-you shall not blame yourselves for anything.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103420,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI thank you, sir,\\u201dsaid Van Helsing proudly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103467,\n            \"Then Arthur spoke out:-\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, I don\\u2019t quite like to \\u2018 buy a pig in a poke,\\u2019as they say in Scotland, and if it be anything in which my honour as a gentleman or my faith as a Christian is concerned, I cannot make such a promise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103529,\n            \"If you can assure me that what you intend does not violate either of these two, then I give my consent at once;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103570,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI accept your limitation,\\u201dsaid Van Helsing, \\u201cand all I ask of you is that if you feel it necessary to condemn any act of mine, you will first consider it well and be satisfied that it does not violate your reservations.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104226,\n            \"What have I done to you that you should torture me so?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104259,\n            \"Are you mad to speak such things, or am I mad to listen to them?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104288,\n            \"I shall not give my consent to anything you do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104322,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing rose up from where he had all the time been seated, and said, gravely and sternly:-\\u201cMy Lord Godalming, I, too, have a duty to do, a duty to others, a duty to you, a duty to the dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104991,\n            \"Van Helsing said to me:-\\u201cYou were with me here yesterday.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105145,\n            \"Van Helsing forced back the leaden flange, and we all looked in and recoiled.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105240,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI swear to you by all that I hold sacred that I have not removed nor touched her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105690,\n            \"I was myself tolerably patient, and half inclined again to throw aside doubt and to accept Van Helsing\\u2019s conclusions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105768,\n            \"As to Van Helsing, he was employed in a definite way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105980,\n            \"Van Helsing reverently lifted his hat as he answered:-\\u201cThe Host.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106399,\n            \"My own heart grew cold as ice, and I could hear the gasp of Arthur, as we recognised the features of Lucy Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106450,\n            \"Van Helsing stepped out, and, obedient to his gesture, we all advanced too;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106482,\n            \"Van Helsing raised his lantern and drew the slide;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106492,\n            \"by the concentrated light that fell on Lucy\\u2019s face we could see that the lips were crimson with fresh blood, and that the stream had trickled over her chin and stained the purity of her lawn death-robe.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106540,\n            \"I could see by the tremulous light that even Van Helsing\\u2019s iron nerve had failed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106582,\n            \"When Lucy-I call the thing that was before us Lucy because it bore her shape-saw us she drew back with an angry snarl, such as a cat gives when taken unawares;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106672,\n            \"had she then to be killed, I could have done it with savage delight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106926,\n            \"She was leaping for them, when Van Helsing sprang forward and held between them his little golden crucifix.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106996,\n            \"Then she turned, and her face was shown in the clear burst of moonlight and by the lamp, which had now no quiver from Van Helsing\\u2019s iron nerves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107258,\n            \"We could hear the click of the closing lantern as Van Helsing held it down;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107298,\n            \"We all looked on in horrified amazement as we saw, when he stood back, the woman, with a corporeal body as real at that moment as our own, pass in through the interstice where scarce a knife-blade could have gone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107345,\n            \"We all felt a glad sense of relief when we saw the Professor calmly restoring the strings of putty to the edges of the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107371,\n            \"When this was done, he lifted the child and said: \\u201cCome now, my friends;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107581,\n            \"Till then I shall not ask you to forgive me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107641,\n            \"- A little before twelve o\\u2019clock we three-Arthur, Quincey Morris, and myself-called for the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107792,\n            \"When we were alone and had heard the last of the footsteps die out up the road, we silently, and as if by ordered intention, followed the Professor to the tomb.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107827,\n            \"He unlocked the door, and we entered, closing it behind us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107889,\n            \"When he again lifted the lid off Lucy\\u2019s coffin we all looked-Arthur trembling like an aspen-and saw that the body lay there in all its death-beauty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107924,\n            \"But there was no love in my own heart, nothing but loathing for the foul Thing which had taken Lucy\\u2019s shape without her soul.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108267,\n            \"When all was ready, Van Helsing said:-\\u201cBefore we do anything, let me tell you this;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109012,\n            \"Then when we begin our prayer for the dead-I shall read him, I have here the book, and the others shall follow-strike in God\\u2019s name, that so all may be well with the dead that we love and that the Un-Dead pass away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109093,\n            \"Van Helsing opened his missal and began to read, and Quincey and I followed as well as we could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109678,\n            \"God bless you that you have given my dear one her soul again, and me peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109696,\n            \"\\u201d He put his hands on the Professor\\u2019s shoulder, and laying his head on his breast, cried for a while silently, whilst we stood unmoving.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109727,\n            \"When he raised his head Van Helsing said to him:-\\u201cAnd now, my child, you may kiss her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109836,\n            \"the Professor and I sawed the top off the stake, leaving the point of it in the body.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109966,\n            \"Before we moved away Van Helsing said:-\\u201cNow, my friends, one step of our work is done, one the most harrowing to ourselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110019,\n            \"I have clues which we can follow;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110048,\n            \"Shall you not all help me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110096,\n            \"\\u201d Each in turn, we took his hand, and the promise was made.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110112,\n            \"Then said the Professor as we moved off:-\\u201cTwo nights hence you shall meet with me and dine together at seven of the clock with friend John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110143,\n            \"I shall entreat two others, two that you know not as yet;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110157,\n            \"and I shall be ready to all our work show and our plans unfold.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110279,\n            \"SEWARD\\u2019S DIARY-continued WHEN we arrived at the Berkeley Hotel, Van Helsing found a telegram waiting for him:-\\u201cAm coming up by train.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110327,\n            \"\\u201cAh, that wonderful Madam Mina,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cpearl among women!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110395,\n            \"over it he told me of a diary kept by Jonathan Harker when abroad, and gave me a typewritten copy of it, as also of Mrs. Harker\\u2019s diary at Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110445,\n            \"When I have returned you will be master of all the facts, and we can then better enter on our inquisition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110503,\n            \"What is here told,\\u201dhe laid his hand heavily and gravely on the packet of papers as he spoke, \\u201cmay be the beginning of the end to you and me and many another;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110557,\n            \"Read all, I pray you, with the open mind;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110673,\n            \"and I was beginning to feel uneasy, lest I might miss my guest, when a sweet-faced, dainty-looking girl stepped up to me, and, after a quick glance, said: \\u201cDr. Seward, is it not?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110916,\n            \"As yet I have not had the chance of looking at the papers which Van Helsing left with me, though they lie open before me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112538,\n            \"Jonathan and I have been working day and night since Professor Van Helsing saw us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112554,\n            \"He is gone to Whitby to get more information, and he will be here to-morrow to help us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113108,\n            \"We must be ready for Dr. Van Helsing when he comes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113188,\n            \"Let us be able to tell him when they come.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115592,\n            \"Of course they had heard Lucy speak of me, and it seemed that Dr. Van Helsing, too, has been quite \\u201cblowing my trumpet,\\u201das Mr. Morris expressed it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115834,\n            \"\\u201d I nodded, and he went on:-\\u201cI don\\u2019t quite see the drift of it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115893,\n            \"I have had one lesson already in accepting facts that should make a man humble to the last hour of his life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115939,\n            \"I could hear the tears in his voice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115948,\n            \"Mr. Morris, with instinctive delicacy, just laid a hand for a moment on his shoulder, and then walked quietly out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116036,\n            \"I sat down beside him and took his hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116046,\n            \"I hope he didn\\u2019t think it forward of me, and that if he ever thinks of it afterwards he never will have such a thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116075,\n            \"There I wrong him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116080,\n            \"I know he never will-he is too true a gentleman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116093,\n            \"I said to him, for I could see that his heart was breaking:-\\u201cI loved dear Lucy, and I know what she was to you, and what you were to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116138,\n            \"and now she is gone, will you not let me be like a sister to you in your trouble?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116159,\n            \"I know what sorrows you have had, though I cannot measure the depth of them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116176,\n            \"If sympathy and pity can help in your affliction, won\\u2019t you let me be of some little service-for Lucy\\u2019s sake?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116217,\n            \"It seemed to me that all that he had of late been suffering in silence found a vent at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116277,\n            \"I felt an infinite pity for him, and opened my arms unthinkingly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116291,\n            \"With a sob he laid his head on my shoulder and cried like a wearied child, whilst he shook with emotion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116338,\n            \"I felt this big sorrowing man\\u2019s head resting on me, as though it were that of the baby that some day may lie on my bosom, and I stroked his hair as though he were my own child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116418,\n            \"He told me that for days and nights past-weary days and sleepless nights-he had been unable to speak with any one, as a man must speak in his time of sorrow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116455,\n            \"There was no woman whose sympathy could be given to him, or with whom, owing to the terrible circumstance with which his sorrow was surrounded, he could speak freely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116488,\n            \"\\u201cI know now how I suffered,\\u201dhe said, as he dried his eyes, \\u201cbut I do not know even yet-and none other can ever know-how much your sweet sympathy has been to me to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116562,\n            \"You will let me be like a brother, will you not, for all our lives-for dear Lucy\\u2019s sake?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116604,\n            \"\\u201cAy, and for your own sake,\\u201dhe added, \\u201cfor if a man\\u2019s esteem and gratitude are ever worth the winning, you have won mine to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116641,\n            \"If ever the future should bring to you a time when you need a man\\u2019s help, believe me, you will not call in vain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116689,\n            \"but if it should ever come, promise me that you will let me know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116705,\n            \"\\u201d He was so earnest, and his sorrow was so fresh, that I felt it would comfort him, so I said:-\\u201cI promise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116735,\n            \"\\u201d As I came along the corridor I saw Mr. Morris looking out of a window.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116753,\n            \"He turned as he heard my footsteps.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116770,\n            \"Then noticing my red eyes, he went on: \\u201cAh, I see you have been comforting him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118334,\n            \"Looking at my watch, I saw that I should go to the station to meet Van Helsing, so I told Mrs. Harker that it was time to leave.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118431,\n            \"May He bless and keep you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118438,\n            \"\\u201d When I went to the station to meet Van Helsing I left the boys behind me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118490,\n            \"Van Helsing stepped from the carriage with the eager nimbleness of a boy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118592,\n            \"\\u201d As I drove to the house I told him of what had passed, and of how my own diary had come to be of some use through Mrs. Harker\\u2019s suggestion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118628,\n            \"at which the Professor interrupted me:-\\u201cAh, that wonderful Madam Mina!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118670,\n            \"The good God fashioned her for a purpose, believe me, when He made that so good combination.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119395,\n            \"Professor Van Helsing took the head of the table, to which Dr. Seward motioned him as he came into the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119539,\n            \"I shall then make known to you something of the history of this man, which has been ascertained for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120222,\n            \"\\u201d Whilst he was speaking, Jonathan had taken my hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120307,\n            \"When the Professor had done speaking my husband looked in my eyes, and I in his;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120364,\n            \"\\u201cI am with you,\\u201dsaid Lord Godalming, \\u201cfor Lucy\\u2019s sake, if for no other reason.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120476,\n            \"We resumed our places, and Dr. Van Helsing went on with a sort of cheerfulness which showed that the serious work had begun.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122039,\n            \"and in one manuscript this very Dracula is spoken of as \\u2018 wampyr,\\u2019which we all understand too well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122061,\n            \"There have been from the loins of this very one great men and good women, and their graves make sacred the earth where alone this foulness can dwell.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122150,\n            \"There was a little pause, and then the Professor went on:-\\u201cAnd now we must settle what we do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122558,\n            \"\\u201d Without saying any more he took his seat, and the Professor began to resume his statement:-\\u201cWe must trace each of these boxes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122587,\n            \"and when we are ready, we must either capture or kill this monster in his lair;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123662,\n            \"What shall any man say of his pleasure at meeting Van Helsing?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124404,\n            \"He said to Renfield in a tone which did not surprise me at the time, but only when I thought of it afterwards-for it was as of one addressing an equal:-\\u201cCan you not tell frankly your real reason for wishing to be free to-night?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124458,\n            \"I will undertake that if you will satisfy even me-a stranger, without prejudice, and with the habit of keeping an open mind-Dr. Seward will give you, at his own risk and on his own responsibility, the privilege you seek.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124635,\n            \"\\u201d He still shook his head as he said:-\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, I have nothing to say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124658,\n            \"Your argument is complete, and if I were free to speak I should not hesitate a moment;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124688,\n            \"I can only ask you to trust me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124853,\n            \"I glanced at Van Helsing, and saw my conviction reflected in his eyes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124980,\n            \"He threw himself on his knees, and held up his hands, wringing them in plaintive supplication, and poured forth a torrent of entreaty, with the tears rolling down his cheeks, and his whole face and form expressive of the deepest emotion:-\\u201cLet me entreat you, Dr. Seward, oh, let me implore you, to let me out of this house at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125055,\n            \"Send me away how you will and where you will;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125104,\n            \"You don\\u2019t know what you do by keeping me here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125159,\n            \"By all you hold sacred-by all you hold dear-by your love that is lost-by your hope that lives-for the sake of the Almighty, take me out of this and save my soul from guilt!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125203,\n            \"Can\\u2019t you hear me, man?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125695,\n            \"\\u201d Lord Godalming and I were silent, but Dr. Van Helsing added:-\\u201cFriend John, you know more of lunatics than I do, and I\\u2019m glad of it, for I fear that if it had been to me to decide I would before that last hysterical outburst have given him free.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125787,\n            \"\\u201d Dr. Seward seemed to answer them both in a dreamy kind of way:-\\u201cI don\\u2019t know but that I agree with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128316,\n            \"\\u201cSo far,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cour night has been eminently successful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128332,\n            \"No harm has come to us such as I feared might be and yet we have ascertained how many boxes are missing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128355,\n            \"More than all do I rejoice that this, our first-and perhaps our most difficult and dangerous-step has been accomplished without the bringing thereinto our most sweet Madam Mina or troubling her waking or sleeping thoughts with sights and sounds and smells of horror which she might never forget.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129743,\n            \"you are the old fool Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129772,\n            \"\\u201d Not a word more would he say, but sat in his implacable sullenness as indifferent to me as though I had not been in the room at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129976,\n            \"\\u201d So Van Helsing has gone to confer with Mrs. Harker and Harker;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131603,\n            \"I would get Dr. Van Helsing or Dr. Seward to prescribe something for me which would make me sleep, only that I fear to alarm them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135732,\n            \"when I had finished Van Helsing said:-\\u201cThis has been a great day\\u2019s work, friend Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135844,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWe got into the other,\\u201danswered Lord Godalming quickly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135962,\n            \"By-and-by he stopped and said, turning from one to another of us:-\\u201cQuincey\\u2019s head is level.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136024,\n            \"\\u201d As nothing could well be done before morning, and as it would be at least advisable to wait till Lord Godalming should hear from Mitchell\\u2019s, we decided not to take any active step before breakfast time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136245,\n            \"This morning, when I went to see him after his repulse of Van Helsing, his manner was that of a man commanding destiny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137072,\n            \"Van Helsing sits in my study poring over the record prepared by the Harkers;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137119,\n            \"I would have taken him with me to see the patient, only I thought that after his last repulse he might not care to go again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138477,\n            \"- I went after my round to Van Helsing and told him my suspicion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139771,\n            \"\\u201d I said to him:-\\u201cGo to Dr. Van Helsing, and ask him to kindly come here at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139796,\n            \"I want him without an instant\\u2019s delay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139806,\n            \"\\u201d The man ran off, and within a few minutes the Professor, in his dressing gown and slippers, appeared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139829,\n            \"When he saw Renfield on the ground, he looked keenly at him a moment, and then turned to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139851,\n            \"I think he recognised my thought in my eyes, for he said very quietly, manifestly for the ears of the attendant:-\\u201cAh, a sad accident!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139894,\n            \"I shall stay with you myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139908,\n            \"If you will remain I shall in a few minutes join you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139968,\n            \"for, almost before he looked at the patient, he whispered to me:-\\u201cSend the attendant away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140031,\n            \"You had better go your round, and Dr. Van Helsing will operate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140100,\n            \"The Professor thought a moment and said:-\\u201cWe must reduce the pressure and get back to normal conditions, as far as can be;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140184,\n            \"I went over and opened it and found in the corridor without, Arthur and Quincey in pajamas and slippers: the former spoke:-\\u201cI heard your man call up Dr. Van Helsing and tell him of an accident.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140416,\n            \"\\u201cWe shall wait,\\u201dsaid Van Helsing, \\u201cjust long enough to fix the best spot for trephining, so that we may most quickly and perfectly remove the blood clot;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140473,\n            \"I had a horrible sinking in my heart, and from Van Helsing\\u2019s face I gathered that he felt some fear or apprehension as to what was to come.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140716,\n            \"I looked up at the Professor and caught his eyes fixed on mine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140961,\n            \"Then Van Helsing said in a quiet grave tone:-\\u201cTell us your dream, Mr. Renfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140982,\n            \"\\u201d As he heard the voice his face brightened, through its mutilation, and he said:-\\u201cThat is Dr. Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141422,\n            \"\\u201d As he spoke, Van Helsing\\u2019s eyes never blinked, but his hand came out and met mine and gripped it hard.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141473,\n            \"Renfield proceeded:-\\u201cHe came up to the window in the mist, as I had seen him often before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141663,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing nodded to him as he whispered to me unconsciously:-\\u201cThe Acherontia Aitetropos of the Sphinges-what you call the \\u2018 Death\\u2019s-head Moth \\u2019?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142067,\n            \"I was about to call him back to the point, but Van Helsing whispered to me: \\u201cLet him go on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142245,\n            \"I thought that, somehow, Mrs. Harker had come into the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142365,\n            \"he went on:-\\u201cI didn\\u2019t know that she was here till she spoke;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142403,\n            \"I like them with lots of blood in them, and hers had all seemed to have run out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142434,\n            \"but when she went away I began to think, and it made me mad to know that He had been taking the life out of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142563,\n            \"and I thought I was going to win, for I didn\\u2019t mean Him to take any more of her life, till I saw His eyes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142671,\n            \"\\u201cWe know the worst now,\\u201dhe said.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142773,\n            \"The Professor had his ready, and as we met in the corridor he pointed to them significantly as he said:-\\u201cThey never leave me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142846,\n            \"his voice was breaking, and I do not know if rage or terror predominated in my own heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142874,\n            \"Art and Quincey held back, and the latter said:-\\u201cShould we disturb her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142892,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWe must,\\u201dsaid Van Helsing grimly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142937,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing said solemnly, \\u201cYou are always right;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143052,\n            \"The Professor did actually fall, and I saw across him as he gathered himself up from hands and knees.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143206,\n            \"With his left hand he held both Mrs. Harker\\u2019s hands, keeping them away with her arms at full tension;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143413,\n            \"But by this time the Professor had gained his feet, and was holding towards him the envelope which contained the Sacred Wafer.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143437,\n            \"The Count suddenly stopped, just as poor Lucy had done outside the tomb, and cowered back.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143535,\n            \"Van Helsing, Art, and I moved forward to Mrs. Harker, who by this time had drawn her breath and with it had given a scream so wild, so ear-piercing, so despairing that it seems to me now that it will ring in my ears till my dying day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143696,\n            \"Van Helsing stepped forward and drew the coverlet gently over her body, whilst Art, after looking at her face for an instant despairingly, ran out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143728,\n            \"Van Helsing whispered to me:-\\u201cJonathan is in a stupor such as we know the Vampire can produce.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143772,\n            \"\\u201d He dipped the end of a towel in cold water and with it began to flick him on the face, his wife all the while holding her face between her hands and sobbing in a way that was heart-breaking to hear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144012,\n            \"\\u201cDr. Seward, Dr. Van Helsing, what is it?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144139,\n            \"\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, you love Mina, I know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144291,\n            \"Van Helsing and I tried to calm them both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144301,\n            \"The Professor held up his little golden crucifix, and said with wonderful calmness:-\\u201cDo not fear, my dear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144601,\n            \"After a while her sobs became less frequent and more faint, and then he said to me, speaking with a studied calmness which I felt tried his nervous power to the utmost:-\\u201cAnd now, Dr. Seward, tell me all about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144682,\n            \"but his nostrils twitched and his eyes blazed as I told how the ruthless hands of the Count had held his wife in that terrible and horrid position, with her mouth to the open wound in his breast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144789,\n            \"I understood him to mean if we were to take advantage of their coming to divert if possible the thoughts of the unhappy husband and wife from each other and from themselves;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145344,\n            \"then Van Helsing said, placing his hand very tenderly on Mrs. Harker\\u2019s head:-\\u201cAnd now, Madam Mina-poor, dear, dear Madam Mina-tell us exactly what happened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145384,\n            \"God knows that I do not want that you be pained;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145491,\n            \"Then she raised her head proudly, and held out one hand to Van Helsing who took it in his, and, after stooping and kissing it reverently, held it fast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146923,\n            \"for Dr. Van Helsing and Dr. Seward are agreed that if we do not eat we cannot work our best.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147094,\n            \"When Dr. Van Helsing and Dr. Seward had come back from seeing poor Renfield, we went gravely into what was to be done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147121,\n            \"First, Dr. Seward told us that when he and Dr. Van Helsing had gone down to the room below they had found Renfield lying on the floor, all in a heap.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147175,\n            \"Dr. Seward asked the attendant who was on duty in the passage if he had heard anything.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147270,\n            \"Van Helsing asked if he had heard \\u201cvoices\\u201dor \\u201ca voice,\\u201dand he said he could not say;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147345,\n            \"Dr. Seward said to us, when we were alone, that he did not wish to go into the matter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147396,\n            \"As it was, he thought that on the attendant\\u2019s evidence he could give a certificate of death by misadventure in falling from bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147586,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing was looking at her fixedly as she spoke, and said, suddenly but quietly:-\\u201cBut dear Madam Mina, are you not afraid;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147672,\n            \"\\u201d he asked gently, whilst we were all very still;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147790,\n            \"\\u201d She looked at him meaningly as she spoke.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147805,\n            \"but now he rose and came close to her and put his hand on her head as he said solemnly: \\u201cMy child, there is such an one if it were for your good.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147842,\n            \"For myself I could hold it in my account with God to find such an euthanasia for you, even at this moment if it were best.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148274,\n            \"As usual Van Helsing had thought ahead of everyone else, and was prepared with an exact ordering of our work.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148296,\n            \"\\u201cIt is perhaps well,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cthat at our meeting after our visit to Carfax we decided not to do anything with the earth-boxes that lay there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            148634,\n            \"\\u201cNay, friend Jonathan,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cin this, the quickest way home is the longest way, so your proverb say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149547,\n            \"\\u201d I could not but see how right he was and the terrible despair of Mina\\u2019s face became relaxed a thought;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            149579,\n            \"Van Helsing went on:-\\u201cWhen once within that house we may find more clues;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150411,\n            \"\\u201cDo you forget,\\u201dhe said, with actually a smile, \\u201cthat last night he banqueted heavily, and will sleep late?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150490,\n            \"Van Helsing had not intended to recall her frightful experience.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150501,\n            \"He had simply lost sight of her and her part in the affair in his intellectual effort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150519,\n            \"When it struck him what he said, he was horrified at his thoughtlessness and tried to comfort her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150539,\n            \"\\u201cOh, Madam Mina,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cdear, dear Madam Mina, alas!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150558,\n            \"that I of all who so reverence you should have said anything so forgetful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150599,\n            \"\\u201d He bent low beside her as he spoke;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150609,\n            \"she took his hand, and looking at him through her tears, said hoarsely:-\\u201cNo, I shall not forget, for it is well that I remember;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150642,\n            \"and with it I have so much in memory of you that is sweet, that I take it all together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150719,\n            \"When it was over, Van Helsing stood up and said:-\\u201cNow, my dear friends, we go forth to our terrible enterprise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150777,\n            \"\\u201d We all assured him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150820,\n            \"But before we go let me see you armed against personal attack.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150833,\n            \"I have myself, since you came down, prepared your chamber by the placing of things of which we know, so that He may not enter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150862,\n            \"Now let me guard yourself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150868,\n            \"On your forehead I touch this piece of Sacred Wafer in the name of the Father, the Son, and--\\u201dThere was a fearful scream which almost froze our hearts to hear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150905,\n            \"As he had placed the Wafer on Mina\\u2019s forehead, it had seared it-had burned into the flesh as though it had been a piece of white-hot metal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151134,\n            \"so gravely that I could not help feeling that he was in some way inspired, and was stating things outside himself:-\\u201cIt may be that you may have to bear that mark till God himself see fit, as He most surely shall, on the Judgment Day, to redress all wrongs of the earth and of His children that He has placed thereon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151259,\n            \"For so surely as we live, that scar shall pass away when God sees right to lift the burden that is hard upon us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151285,\n            \"Till then we bear our Cross, as His Son did in obedience to His Will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151302,\n            \"It may be that we are chosen instruments of His good pleasure, and that we ascend to His bidding as that other through stripes and shame;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151368,\n            \"Mina and I both felt so, and simultaneously we each took one of the old man\\u2019s hands and bent over and kissed it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151674,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing said to us solemnly as we stood before them:-\\u201cAnd now, my friends, we have a duty here to do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151810,\n            \"but we did not somehow seem to mind, for our attention was concentrated on the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151828,\n            \"Taking from his box a piece of the Sacred Wafer he laid it reverently on the earth, and then shutting down the lid began to screw it home, we aiding him as he worked.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151902,\n            \"When we closed the door behind us, the Professor said solemnly:-\\u201cSo much is already done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152088,\n            \"- Just before we reached Fenchurch Street Lord Godalming said to me:-\\u201cQuincey and I will find a locksmith.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152166,\n            \"\\u201d I demurred as to my not sharing any danger even of odium, but he went on: \\u201cBesides, it will attract less attention if there are not too many of us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152287,\n            \"\\u201d said Van Helsing, so we said no more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152298,\n            \"Godalming and Morris hurried off in a cab, we following in another.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152578,\n            \"Lord Godalming smiled, and the man lifted a good-sized bunch of keys;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152657,\n            \"my own cigar burnt furiously, but Van Helsing\\u2019s went cold altogether.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152711,\n            \"This he finally handed to Lord Godalming, who took out his purse and gave him something.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153233,\n            \"When we had examined this last find, Lord Godalming and Quincey Morris taking accurate notes of the various addresses of the houses in the East and the South, took with them the keys in a great bunch, and set out to destroy the boxes in these places.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153318,\n            \"- The time seemed terrible long whilst we were waiting for the coming of Godalming and Quincey Morris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153859,\n            \"The knowledge may help us to defeat him!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153913,\n            \"for had he dared, at the first, to attempt certain things he would long ago have been beyond our power.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153936,\n            \"However, he means to succeed, and a man who has centuries before him can afford to wait and to go slow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154025,\n            \"Do you not see how, of late, this monster has been creeping into knowledge experimentally.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154064,\n            \"for your Vampire, though in all afterwards he can come when and how he will, must at the first make entry only when asked thereto by an inmate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154313,\n            \"I delayed this morning that so we might be sure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154347,\n            \"By my clock it is one hour and already, if all be well, friend Arthur and Quincey are on their way to us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154407,\n            \"\\u201d Whilst he was speaking we were startled by a knock at the hall door, the double postman\\u2019s knock of the telegraph boy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154434,\n            \"We all moved out to the hall with one impulse, and Van Helsing, holding up his hand to us to keep silence, stepped to the door and opened it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154563,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing turned to him quickly and said:-\\u201cGod will act in His own way and time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154853,\n            \"It was just an ordinary knock, such as is given hourly by thousands of gentlemen, but it made the Professor\\u2019s heart and mine beat loudly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155093,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cHe will be here before long now,\\u201dsaid Van Helsing, who had been consulting his pocket-book.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155244,\n            \"Believe me, my friends, we shall not have long to wait now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155293,\n            \"\\u201d He held up a warning hand as he spoke, for we all could hear a key softly inserted in the lock of the hall door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155429,\n            \"Van Helsing, Harker, and I were just behind the door, so that when it was opened the Professor could guard it whilst we two stepped between the incomer and the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156232,\n            \"The first of us to speak was the Professor, as, realising the difficulty of following him through the stable, we moved toward the hall.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156294,\n            \"His very tone betray him, or my ears deceive.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156444,\n            \"Van Helsing and I tried to make inquiry at the back of the house;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157639,\n            \"Van Helsing beckoned to us and we stole out of the room, leaving the two loving hearts alone with their God.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157662,\n            \"Before they retired the Professor fixed up the room against any coming of the Vampire, and assured Mrs. Harker that she might rest in peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157733,\n            \"Van Helsing had placed at hand a bell which either of them was to sound in case of any emergency.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158501,\n            \"She said to me hurriedly:-\\u201cGo, call the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158515,\n            \"I want to see him at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158554,\n            \"He must hypnotise me before the dawn, and then I shall be able to speak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158628,\n            \"\\u201cbut Mina wants to see Dr. Van Helsing at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158641,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI will go,\\u201dhe said, and hurried into the Professor\\u2019s room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158660,\n            \"In two or three minutes later Van Helsing was in the room in his dressing-gown, and Mr. Morris and Lord Godalming were with Dr. Seward at the door asking questions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158696,\n            \"When the Professor saw Mina smile-a positive smile ousted the anxiety of his face;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158713,\n            \"he rubbed his hands as he said:-\\u201cOh, my dear Madam Mina, this is indeed a change.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158847,\n            \"Looking fixedly at her, he commenced to make passes in front of her, from over the top of her head downward, with each hand in turn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159000,\n            \"Raising his hand to impose silence, the Professor motioned to me to bring the others in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159050,\n            \"The stillness was broken by Van Helsing\\u2019s voice speaking in a low level tone which would not break the current of her thoughts:-\\u201cWhere are you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159592,\n            \"\\u201d Mr. Morris and Lord Godalming started for the door but the Professor\\u2019s calm voice called them back:-\\u201cStay, my friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159776,\n            \"Hear me, ESCAPE!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159877,\n            \"I, too, am wily and I think his mind in a little while.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159994,\n            \"\\u201d Mina looked at him appealingly as she asked:-\\u201cBut why need we seek him further, when he is gone away from us?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160022,\n            \"\\u201d He took her hand and patted it as he replied:-\\u201cAsk me nothings as yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160042,\n            \"When we have breakfast, then I answer all questions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160053,\n            \"\\u201d He would say no more, and we separated to dress.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160073,\n            \"He looked at her gravely for a minute and then said sorrowfully:-\\u201cBecause my dear, dear Madam Mina, now more than ever must we find him even if we have to follow him to the jaws of Hell!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160130,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBecause,\\u201dhe answered solemnly, \\u201che can live for centuries, and you are but mortal woman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160216,\n            \"We shall go to make our search-if I can call it so, for it is not search but knowing, and we seek confirmation only.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160275,\n            \"Let me tell you that so you will know what we four know already, for I have tell them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160420,\n            \"When that fail he make straight for his last resource-his last earth-work I might say did I wish double entente.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160680,\n            \"- When I read to Mina, Van Helsing\\u2019s message in the phonograph, the poor girl brightened up considerably.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160726,\n            \"For my own part, now that his horrible danger is not face to face with us, it seems almost impossible to believe in it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160788,\n            \"In the midst of my thought my eye fell on the red scar on my poor darling\\u2019s white forehead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160833,\n            \"Mina and I fear to be idle, so we have been over all the diaries again and again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160901,\n            \"I shall try to think as she does.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160922,\n            \"It is better to wait till we see the Professor and the others after their investigations.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160986,\n            \"Present: Professor Van Helsing, Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, Mr. Quincey Morris, Jonathan Harker, Mina Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162477,\n            \"\\u201d When Dr. Van Helsing had done speaking, I asked him if he were certain that the Count had remained on board the ship.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162504,\n            \"He replied: \\u201cWe have the best proof of that: your own evidence, when in the hypnotic trance this morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162528,\n            \"\\u201d I asked him again if it were really necessary that they should pursue the Count, for oh!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162577,\n            \"As he went on, however, he grew more angry and more forceful, till in the end we could not but see wherein was at least some of that personal dominance which made him so long a master amongst men:-\\u201cYes, it is necessary-necessary-necessary!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162689,\n            \"All this have I told these others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162722,\n            \"I have told them how the measure of leaving his own barren land-barren of peoples-and coming to a new land where life of man teems till they are like the multitude of standing corn, was the work of centuries.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163035,\n            \"He have infect you-oh, forgive me, my dear, that I must say such;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163054,\n            \"but it is for good of you that I speak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163225,\n            \"\\u201d He paused and I said:-\\u201cBut will not the Count take his rebuff wisely?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163275,\n            \"\\u201d he said, \\u201cyour simile of the tiger good, for me, and I shall adopt him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164270,\n            \"I have mentioned this to Van Helsing, and he and I are to talk it over when we are alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164311,\n            \"The Count had his own purposes when he gave her what Van Helsing called \\u201cthe Vampire\\u2019s baptism of blood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164435,\n            \"Van Helsing is coming to my study a little before the others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164448,\n            \"I shall try to open the subject with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164475,\n            \"I could see that he had something on his mind which he wanted to say, but felt some hesitancy about broaching the subject.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164551,\n            \"then he stopped, so I waited;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164559,\n            \"he went on:-\\u201cMadam Mina, our poor, dear Madam Mina is changing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164592,\n            \"Van Helsing continued:-\\u201cWith the sad experience of Miss Lucy, we must this time be warned before things go too far.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164812,\n            \"he went on:-\\u201cThen, what we must do is to prevent this;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165005,\n            \"Van Helsing has gone away to prepare for the meeting, and his painful part of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165038,\n            \"- At the very outset of our meeting a great personal relief was experienced by both Van Helsing and myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165194,\n            \"Van Helsing roughly put the facts before us first:-\\u201cThe Czarina Catherine left the Thames yesterday morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165654,\n            \"\\u201d I thought that now was the time for Van Helsing to warn him not to disclose our plans to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166073,\n            \"You can ask Dr. Van Helsing if I am not right;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166381,\n            \"Mina woke me early, about the same time as yesterday, and asked me to bring Dr. Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166403,\n            \"I thought that it was another occasion for hypnotism, and without question went for the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166421,\n            \"He had evidently expected some such call, for I found him dressed in his room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166438,\n            \"His door was ajar, so that he could hear the opening of the door of our room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166462,\n            \"as he passed into the room, he asked Mina if the others might come, too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166496,\n            \"You can tell them just as well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166504,\n            \"I must go with you on your journey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166513,\n            \"\\u201d Dr. Van Helsing was as startled as I was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166539,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYou must take me with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166548,\n            \"I am safer with you, and you shall be safer, too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166643,\n            \"I can tell you now, whilst the sun is coming up;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166822,\n            \"\\u201d Dr. Van Helsing said very gravely:-\\u201cMadam Mina, you are, as always, most wise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166864,\n            \"\\u201d When he had spoken, Mina\\u2019s long spell of silence made me look at her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166914,\n            \"Van Helsing motioned to me to come with him quietly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166925,\n            \"We went to his room, and within a minute Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, and Mr. Morris were with us also.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166951,\n            \"He told them what Mina had said, and went on:-\\u201cIn the morning we shall leave for Varna.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167062,\n            \"The Professor paused before replying:-\\u201cWe shall at the first board that ship;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167722,\n            \"I think that none of us were surprised when we were asked to see Mrs. Harker a little before the time of sunset.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167747,\n            \"We have of late come to understand that sunrise and sunset are to her times of peculiar freedom;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167878,\n            \"To-night, when we met, she was somewhat constrained, and bore all the signs of an internal struggle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167901,\n            \"I put it down myself to her making a violent effort at the earliest instant she could do so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167935,\n            \"then, motioning her husband to sit beside her on the sofa where she was half reclining, she made the rest of us bring chairs up close.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167964,\n            \"Taking her husband\\u2019s hand in hers began:-\\u201cWe are all here together in freedom, for perhaps the last time!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167990,\n            \"I know, dear;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167995,\n            \"I know that you will always be with me to the end.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168052,\n            \"You are going to be so good to me as to take me with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168879,\n            \"\\u201d said Lord Godalming, each of them in turn kneeling to her to take the oath.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169964,\n            \"and it has become a habit for Van Helsing to hypnotise her at such times.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170018,\n            \"He seems to have power at these particular moments to simply will, and her thoughts obey him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170037,\n            \"He always asks her what she can see and hear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170276,\n            \"Van Helsing says that our chance will be to get on the boat between sunrise and sunset.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170720,\n            \"If the Count is there, Van Helsing and Seward will cut off his head at once and drive a stake through his heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171020,\n            \"but Van Helsing says I must.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171157,\n            \"The lethargy grows upon her, and though she seems strong and well, and is getting back some of her colour, Van Helsing and I are not satisfied.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171233,\n            \"Van Helsing examines, he tells me, her teeth very carefully, whilst she is in the hypnotic condition, for he says that so long as they do not begin to sharpen there is no active danger of a change in her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171545,\n            \"Van Helsing and I were a little alarmed about Mrs. Harker to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171930,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing is terribly anxious, and told me just now that he fears the Count is escaping us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172250,\n            \"Van Helsing raised his hand over his head for a moment, as though in remonstrance with the Almighty;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172426,\n            \"\\u201d said Van Helsing to us generally.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172470,\n            \"\\u201cYou forget-or perhaps you do not know, though Jonathan does and so does Dr. Van Helsing-that I am the train fiend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172631,\n            \"This land is very different from yours or mine;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172950,\n            \"When the three men had gone out to their tasks Van Helsing asked Mrs. Harker to look up the copy of the diaries and find him the part of Harker\\u2019s journal at the Castle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172995,\n            \"when the door was shut upon her he said to me:-\\u201cWe mean the same!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173044,\n            \"Do you know why I asked her to get the manuscript?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173124,\n            \"In the moment when Madam Mina said those words that arrest both our understanding, an inspiration came to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173145,\n            \"In the trance of three days ago the Count sent her his spirit to read her mind;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173163,\n            \"or more like he took her to see him in his earth-box in the ship with water rushing, just as it go free at rise and set of sun.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173196,\n            \"He learn then that we are here;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173204,\n            \"for she have more to tell in her open life with eyes to see and ears to hear than he, shut, as he is, in his coffin-box.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173237,\n            \"Now he make his most effort to escape us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173247,\n            \"At present he want her not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173254,\n            \"\\u201cHe is sure with his so great knowledge that she will come at his call;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173271,\n            \"but he cut her off-take her, as he can do, out of his own power, that so she come not to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173301,\n            \"there I have hope that our man-brains that have been of man so long and that have not lost the grace of God, will come higher than his child-brain that lie in his tomb for centuries, that grow not yet to our stature, and that do only work selfish and therefore small.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173400,\n            \"when most we want all her great brain which is trained like man\\u2019s brain, but is of sweet woman and have a special power which the Count give her, and which he may not take away altogether-though he think not so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173591,\n            \"Then holding the pages between his finger and thumb he said:-\\u201cFriend John, to you with so much of experience already-and you, too, dear Madam Mina, that are young-here is a lesson: do not fear ever to think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173642,\n            \"A half-thought has been buzzing often in my brain, but I fear to let him loose his wings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173664,\n            \"Here now, with more knowledge, I go back to where that half-thought come from and I find that he be no half-thought at all;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173762,\n            \"See I read here what Jonathan have written:-\\u201cThat other of his race who, in a later age, again and again, brought his forces over The Great River into Turkey Land;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174306,\n            \"Oh, my dear, I see that your eyes are opened, and that to you the lightning flash show all the leagues,\\u201dfor Mrs. Harker began to clap her hands and her eyes sparkled.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174346,\n            \"He went on:-\\u201cNow you shall speak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174373,\n            \"\\u201d He took her hand and held it whilst she spoke.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174385,\n            \"His finger and thumb closed on her pulse, as I thought instinctively and unconsciously, as she spoke:-\\u201cThe Count is a criminal and of criminal type.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174417,\n            \"Nordau and Lombroso would so classify him, and qu\\u00e2 criminal he is of imperfectly formed mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174448,\n            \"His past is a clue, and the one page of it that we know-and that from his own lips-tells that once before, when in what Mr. Morris would call a \\u2018 tight place,\\u2019he went back to his own country from the land he had tried to invade, and thence, without losing purpose, prepared himself for a new effort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174599,\n            \"\\u201d said Van Helsing, enthusiastically, as he stooped and kissed her hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174614,\n            \"A moment later he said to me, as calmly as though we had been having a sick-room consultation:-\\u201cSeventy-two only;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174653,\n            \"\\u201d Turning to her again, he said with keen expectation:-\\u201cBut go on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174692,\n            \"I do in any case, and shall tell you if you are right.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174818,\n            \"So his own selfishness frees my soul somewhat from the terrible power which he acquired over me on that dreadful night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174871,\n            \"and all that haunts me is a fear lest in some trance or dream he may have used my knowledge for his ends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174895,\n            \"\\u201d The Professor stood up:-\\u201cHe has so used your mind;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174910,\n            \"and by it he has left us here in Varna, whilst the ship that carried him rushed through enveloping fog up to Galatz, where, doubtless, he had made preparation for escaping from us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174958,\n            \"and it may be that, as ever is in God\\u2019s Providence, the very thing that the evil-doer most reckoned on for his selfish good, turns out to be his chiefest harm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175012,\n            \"For now that he think he is free from every trace of us all, and that he has escaped us with so many hours to him, then his selfish child-brain will whisper him to sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175052,\n            \"He think, too, that as he cut himself off from knowing your mind, there can be no knowledge of him to you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175084,\n            \"That terrible baptism of blood which he give you makes you free to go to him in spirit, as you have as yet done in your times of freedom, when the sun rise and set.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175122,\n            \"At such times you go by my volition and not by his;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175135,\n            \"and this power to good of you and others, as you have won from your suffering at his hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175156,\n            \"This is now all the more precious that he know it not, and to guard himself have even cut himself off from his knowledge of our where.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175256,\n            \"You must be scribe and write him all down, so that when the others return from their work you can give it to them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175419,\n            \"and after a longer and more serious effort on the part of Van Helsing than has been usually necessary, she sank into the trance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175452,\n            \"but this time the Professor had to ask her questions, and to ask them pretty resolutely, before we could learn anything;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175621,\n            \"Van Helsing and I looked at each other with understanding.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175741,\n            \"when she had gone Van Helsing said:-\\u201cYou see, my friends.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176703,\n            \"She opened her eyes, and we all started as she said, sweetly and seemingly with the utmost unconcern:-\\u201cOh, Professor, why ask me to do what you know I can\\u2019t?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176815,\n            \"\\u2019 It seemed so funny to hear you order me about, as if I were a bad child!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            177483,\n            \"\\u201d This mixture of simplicity and cunning, of superstition and commercial reasoning, aroused Van Helsing, who said:-\\u201cMine friend, that Devil is more clever than he is thought by some;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178812,\n            \"I have asked Dr. Van Helsing, and he has got me all the papers that I have not yet seen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178859,\n            \"I shall try to follow the Professor\\u2019s example, and think without prejudice on the facts before me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180786,\n            \"she will be my care, if I may.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180849,\n            \"And I can die, if need be, as well as younger men.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180864,\n            \"Now let me say that what I would is this: while you, my Lord Godalming and friend Jonathan go in your so swift little steamboat up the river, and whilst John and Quincey guard the bank where perchance he might be landed, I will take Madam Mina right into the heart of the enemy\\u2019s country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181060,\n            \"\\u201d Here Jonathan interrupted him hotly:-\\u201cDo you mean to say, Professor Van Helsing, that you would bring Mina, in her sad case and tainted as she is with that devil\\u2019s illness, right into the jaws of his death-trap?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181248,\n            \"The Professor\\u2019s voice, as he spoke in clear, sweet tones, which seemed to vibrate in the air, calmed us all:-\\u201cOh, my friend, it is because I would save Madam Mina from that awful place that I would go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181299,\n            \"God forbid that I should take her into that place.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181363,\n            \"If the Count escape us this time-and he is strong and subtle and cunning-he may choose to sleep him for a century, and then in time our dear one \\\"-he took my hand-\\\" would come to him to keep him company, and would be as those others that you, Jonathan, saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181524,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo as you will,\\u201dsaid Jonathan, with a sob that shook him all over, \\u201cwe are in the hands of God!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181765,\n            \"Professor Van Helsing and I are to leave by the 11: 40 train to-night for Veresti, where we are to get a carriage to drive to the Borgo Pass.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181837,\n            \"The Professor knows something of a great many languages, so we shall get on all right.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181903,\n            \"Dear Dr. Van Helsing comforts me by telling me that I am fully armed as there may be wolves;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181972,\n            \"the Professor is looking at you keenly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182982,\n            \"I wonder where Mina is now, and Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183487,\n            \"The Professor tells me that this morning at dawn he could hardly hypnotise me at all, and that all I could say was: \\u201cdark and quiet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183528,\n            \"He says that he will later on try to buy additional horses, so that we may be able to change them on the way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183591,\n            \"If Jonathan and I were driving through it alone what a pleasure it would be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183703,\n            \"The Professor encourages her, and whispers to me that it may be a week before we can get any good food again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183975,\n            \"he tells the farmers that he is hurrying to Bistritz, and pays them well to make the exchange of horses.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184187,\n            \"all day he would not take any rest, though he made me sleep for a long spell.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184206,\n            \"At sunset time he hypnotised me, and he says that I answered as usual \\u201cdarkness, lapping water and creaking wood \\\";\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184279,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing is sleeping, Poor dear, he looks very tired and old and grey, but his mouth is set as firmly as a conqueror\\u2019s;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184321,\n            \"When we have well started I must make him rest whilst I drive.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184444,\n            \"At dawn Van Helsing hypnotised me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184451,\n            \"he says I answered \\u201cdarkness, creaking wood and roaring water,\\u201dso the river is changing as they ascend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184582,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing says that by morning we shall reach the Borgo Pass.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184597,\n            \"The houses are very few here now, and the Professor says that the last horse we got will have to go on with us, as we may not be able to change.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184632,\n            \"He got two in addition to the two we changed, so that now we have a rude four-in-hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186164,\n            \"- Let me be accurate in everything, for though you and I have seen some strange things together, you may at the first think that I, Van Helsing, am mad-that the many horrors and the so long strain on nerves has at the last turn my brain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187560,\n            \"\\u201d In fear I turned to my poor Madam Mina, and my heart with gladness leapt like flame;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187620,\n            \"I seized some of the firewood which was by me, and holding out some of the Wafer, advanced on them towards the fire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187646,\n            \"They drew back before me, and laughed their low horrid laugh.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187659,\n            \"I fed the fire, and feared them not;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187669,\n            \"for I knew that we were safe within our protections.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187680,\n            \"They could not approach, me, whilst so armed, nor Madam Mina whilst she remained within the ring, which she could not leave no more than they could enter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187739,\n            \"I knew that there was for the poor beasts no more of terror.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187833,\n            \"Instinctively, with the dawn coming, I turned to Madam Mina, intending to hypnotise her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187851,\n            \"but she lay in a deep and sudden sleep, from which I could not wake her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187869,\n            \"I tried to hypnotise through her sleep, but she made no response, none at all;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187935,\n            \"for there may be places where I must go, where that sunlight, though snow and mist obscure it, will be to me a safety.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187963,\n            \"I will strengthen me with breakfast, and then I will to my terrible work.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188048,\n            \"I fear to think of her, off on the wolds near that horrid place.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188116,\n            \"If I write no more Good-bye, Mina!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188303,\n            \"Thank God for that mercy at all events, though the proving it has been dreadful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188339,\n            \"The blacksmith hammer which I took in the carriage from Veresti was useful;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188462,\n            \"Then I bethought me of my dear Madam Mina, and I was in terrible plight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188487,\n            \"Her, I had not dare to take into this place, but left safe from the Vampire in that Holy circle;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188519,\n            \"I resolve me that my work lay here, and that as to the wolves we must submit, if it were God\\u2019s will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188557,\n            \"So did I choose for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188564,\n            \"Had it but been for myself the choice had been easy, the maw of the wolf were better to rest in than the grave of the Vampire!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188636,\n            \"She lay in her Vampire sleep, so full of life and voluptuous beauty that I shudder as though I have come to do murder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188662,\n            \"Ah, I doubt not that in old time, when such things were, many a man who set forth to do such a task as mine, found at the last his heart fail him, and then his nerve.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188806,\n            \"There is some fascination, surely, when I am moved by the mere presence of such an one, even lying as she lay in a tomb fretted with age and heavy with the dust of centuries, though there be that horrid odour such as the lairs of the Count have had.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188984,\n            \"For it was the voice of my dear Madam Mina that I heard.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188998,\n            \"Then I braced myself again to my horrid task, and found by wrenching away tomb-tops one other of the sisters, the other dark one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189027,\n            \"I dared not pause to look on her as I had on her sister, lest once more I should begin to be enthrall;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189052,\n            \"but I go on searching until, presently, I find in a high great tomb as if made to one much beloved that other fair sister which, like Jonathan I had seen to gather herself out of the atoms of the mist.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189097,\n            \"She was so fair to look on, so radiantly beautiful, so exquisitely voluptuous, that the very instinct of man in me, which calls some of my sex to love and to protect one of hers, made my head whirl with new emotion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189145,\n            \"But God be thanked, that soul-wail of my dear Madam Mina had not died out of my ears;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189208,\n            \"and as there had been only three of these Un-Dead phantoms around us in the night, I took it that there were no more of active Un-Dead existent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189303,\n            \"Before I began to restore these women to their dead selves through my awful work, I laid in Dracula\\u2019s tomb some of the Wafer, and so banished him from it, Un-Dead, for ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189453,\n            \"had I not been nerved by thoughts of other dead, and of the living over whom hung such a pall of fear, I could not have gone on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189593,\n            \"And the poor souls, I can pity them now and weep, as I think of them placid each in her full sleep of death for a short moment ere fading.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189683,\n            \"\\u201d Before I left the castle I so fixed its entrances that never more can the Count enter there Un-Dead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189706,\n            \"When I stepped into the circle where Madam Mina slept, she woke from her sleep, and, seeing, me, cried out in pain that I had endured too much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189792,\n            \"I was glad to see her paleness and her illness, for my mind was full of the fresh horror of that ruddy vampire sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189818,\n            \"And so with trust and hope, and yet full of fear, we go eastward to meet our friends-and him-whom Madam Mina tell me that she know are coming to meet us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189865,\n            \"- It was late in the afternoon when the Professor and I took our way towards the east whence I knew Jonathan was coming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189973,\n            \"When we had gone about a mile, I was tired with the heavy walking and sat down to rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190120,\n            \"I knew from the way Dr. Van Helsing was searching about that he was trying to seek some strategic point, where we would be less exposed in case of attack.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190253,\n            \"\\u201d He brought in our furs, and made a snug nest for me, and got out some provisions and forced them upon me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190479,\n            \"Straight in front of us and not far off-in fact, so near that I wondered we had not noticed before-came a group of mounted men hurrying along.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190549,\n            \"Outlined against the snow as they were, I could see from the men\\u2019s clothes that they were peasants or gypsies of some kind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191601,\n            \"At the same moment Dr. Van Helsing and I rose behind the rock and pointed our weapons at them.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 6]\": [\n        [\n            85,\n            \"I feared to go very far from the station, as we had arrived late and would start as near the correct time as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111,\n            \"The impression I had was that we were leaving the West and entering the East;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            215,\n            \") I asked the waiter, and he said it was called \\u201cpaprika hendl,\\u201dand that, as it was a national dish, I should be able to get it anywhere along the Carpathians.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            340,\n            \"I find that the district he named is in the extreme east of the country, just on the borders of three states, Transylvania, Moldavia and Bukovina, in the midst of the Carpathian mountains;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            389,\n            \"I was not able to light on any map or work giving the exact locality of the Castle Dracula, as there are no maps of this country as yet to compare with our own Ordnance Survey maps;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            450,\n            \"I shall enter here some of my notes, as they may refresh my memory when I talk over my travels with Mina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            518,\n            \"I am going among the latter, who claim to be descended from Attila and the Huns.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            603,\n            \", I must ask the Count all about them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            709,\n            \"I had for breakfast more paprika, and a sort of porridge of maize flour which they said was \\u201cmamaliga,\\u201dand egg-plant stuffed with forcemeat, a very excellent dish, which they call \\u201cimpletata.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            762,\n            \") I had to hurry breakfast, for the train started a little before eight, or rather it ought to have done so, for after rushing to the station at 7: 30 I had to sit in the carriage for more than an hour before we began to move.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            815,\n            \"It seems to me that the further east you go the more unpunctual are the trains.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            946,\n            \"Some of them were just like the peasants at home or those I saw coming through France and Germany, with short jackets and round hats and home-made trousers;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1155,\n            \"They are, however, I am told, very harmless and rather wanting in natural self-assertion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1377,\n            \"When I came close she bowed and said, \\u201cThe Herr Englishman?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1429,\n            \"He went, but immediately returned with a letter:-\\u201cMy Friend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1535,\n            \"- I found that my landlord had got a letter from the Count, directing him to secure the best place on the coach for me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1562,\n            \"but on making inquiries as to details he seemed somewhat reticent, and pretended that he could not understand my German.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1600,\n            \"at least, he answered my questions exactly as if he did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1657,\n            \"When I asked him if he knew Count Dracula, and could tell me anything of his castle, both he and his wife crossed themselves, and, saying that they knew nothing at all, simply refused to speak further.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1700,\n            \"It was so near the time of starting that I had no time to ask any one else, for it was all very mysterious and not by any means comforting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1732,\n            \"Just before I was leaving, the old lady came up to my room and said in a very hysterical way: \\u201cMust you go?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1768,\n            \"\\u201d She was in such an excited state that she seemed to have lost her grip of what German she knew, and mixed it all up with some other language which I did not know at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1807,\n            \"I was just able to follow her by asking many questions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1819,\n            \"When I told her that I must go at once, and that I was engaged on important business, she asked again: \\u201cDo you know what day it is?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1881,\n            \"I know that, but do you know what day it is?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1894,\n            \"\\u201d On my saying that I did not understand, she went on: \\u201cIt is the eve of St.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1963,\n            \"\\u201d She was in such evident distress that I tried to comfort her, but without effect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1981,\n            \"Finally she went down on her knees and implored me not to go;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2037,\n            \"I therefore tried to raise her up, and said, as gravely as I could, that I thanked her, but my duty was imperative, and that I must go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2071,\n            \"She then rose and dried her eyes, and taking a crucifix from her neck offered it to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2091,\n            \"I did not know what to do, for, as an English Churchman, I have been taught to regard such things as in some measure idolatrous, and yet it seemed so ungracious to refuse an old lady meaning so well and in such a state of mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2142,\n            \"She saw, I suppose, the doubt in my face, for she put the rosary round my neck, and said, \\u201cFor your mother\\u2019s sake,\\u201dand went out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2216,\n            \"Whether it is the old lady\\u2019s fear, or the many ghostly traditions of this place, or the crucifix itself, I do not know, but I am not feeling nearly as easy in my mind as usual.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2259,\n            \"If this book should ever reach Mina before I do, let it bring my good-bye.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2479,\n            \"When I got on the coach the driver had not taken his seat, and I saw him talking with the landlady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2502,\n            \"They were evidently talking of me, for every now and then they looked at me, and some of the people who were sitting on the bench outside the door-which they call by a name meaning \\u201cword-bearer \\\"-came and listened, and then looked at me, most of them pityingly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2562,\n            \"I could hear a lot of words often repeated, queer words, for there were many nationalities in the crowd;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2584,\n            \"so I quietly got my polyglot dictionary from my bag and looked them out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2599,\n            \"I must say they were not cheering to me, for amongst them were \\u201cOrdog \\\"-Satan, \\u201cpokol \\\"-hell, \\u201cstregoica \\\"-witch, \\u201cvrolok\\u201dand \\u201cvlkoslak \\\"-both of which mean the same thing, one being Slovak and the other Servian for something that is either were-wolf or vampire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2668,\n            \", I must ask the Count about these superstitions) When we started, the crowd round the inn door, which had by this time swelled to a considerable size, all made the sign of the cross and pointed two fingers towards me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2714,\n            \"With some difficulty I got a fellow-passenger to tell me what they meant;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2730,\n            \"he would not answer at first, but on learning that I was English, he explained that it was a charm or guard against the evil eye.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2779,\n            \"but every one seemed so kind-hearted, and so sorrowful, and so sympathetic that I could not but be touched.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2803,\n            \"I shall never forget the last glimpse which I had of the inn-yard and its crowd of picturesque figures, all crossing themselves, as they stood round the wide archway, with its background of rich foliage of oleander and orange trees in green tubs clustered in the centre of the yard.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2906,\n            \"I soon lost sight and recollection of ghostly fears in the beauty of the scene as we drove along, although had I known the language, or rather languages, which my fellow-passengers were speaking, I might not have been able to throw them off so easily.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3013,\n            \"and as we drove by I could see the green grass under the trees spangled with the fallen petals.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3107,\n            \"I could not understand then what the haste meant, but the driver was evidently bent on losing no time in reaching Borgo Prund.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3360,\n            \"One of my companions touched my arm as we swept round the base of a hill and opened up the lofty, snow-covered peak of a mountain, which seemed, as we wound on our serpentine way, to be right before us:-\\u201cLook!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3487,\n            \"Here and there we passed Cszeks and Slovaks, all in picturesque attire, but I noticed that goitre was painfully prevalent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3875,\n            \"I wished to get down and walk up them, as we do at home, but the driver would not hear of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            3923,\n            \"and then he added, with what he evidently meant for grim pleasantry-for he looked round to catch the approving smile of the rest-\\\" and you may have enough of such matters before you go to sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4040,\n            \"Then through the darkness I could see a sort of patch of grey light ahead of us, as though there were a cleft in the hills.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4143,\n            \"One by one several of the passengers offered me gifts, which they pressed upon me with an earnestness which would take no denial;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4261,\n            \"It was evident that something very exciting was either happening or expected, but though I asked each passenger, no one would give me the slightest explanation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4448,\n            \"The passengers drew back with a sigh of gladness, which seemed to mock my own disappointment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4466,\n            \"I was already thinking what I had best do, when the driver, looking at his watch, said to the others something which I could hardly hear, it was spoken so quietly and in so low a tone;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4520,\n            \"\\u201d Then turning to me, he said in German worse than my own:-\\u201cThere is no carriage here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4639,\n            \"I could see from the flash of our lamps, as the rays fell on them, that the horses were coal-black and splendid animals.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4695,\n            \"I could only see the gleam of a pair of very bright eyes, which seemed red in the lamplight, as he turned to us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4936,\n            \"Then I descended from the side of the coach, as the cal\\u00e8che was close alongside, the driver helping me with a hand which caught my arm in a grip of steel;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4999,\n            \"As I looked back I saw the steam from the horses of the coach by the light of the lamps, and projected against it the figures of my late companions crossing themselves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5075,\n            \"but a cloak was thrown over my shoulders, and a rug across my knees, and the driver said in excellent German:-\\u201cThe night is chill, mein Herr, and my master the Count bade me take all care of you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5223,\n            \"It seemed to me that we were simply going over and over the same ground again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5257,\n            \"I would have liked to have asked the driver what this all meant, but I really feared to do so, for I thought that, placed as I was, any protest would have had no effect in case there had been an intention to delay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5503,\n            \"Then, far off in the distance, from the mountains on each side of us began a louder and a sharper howling-that of wolves-which affected both the horses and myself in the same way-for I was minded to jump from the cal\\u00e8che and run, whilst they reared again and plunged madly, so that the driver had to use all his great strength to keep them from bolting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5580,\n            \"In a few minutes, however, my own ears got accustomed to the sound, and the horses so far became quiet that the driver was able to descend and to stand before them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5616,\n            \"He petted and soothed them, and whispered something in their ears, as I have heard of horse-tamers doing, and with extraordinary effect, for under his caresses they became quite manageable again, though they still trembled.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5875,\n            \"he kept turning his head to left and right, but I could not see anything through the darkness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5895,\n            \"Suddenly, away on our left, I saw a faint flickering blue flame.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5938,\n            \"I did not know what to do, the less as the howling of the wolves grew closer;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5957,\n            \"but while I wondered the driver suddenly appeared again, and without a word took his seat, and we resumed our journey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6017,\n            \"Once the flame appeared so near the road, that even in the darkness around us I could watch the driver\\u2019s motions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6085,\n            \"Once there appeared a strange optical effect: when he stood between me and the flame he did not obstruct it, for I could see its ghostly flicker all the same.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6219,\n            \"I could not see any cause for it, for the howling of the wolves had ceased altogether;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6238,\n            \"but just then the moon, sailing through the black clouds, appeared behind the jagged crest of a beetling, pine-clad rock, and by its light I saw around us a ring of wolves, with white teeth and lolling red tongues, with long, sinewy limbs and shaggy hair.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6411,\n            \"I called to the coachman to come, for it seemed to me that our only chance was to try to break out through the ring and to aid his approach.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6443,\n            \"I shouted and beat the side of the cal\\u00e8che, hoping by the noise to scare the wolves from that side, so as to give him a chance of reaching the trap.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6477,\n            \"How he came there, I know not, but I heard his voice raised in a tone of imperious command, and looking towards the sound, saw him stand in the roadway.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6557,\n            \"When I could see again the driver was climbing into the cal\\u00e8che, and the wolves had disappeared.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6644,\n            \"Suddenly, I became conscious of the fact that the driver was in the act of pulling up the horses in the courtyard of a vast ruined castle, from whose tall black windows came no ray of light, and whose broken battlements showed a jagged line against the moonlit sky.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6780,\n            \"When the cal\\u00e8che stopped, the driver jumped down and held out his hand to assist me to alight.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6800,\n            \"Again I could not but notice his prodigious strength.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6810,\n            \"His hand actually seemed like a steel vice that could have crushed mine if he had chosen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6828,\n            \"Then he took out my traps, and placed them on the ground beside me as I stood close to a great door, old and studded with large iron nails, and set in a projecting doorway of massive stone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6898,\n            \"As I stood, the driver jumped again into his seat and shook the reins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            6992,\n            \"What sort of place had I come to, and among what kind of people?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7076,\n            \"and I am now a full-blown solicitor!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7169,\n            \"I was indeed awake and among the Carpathians.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7409,\n            \"The instant, however, that I had stepped over the threshold, he moved impulsively forward, and holding out his hand grasped mine with a strength which made me wince, an effect which was not lessened by the fact that it seemed as cold as ice-more like the hand of a dead than a living man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7678,\n            \"\\u201d He insisted on carrying my traps along the passage, and then up a great winding stair, and along another great passage, on whose stone floor our steps rang heavily.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7762,\n            \"The Count halted, putting down my bags, closed the door, and crossing the room, opened another door, which led into a small octagonal room lit by a single lamp, and seemingly without a window of any sort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7806,\n            \"Passing through this, he opened another door, and motioned me to enter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7866,\n            \"The Count himself left my luggage inside and withdrew, saying, before he closed the door:-\\u201cYou will need, after your journey, to refresh yourself by making your toilet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7930,\n            \"\\u201d The light and warmth and the Count\\u2019s courteous welcome seemed to have dissipated all my doubts and fears.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8788,\n            \"\\u201d Seeing, I suppose, some expression in my face strange to him, he added:-\\u201cAh, sir, you dwellers in the city cannot enter into the feelings of the hunter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            8826,\n            \"\\u201d Then he rose and said:-\\u201cBut you must be tired.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94417,\n            \"Do not answer this, as I shall take it that, if I do not hear, you will come to breakfast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94441,\n            \"\\u201cBelieve me, \\u201cYour faithful and grateful friend, \\u201cMina Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102745,\n            \"Take the papers that are with this, the diaries of Harker and the rest, and read them, and then find this great Un-Dead, and cut off his head and burn his heart or drive a stake through it, so that the world may rest from him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110673,\n            \"and I was beginning to feel uneasy, lest I might miss my guest, when a sweet-faced, dainty-looking girl stepped up to me, and, after a quick glance, said: \\u201cDr. Seward, is it not?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110743,\n            \"\\u201cI knew you from the description of poor dear Lucy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110771,\n            \"The blush that rose to my own cheeks somehow set us both at ease, for it was a tacit answer to her own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110796,\n            \"I got her luggage, which included a typewriter, and we took the Underground to Fenchurch Street, after I had sent a wire to my housekeeper to have a sitting-room and bedroom prepared at once for Mrs. Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110846,\n            \"She knew, of course, that the place was a lunatic asylum, but I could see that she was unable to repress a shudder when we entered.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110876,\n            \"She told me that, if she might, she would come presently to my study, as she had much to say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110900,\n            \"So here I am finishing my entry in my phonograph diary whilst I await her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110943,\n            \"I must get her interested in something, so that I may have an opportunity of reading them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110962,\n            \"She does not know how precious time is, or what a task we have in hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110980,\n            \"I must be careful not to frighten her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111578,\n            \"\\u201d By this time my mind was made up that the diary of a doctor who attended Lucy might have something to add to the sum of our knowledge of that terrible Being, and I said boldly:-\\u201cThen, Dr. Seward, you had better let me copy it out for you on my typewriter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112421,\n            \"because in the struggle which we have before us to rid the earth of this terrible monster we must have all the knowledge and all the help which we can get.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113508,\n            \"If this journal be true-and judging by one\\u2019s own wonderful experiences, it must be-he is also a man of great nerve.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113553,\n            \"After reading his account of it I was prepared to meet a good specimen of manhood, but hardly the quiet, business-like gentleman who came here to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113588,\n            \"- After lunch Harker and his wife went back to their own room, and as I passed a while ago I heard the click of the typewriter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113623,\n            \"Mrs. Harker says that they are knitting together in chronological order every scrap of evidence they have.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113666,\n            \"He is now reading his wife\\u2019s typescript of my diary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113747,\n            \"Oh, if we had only had them earlier we might have saved poor Lucy!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113782,\n            \"He says that by dinner-time they will be able to show a whole connected narrative.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113800,\n            \"He thinks that in the meantime I should see Renfield, as hitherto he has been a sort of index to the coming and going of the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113847,\n            \"What a good thing that Mrs. Harker put my cylinders into type!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113964,\n            \"I believe that, had I not had the chat with Harker and read the letters and the dates of his outbursts, I should have been prepared to sign for him after a brief time of observation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114721,\n            \"- The station-master was good enough to give me a line to his old companion the station-master at King\\u2019s Cross, so that when I arrived there in the morning I was able to ask him about the arrival of the boxes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115495,\n            \"To read Dr. Seward\\u2019s account of poor Lucy\\u2019s death, and what followed, is enough to dry up the springs of pity in one\\u2019s heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117056,\n            \"- I got home at five o\\u2019clock, and found that Godalming and Morris had not only arrived, but had already studied the transcript of the various diaries and letters which Harker and his wonderful wife had made and arranged.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117100,\n            \"Harker had not yet returned from his visit to the carriers\\u2019 men, of whom Dr. Hennessey had written to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117124,\n            \"Mrs. Harker gave us a cup of tea, and I can honestly say that, for the first time since I have lived in it, this old house seemed like home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117159,\n            \"When we had finished, Mrs. Harker said:-\\u201cDr. Seward, may I ask a favour?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117181,\n            \"I want to see your patient, Mr. Renfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117192,\n            \"Do let me see him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117198,\n            \"What you have said of him in your diary interests me so much!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117212,\n            \"\\u201d She looked so appealing and so pretty that I could not refuse her, and there was no possible reason why I should;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117237,\n            \"so I took her with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117711,\n            \"\\u201d I thought that this style of conversation might not be pleasant to Mrs. Harker, any more than it was to me, so I joined in:-\\u201cHow did you know I wanted to marry any one?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117754,\n            \"\\u201d His reply was simply contemptuous, given in a pause in which he turned his eyes from Mrs. Harker to me, instantly turning them back again:-\\u201cWhat an asinine question!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118334,\n            \"Looking at my watch, I saw that I should go to the station to meet Van Helsing, so I told Mrs. Harker that it was time to leave.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118592,\n            \"\\u201d As I drove to the house I told him of what had passed, and of how my own diary had come to be of some use through Mrs. Harker\\u2019s suggestion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118993,\n            \"Before we went to prepare for dinner he said to Mrs. Harker:-\\u201cI am told, Madam Mina, by my friend John that you and your husband have put up in exact order all things that have been, up to this moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143939,\n            \"His wife was aroused by the quick movement, and turned to him with her arms stretched out, as though to embrace him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144168,\n            \"Guard her while I look for him!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145106,\n            \"\\u201d Mrs. Harker raised her head, looking from one to the other of us she said solemnly:-\\u201cGod\\u2019s will be done!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145344,\n            \"then Van Helsing said, placing his hand very tenderly on Mrs. Harker\\u2019s head:-\\u201cAnd now, Madam Mina-poor, dear, dear Madam Mina-tell us exactly what happened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153337,\n            \"The Professor tried to keep our minds active by using them all the time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153352,\n            \"I could see his beneficent purpose, by the side glances which he threw from time to time at Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153503,\n            \"Poor fellow, I thought my own trouble was bad enough, but his--!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153553,\n            \"So well as I can remember, here it is:-\\u201cI have studied, over and over again since they came into my hands, all the papers relating to this monster;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153968,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI fail to understand,\\u201dsaid Harker wearily.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153999,\n            \"\\u201d The Professor laid his hand tenderly on his shoulder as he spoke:-\\u201cAh, my child, I will be plain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154536,\n            \"\\u201d There was a pause, broken by Jonathan Harker\\u2019s voice:-\\u201cNow, God be thanked, we shall soon meet!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154563,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing turned to him quickly and said:-\\u201cGod will act in His own way and time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154609,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI care for nothing now,\\u201dhe answered hotly, \\u201cexcept to wipe out this brute from the face of creation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154684,\n            \"But God is merciful and just, and knows your pain and your devotion to that dear Madam Mina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154704,\n            \"Think you, how her pain would be doubled, did she but hear your wild words.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155429,\n            \"Van Helsing, Harker, and I were just behind the door, so that when it was opened the Professor could guard it whilst we two stepped between the incomer and the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155711,\n            \"Harker evidently meant to try the matter, for he had ready his great Kukri knife and made a fierce and sudden cut at him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155804,\n            \"The expression of the Count\\u2019s face was so hellish, that for a moment I feared for Harker, though I saw him throw the terrible knife aloft again for another stroke.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155953,\n            \"The next instant, with a sinuous dive he swept under Harker\\u2019s arm, ere his blow could fall, and, grasping a handful of the money from the floor, dashed across the room, threw himself at the window.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156361,\n            \"took the title-deeds in the bundle as Harker had left them, and swept the remaining things into the open fireplace, where he set fire to them with a match.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156395,\n            \"Godalming and Morris had rushed out into the yard, and Harker had lowered himself from the window to follow the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156428,\n            \"and by the time they had forced it open there was no sign of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156535,\n            \"and we can there, at least, protect her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156579,\n            \"\\u201d I could see that he spoke as bravely as he could to comfort Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156624,\n            \"With sad hearts we came back to my house, where we found Mrs. Harker waiting us, with an appearance of cheerfulness which did honour to her bravery and unselfishness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156657,\n            \"When she saw our faces, her own became as pale as death: for a second or two her eyes were closed as if she were in secret prayer;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156688,\n            \"and then she said cheerfully:-\\u201cI can never thank you all enough.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156851,\n            \"True to our promise, we told Mrs. Harker everything which had passed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156902,\n            \"When we came to the part where Harker had rushed at the Count so recklessly, she clung to her husband\\u2019s arm, and held it tight as though her clinging could protect him from any harm that might come.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156970,\n            \"Then without letting go her husband\\u2019s hand she stood up amongst us and spoke.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156999,\n            \"of that sweet, sweet, good, good woman in all the radiant beauty of her youth and animation, with the red scar on her forehead, of which she was conscious, and which we saw with grinding of our teeth-remembering whence and how it came;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157051,\n            \"her loving kindness against our grim hate;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157059,\n            \"her tender faith against all our fears and doubting;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157069,\n            \"and we, knowing that so far as symbols went, she with all her goodness and purity and faith, was outcast from God.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157095,\n            \"\\u201cJonathan,\\u201dshe said, and the word sounded like music on her lips it was so full of love and tenderness, \\u201cJonathan dear, and you all my true, true friends, I want you to bear something in mind through all this dreadful time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157246,\n            \"\\u201d As she spoke I could see her husband\\u2019s face darken and draw together, as though the passion in him were shrivelling his being to its core.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157277,\n            \"Instinctively the clasp on his wife\\u2019s hand grew closer, till his knuckles looked white.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157295,\n            \"She did not flinch from the pain which I knew she must have suffered, but looked at him with eyes that were more appealing than ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157323,\n            \"As she stopped speaking he leaped to his feet, almost tearing his hand from hers as he spoke:-\\u201cMay God give him into my hand just for long enough to destroy that earthly life of him which we are aiming at.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157419,\n            \"or you will crush me with fear and horror.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157429,\n            \"Just think, my dear-I have been thinking all this long, long day of it-that.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157612,\n            \"Her husband flung himself on his knees beside her, and putting his arms round her, hid his face in the folds of her dress.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157662,\n            \"Before they retired the Professor fixed up the room against any coming of the Vampire, and assured Mrs. Harker that she might rest in peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157690,\n            \"She tried to school herself to the belief, and, manifestly for her husband\\u2019s sake, tried to seem content.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157754,\n            \"When they had retired, Quincey, Godalming, and I arranged that we should sit up, dividing the night between us, and watch over the safety of the poor stricken lady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164641,\n            \"I can see the characteristics of the vampire coming in her face.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164717,\n            \"She did not speak, even when she wrote that which she wished to be known later.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164741,\n            \"If it be that she can, by our hypnotic trance, tell what the Count see and hear, is it not more true that he who have hypnotise her first, and who have drink of her very blood and make her drink of his, should, if he will, compel her mind to disclose to him that which she know?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164829,\n            \"we must keep her ignorant of our intent, and so she cannot tell what she know not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164873,\n            \"When to-day we meet, I must tell her that for reason which we will not to speak she must not more be of our council, but be simply guarded by us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            164909,\n            \"\\u201d He wiped his forehead, which had broken out in profuse perspiration at the thought of the pain which he might have to inflict upon the poor soul already so tortured.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165059,\n            \"Mrs. Harker had sent a message by her husband to say that she would not join us at present, as she thought it better that we should be free to discuss our movements without her presence to embarrass us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165120,\n            \"For my own part, I thought that if Mrs. Harker realised the danger herself, it was much pain as well as much danger averted.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165215,\n            \"It will take her at the quickest speed she has ever made at least three weeks to reach Varna;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165583,\n            \"\\u201d said Harker interrogatively, looking from one to another of us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165600,\n            \"\\u201d answered the Professor quickly, \\u201cyou must remain to take care of your so sweet wife!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165619,\n            \"\\u201d Harker was silent for awhile and then said in a hollow voice:-\\u201cLet us talk of that part of it in the morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165647,\n            \"I want to consult with Mina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165654,\n            \"\\u201d I thought that now was the time for Van Helsing to warn him not to disclose our plans to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165682,\n            \"I looked at him significantly and coughed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167693,\n            \"- Jonathan Harker has asked me to note this, as he says he is hardly equal to the task, and he wants an exact record kept.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168192,\n            \"\\u201d She looked appealingly to us all in turn, beginning and ending with her husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168424,\n            \"The faces of the others were set and Harker\\u2019s grew ashen grey;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168439,\n            \"perhaps he guessed better than any of us what was coming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169071,\n            \"And oh, my dear, if it is to be that I must meet death at any hand, let it be at the hand of him that loves me best.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169104,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing, I have not forgotten your mercy in poor Lucy\\u2019s case to him who loved \\\"-she stopped with a flying blush, and changed her phrase-\\\" to him who had best right to give her peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169151,\n            \"If that time shall come again, I look to you to make it a happy memory of my husband\\u2019s life that it was his loving hand which set me free from the awful thrall upon me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169206,\n            \"Mrs. Harker smiled, positively smiled, as with a sigh of relief she leaned back and said:-\\u201cAnd now one word of warning, a warning which you must never forget: this time, if it ever come, may come quickly and unexpectedly, and in such case you must lose no time in using your opportunity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169304,\n            \"\\u201d she became very solemn as she said this, \\u201cit is not vital and necessary like the other, but I want you to do one thing for me, if you will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169350,\n            \"there was no need to speak:-\\u201cI want you to read the Burial Service.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169368,\n            \"\\u201d She was interrupted by a deep groan from her husband;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169380,\n            \"taking his hand in hers, she held it over her heart, and continued: \\u201cYou must read it over me some day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169432,\n            \"You, my dearest, will I hope read it, for then it will be in your voice in my memory for ever-come what may!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169461,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut oh, my dear one,\\u201dhe pleaded, \\u201cdeath is afar off from you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169518,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cOh, my wife, must I read it?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169566,\n            \"\\u201cHow can I-how could any one-tell of that strange scene, its solemnity, its gloom, its sadness, its horror;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169601,\n            \"Even a sceptic, who can see nothing but a travesty of bitter truth in anything holy or emotional, would have been melted to the heart had he seen that little group of loving and devoted friends kneeling round that stricken and sorrowing lady;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169687,\n            \"I-I cannot go on-words-and-v-voice-f-fail m-me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169746,\n            \"and the silence, which showed Mrs. Harker\\u2019s coming relapse from her freedom of soul, did not seem so full of despair to any of us as we had dreaded.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170768,\n            \"The Professor says that if we can so treat the Count\\u2019s body, it will soon after fall into dust.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171207,\n            \"It would break poor Harker\\u2019s heart-certainly his nerve-if he knew that we had even a suspicion on the subject.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171466,\n            \"We men are all in a fever of excitement, except Harker, who is calm;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172950,\n            \"When the three men had gone out to their tasks Van Helsing asked Mrs. Harker to look up the copy of the diaries and find him the part of Harker\\u2019s journal at the Castle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174306,\n            \"Oh, my dear, I see that your eyes are opened, and that to you the lightning flash show all the leagues,\\u201dfor Mrs. Harker began to clap her hands and her eyes sparkled.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175290,\n            \"\\u201d And so I have written it whilst we wait their return, and Mrs. Harker has written with her typewriter all since she brought the MS.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175403,\n            \"When the usual time came round Mrs. Harker prepared herself for her hypnotic effort;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175632,\n            \"Quincey raised his eyebrows slightly and looked at her intently, whilst Harker\\u2019s hand instinctively closed round the hilt of his Kukri.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175975,\n            \"at which time we might learn more from Mrs. Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175987,\n            \"Early this morning we listened, with breathless anxiety, for her response in her trance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176155,\n            \"Thus we shall have two more hypnotic messages from Mrs. Harker;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176239,\n            \"I am in fear that her power of reading the Count\\u2019s sensations may die away, just when we want it most.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176264,\n            \"It seems to me that her imagination is beginning to work.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176304,\n            \"If I thought that the Count\\u2019s power over her would die away equally with her power of knowledge it would be a happy thought;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176370,\n            \"I can hear, far off, confused sounds-as of men talking in strange tongues, fierce-falling water, and the howling of wolves.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176703,\n            \"She opened her eyes, and we all started as she said, sweetly and seemingly with the utmost unconcern:-\\u201cOh, Professor, why ask me to do what you know I can\\u2019t?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176750,\n            \"\\u201d Then, seeing the look of amazement on our faces, she said, turning from one to the other with a troubled look:-\\u201cWhat have I said?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176815,\n            \"\\u2019 It seemed so funny to hear you order me about, as if I were a bad child!\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 7]\": [\n        [\n            340,\n            \"I find that the district he named is in the extreme east of the country, just on the borders of three states, Transylvania, Moldavia and Bukovina, in the midst of the Carpathian mountains;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            603,\n            \", I must ask the Count all about them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1535,\n            \"- I found that my landlord had got a letter from the Count, directing him to secure the best place on the coach for me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1657,\n            \"When I asked him if he knew Count Dracula, and could tell me anything of his castle, both he and his wife crossed themselves, and, saying that they knew nothing at all, simply refused to speak further.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2668,\n            \", I must ask the Count about these superstitions) When we started, the crowd round the inn door, which had by this time swelled to a considerable size, all made the sign of the cross and pointed two fingers towards me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4740,\n            \"\\u201d The man stammered in reply:-\\u201cThe English Herr was in a hurry,\\u201dto which the stranger replied:-\\u201cThat is why, I suppose, you wished him to go on to Bukovina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5075,\n            \"but a cloak was thrown over my shoulders, and a rug across my knees, and the driver said in excellent German:-\\u201cThe night is chill, mein Herr, and my master the Count bade me take all care of you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7409,\n            \"The instant, however, that I had stepped over the threshold, he moved impulsively forward, and holding out his hand grasped mine with a strength which made me wince, an effect which was not lessened by the fact that it seemed as cold as ice-more like the hand of a dead than a living man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7678,\n            \"\\u201d He insisted on carrying my traps along the passage, and then up a great winding stair, and along another great passage, on whose stone floor our steps rang heavily.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            13807,\n            \"In the meantime I must find out all I can about Count Dracula, as it may help me to understand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14461,\n            \"Who was it but one of my own race who as Voivode crossed the Danube and beat the Turk on his own ground?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14485,\n            \"This was a Dracula indeed!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14520,\n            \"Was it not this Dracula, indeed, who inspired that other of his race who in a later age again and again brought his forces over the great river into Turkey-land;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14631,\n            \"Again, when, after the battle of Moh\\u00e1cs, we threw off the Hungarian yoke, we of the Dracula blood were amongst their leaders, for our spirit would not brook that we were not free.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14670,\n            \"Ah, young sir, the Szekelys-and the Dracula as their heart\\u2019s blood, their brains, and their swords-can boast a record that mushroom growths like the Hapsburgs and the Romanoffs can never reach.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            14853,\n            \"Last evening when the Count came from his room he began by asking me questions on legal matters and on the doing of certain kinds of business.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15451,\n            \"I explained all these things to him to the best of my ability, and he certainly left me under the impression that he would have made a wonderful solicitor, for there was nothing that he did not think of or foresee.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15495,\n            \"For a man who was never in the country, and who did not evidently do much in the way of business, his knowledge and acumen were wonderful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15525,\n            \"When he had satisfied himself on these points of which he had spoken, and I had verified all as well as I could by the books available, he suddenly stood up and said:-\\u201cHave you written since your first letter to our friend Mr. Peter Hawkins, or to any other?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15615,\n            \"\\u201cThen write now, my young friend,\\u201dhe said, laying a heavy hand on my shoulder: \\u201cwrite to our friend and to any other;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15646,\n            \"and say, if it will please you, that you shall stay with me until a month from now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            15667,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo you wish me to stay so long?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118865,\n            \"\\u201d I agreed heartily with him, and then I told him what we had found in his absence: that the house which Dracula had bought was the very next one to my own.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118924,\n            \"\\u201d he said, \\u201cfor then we might have reached him in time to save poor Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132388,\n            \"The systematic manner in which this was done made me think that he could not mean to confine himself to two sides of London.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            133058,\n            \"Indeed, it may not be a hard task, after all, for she herself has become reticent on the subject, and has not spoken of the Count or his doings ever since we told her of our decision.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            134509,\n            \"beyond the Junior Constitutional I came across the house described, and was satisfied that this was the next of the lairs arranged by Dracula.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160726,\n            \"For my own part, now that his horrible danger is not face to face with us, it seems almost impossible to believe in it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161111,\n            \"He was in sailing ship, since Madam Mina tell of sails being set.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162228,\n            \"\\u201cAnd so, my dear Madam Mina, it is that we have to rest for a time, for our enemy is on the sea, with the fog at his command, on his way to the Danube mouth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162284,\n            \"and when we start we go on land more quick, and we meet him there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162301,\n            \"Our best hope is to come on him when in the box between sunrise and sunset;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162318,\n            \"for then he can make no struggle, and we may deal with him as we should.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162351,\n            \"We know all about where he go;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162477,\n            \"\\u201d When Dr. Van Helsing had done speaking, I asked him if he were certain that the Count had remained on board the ship.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162528,\n            \"\\u201d I asked him again if it were really necessary that they should pursue the Count, for oh!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162722,\n            \"I have told them how the measure of leaving his own barren land-barren of peoples-and coming to a new land where life of man teems till they are like the multitude of standing corn, was the work of centuries.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162767,\n            \"Were another of the Un-Dead, like him, to try to do what he has done, perhaps not all the centuries of the world that have been, or that will be, could aid him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162936,\n            \"In a hard and warlike time he was celebrate that he have more iron nerve, more subtle brain, more braver heart, than any man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163025,\n            \"And now this is what he is to us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163035,\n            \"He have infect you-oh, forgive me, my dear, that I must say such;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163065,\n            \"He infect you in such wise, that even if he do no more, you have only to live-to live in your own old, sweet way;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163096,\n            \"and so in time, death, which is of man\\u2019s common lot and with God\\u2019s sanction, shall make you like to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163225,\n            \"\\u201d He paused and I said:-\\u201cBut will not the Count take his rebuff wisely?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163296,\n            \"Your man-eater, as they of India call the tiger who has once tasted blood of the human, care no more for the other prey, but prowl unceasing till he get him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163333,\n            \"This that we hunt from our village is a tiger, too, a man-eater, and he never cease to prowl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163543,\n            \"His glimpse that he have had, whet his appetite only and enkeen his desire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180926,\n            \"Whilst the old fox is tied in his box, floating on the running stream whence he cannot escape to land-where he dares not raise the lid of his coffin-box lest his Slovak carriers should in fear leave him to perish-we shall go in the track where Jonathan went,-from Bistritz over the Borgo, and find our way to the Castle of Dracula.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189303,\n            \"Before I began to restore these women to their dead selves through my awful work, I laid in Dracula\\u2019s tomb some of the Wafer, and so banished him from it, Un-Dead, for ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189994,\n            \"Then we looked back and saw where the clear line of Dracula\\u2019s castle cut the sky;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 8]\": [\n        [\n            117503,\n            \"She walked over to him, smiling pleasantly, and held out her hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118628,\n            \"at which the Professor interrupted me:-\\u201cAh, that wonderful Madam Mina!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118644,\n            \"She has man\\u2019s brain-a brain that a man should have were he much gifted-and a woman\\u2019s heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118670,\n            \"The good God fashioned her for a purpose, believe me, when He made that so good combination.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118690,\n            \"Friend John, up to now fortune has made that woman of help to us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118832,\n            \"You tell me she has wrote all, then she must consult with us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118847,\n            \"but to-morrow she say good-bye to this work, and we go alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151204,\n            \"And oh, Madam Mina, my dear, my dear, may we who love you be there to see, when that red scar, the sign of God\\u2019s knowledge of what has been, shall pass away, and leave your forehead as pure as the heart we know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            151923,\n            \"If it may be that with all the others we can be so successful, then the sunset of this evening may shine on Madam Mina\\u2019s forehead all white as ivory and with no stain!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166822,\n            \"\\u201d Dr. Van Helsing said very gravely:-\\u201cMadam Mina, you are, as always, most wise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166974,\n            \"We have now to deal with a new factor: Madam Mina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167289,\n            \"My child, believe me none of us shall lag behind or pause from any fear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167640,\n            \"I write all these things in the diary since my darling must not hear them now;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167657,\n            \"but if it may be that she can see them again, they shall be ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172783,\n            \"John will stay with Madam Mina and me, and we shall consult.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173124,\n            \"In the moment when Madam Mina said those words that arrest both our understanding, an inspiration came to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173366,\n            \"not a word to her of her trance!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173591,\n            \"Then holding the pages between his finger and thumb he said:-\\u201cFriend John, to you with so much of experience already-and you, too, dear Madam Mina, that are young-here is a lesson: do not fear ever to think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184451,\n            \"he says I answered \\u201cdarkness, creaking wood and roaring water,\\u201dso the river is changing as they ascend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184474,\n            \"I do hope that my darling will not run any chance of danger-more than need be;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184729,\n            \"We go to seek the place where my poor darling suffered so much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184866,\n            \"It is morning, and I write by a fire which all the night I have kept alive-Madam Mina aiding me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185041,\n            \"At sunset I try to hypnotise her, but alas!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185096,\n            \"Now to the historical, for as Madam Mina write not in her stenography, I must, in my cumbrous old fashion, that so each day of us may not go unrecorded.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185174,\n            \"I made a couch with furs, and Madam Mina, lying down, yield herself as usual, but more slow and more short time than ever, to the hypnotic sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185223,\n            \"\\u201d Then she woke, bright and radiant and we go on our way and soon reach the Pass.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185465,\n            \"At the first, I tell Madam Mina to sleep;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185489,\n            \"till at the last, I feel myself to suspicious grow, and attempt to wake her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185507,\n            \"But she sleep on, and I may not wake her though I try.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185522,\n            \"I do not wish to try too hard lest I harm her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185535,\n            \"for I know that she have suffer much, and sleep at times be all-in-all to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185605,\n            \"I look down and find Madam Mina still sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185683,\n            \"Then I arouse Madam Mina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185689,\n            \"This time she wake with not much trouble, and then I try to put her to hypnotic sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185709,\n            \"But she sleep not, being as though I were not.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185721,\n            \"Still I try and try, till all at once I find her and myself in dark;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185753,\n            \"Madam Mina laugh, and I turn and look at her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185765,\n            \"She is now quite awake, and look so well as I never saw her since that night at Carfax when we first enter the Count\\u2019s house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185805,\n            \"but she is so bright and tender and thoughtful for me that I forget all fear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185822,\n            \"I light a fire, for we have brought supply of wood with us, and she prepare food while I undo the horses and set them, tethered in shelter, to feed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185857,\n            \"Then when I return to the fire she have my supper ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185870,\n            \"I go to help her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185876,\n            \"but she smile, and tell me that she have eat already-that she was so hungry that she would not wait.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185911,\n            \"but I fear to affright her, and so I am silent of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185926,\n            \"She help me and I eat alone;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185934,\n            \"and then we wrap in fur and lie beside the fire, and I tell her to sleep while I watch.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185964,\n            \"and when I sudden remember that I watch, I find her lying quiet, but awake, and looking at me with so bright eyes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186008,\n            \"When I wake I try to hypnotise her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186061,\n            \"I have to lift her up, and place her sleeping in the carriage when I have harnessed the horses and made all ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186270,\n            \"and though I did have hunger and appeased it, I could not waken her-even for food.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186290,\n            \"I began to fear that the fatal spell of the place was upon her, tainted as she is with that Vampire baptism.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186314,\n            \"\\u201cWell,\\u201dsaid I to myself, \\u201cif it be that she sleep all the day, it shall also be that I do not sleep at night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186375,\n            \"Again I waked with a sense of guilt and of time passed, and found Madam Mina still sleeping, and the sun low down.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186463,\n            \"I woke Madam Mina, and again tried to hypnotise her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186540,\n            \"and near it I make Madam Mina, now awake and more charming than ever, sit comfortable amid her rugs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186562,\n            \"I got ready food: but she would not eat, simply saying that she had not hunger.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186581,\n            \"I did not press her, knowing her unavailingness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186606,\n            \"Then, with the fear on me of what might be, I drew a ring so big for her comfort, round where Madam Mina sat;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186691,\n            \"But when I drew near, she clung to me, and I could know that the poor soul shook her from head to feet with a tremor that was pain to feel.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186725,\n            \"I said to her presently, when she had grown more quiet:-\\u201cWill you not come over to the fire?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186749,\n            \"\\u201d for I wished to make a test of what she could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186808,\n            \"Then, looking at me with open eyes, as of one waked from sleep, she said simply:-\\u201cI cannot!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186838,\n            \"I rejoiced, for I knew that what she could not, none of those that we dreaded could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187201,\n            \"I feared for my dear Madam Mina when these weird figures drew near and circled round.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187218,\n            \"I looked at her, but she sat calm, and smiled at me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187233,\n            \"when I would have stepped to the fire to replenish it, she caught me and held me back, and whispered, like a voice that one hears in a dream, so low it was:-\\u201cNo!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187287,\n            \"\\u201d I turned to her, and looking in her eyes, said:-\\u201cBut you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187306,\n            \"It is for you that I fear!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187340,\n            \"None safer in all the world from them than I am,\\u201dand as I wondered at the meaning of her words, a puff of wind made the flame leap up, and I see the red scar on her forehead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187494,\n            \"They smiled ever at poor dear Madam Mina;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187503,\n            \"and as their laugh came through the silence of the night, they twined their arms and pointed to her, and said in those so sweet tingling tones that Jonathan said were of the intolerable sweetness of the water-glasses:-\\u201cCome, sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187680,\n            \"They could not approach, me, whilst so armed, nor Madam Mina whilst she remained within the ring, which she could not leave no more than they could enter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187833,\n            \"Instinctively, with the dawn coming, I turned to Madam Mina, intending to hypnotise her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189706,\n            \"When I stepped into the circle where Madam Mina slept, she woke from her sleep, and, seeing, me, cried out in pain that I had endured too much.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 9]\": [\n        [\n            56738,\n            \"\\u201cMy good Friend,-\\u201cWhen I have received your letter I am already coming to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56810,\n            \"Tell your friend that when that time you suck from my wound so swiftly the poison of the gangrene from that knife that our other friend, too nervous, let slip, you did more for him when he wants my aids and you call for them than all his great fortune could do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56866,\n            \"But it is pleasure added to do for him, your friend;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56879,\n            \"it is to you that I come.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56974,\n            \"\\u201d Letter, Dr. Seward to Hon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59303,\n            \"Mrs. Westenra was naturally anxious concerning Lucy, and has consulted me professionally about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59320,\n            \"I took advantage of the opportunity, and told her that my old master, Van Helsing, the great specialist, was coming to stay with me, and that I would put her in his charge conjointly with myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59479,\n            \"- The first thing Van Helsing said to me when we met at Liverpool Street was:-\\u201cHave you said anything to our young friend the lover of her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59611,\n            \"And, my good friend John, let me caution you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59623,\n            \"You deal with the madmen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59640,\n            \"and inasmuch as you deal discreetly with your madmen, so deal with God\\u2019s madmen, too-the rest of the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59713,\n            \"You and I shall keep as yet what we know here, and here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60054,\n            \"Then he went on, and very gravely:-\\u201cYou were always a careful student, and your case-book was ever more full than the rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60126,\n            \"Even if you have not kept the good practise, let me tell you that this case of our dear miss is one that may be-mind, I say may be-of such interest to us and others that all the rest may not make him kick the beam, as your peoples say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60196,\n            \"I counsel you, put down in record even your doubts and surmises.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61184,\n            \"You are better than me, better than my friend John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61235,\n            \"My friend John and I have consulted;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61272,\n            \"John was to give his blood, as he is the more young and strong than me \\\"-here Arthur took my hand and wrung it hard in silence-\\\" but, now you are here, you are more good than us, old or young, who toil much in the world of thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63086,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAh, I can trust you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63135,\n            \"How good you are to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65080,\n            \"When her mother came up to see her, she did not seem to notice any change whatever, but said to me gratefully:-\\u201cWe owe you so much, Dr. Seward, for all you have done, but you really must now take care not to overwork yourself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65141,\n            \"You want a wife to nurse and look after you a bit;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65229,\n            \"Van Helsing returned in a couple of hours, and presently said to me: \\u201cNow you go home, and eat much and drink enough.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65278,\n            \"You and I must watch the case, and we must have none other to know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65566,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cYes, my dear, but not for you to play with.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66000,\n            \"Come with me, friend John, and you shall help me deck the room with my garlic, which is all the way from Haarlem, where my friend Vanderpool raise herb in his glass-houses all the year.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66433,\n            \"To-morrow in the morning early you call for me, and we come together to see our pretty miss, so much more strong for my \\u2018 spell\\u2019which I have work.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66905,\n            \"She greeted us warmly and said:-\\u201cYou will be glad to know that Lucy is better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79335,\n            \"I never knew either father or mother, so that the dear old man\\u2019s death is a real blow to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79569,\n            \"but, Lucy dear, I must tell some one, for the strain of keeping up a brave and cheerful appearance to Jonathan tries me, and I have no one here that I can confide in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79608,\n            \"I dread coming up to London, as we must do the day after to-morrow;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79726,\n            \"I am too miserable, too low-spirited, too sick of the world and all in it, including life itself, that I would not care if I heard this moment the flapping of the wings of the angel of death.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79809,\n            \"I duly relieved Van Helsing in his watch over Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79835,\n            \"It was only when I told him that we should want him to help us during the day, and that we must not all break down for want of rest, lest Lucy should suffer, that he agreed to go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80034,\n            \"She lay quite still, and I looked round the room to see that all was as it should be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80055,\n            \"I could see that the Professor had carried out in this room, as in the other, his purpose of using the garlic;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80186,\n            \"I sat down by her, and presently she moved uneasily.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80278,\n            \"When I came back to my seat, I found that Lucy had moved slightly, and had torn away the garlic flowers from her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80305,\n            \"I replaced them as well as I could, and sat watching her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80319,\n            \"Presently she woke, and I gave her food, as Van Helsing had prescribed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80369,\n            \"It struck me as curious that the moment she became conscious she pressed the garlic flowers close to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80631,\n            \"Then he turned to me and said calmly:-\\u201cShe is dying.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80820,\n            \"\\u201cCome,\\u201dI said, \\u201cmy dear old fellow, summon all your fortitude: it will be best and easiest for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80847,\n            \"\\u201d When we came into Lucy\\u2019s room I could see that Van Helsing had, with his usual forethought, been putting matters straight and making everything look as pleasing as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81082,\n            \"In a sort of sleep-waking, vague, unconscious way she opened her eyes, which were now dull and hard at once, and said in a soft, voluptuous voice, such as I had never heard from her lips:-\\u201cArthur!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81156,\n            \"but at that instant Van Helsing, who, like me, had been startled by her voice, swooped upon him, and catching him by the neck with both hands, dragged him back with a fury of strength which I never thought he could have possessed, and actually hurled him almost across the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81288,\n            \"I kept my eyes fixed on Lucy, as did Van Helsing, and we saw a spasm as of rage flit like a shadow over her face;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81699,\n            \"\\u201d I stood beside Van Helsing, and said:-\\u201cAh, well, poor girl, there is peace for her at last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81759,\n            \"\\u201d When I asked him what he meant, he only shook his head and answered:-\\u201cWe can do nothing as yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81822,\n            \"I attended to all the ghastly formalities, and the urbane undertaker proved that his staff were afflicted-or blessed-with something of his own obsequious suavity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81852,\n            \"Even the woman who performed the last offices for the dead remarked to me, in a confidential, brother-professional way, when she had come out from the death-chamber:-\\u201cShe makes a very beautiful corpse, sir.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81989,\n            \"Under the circumstances, Van Helsing and I took it upon ourselves to examine papers, etc.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82018,\n            \"I asked him why, for I feared that he, being a foreigner, might not be quite aware of English legal requirements, and so might in ignorance make some unnecessary trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82065,\n            \"You forget that I am a lawyer as well as a doctor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82087,\n            \"You knew that, when you avoided the coroner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82146,\n            \"\\u201cWhen you find anything of the solicitor who is for the late Mrs. Westenra, seal all her papers, and write him to-night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82219,\n            \"\\u201d I went on with my part of the work, and in another half hour had found the name and address of Mrs. Westenra\\u2019s solicitor and had written to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82421,\n            \"\\u201d When we had finished the work in hand, he said to me:-\\u201cAnd now, friend John, I think we may to bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82451,\n            \"We want sleep, both you and I, and rest to recuperate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82588,\n            \"All Lucy\\u2019s loveliness had come back to her in death, and the hours that had passed, instead of leaving traces of \\u201cdecay\\u2019s effacing fingers,\\u201dhad but restored the beauty of life, till positively I could not believe my eyes that I was looking at a corpse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82651,\n            \"He had not loved her as I had, and there was no need for tears in his eyes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82761,\n            \"I was undressing in my own room, when, with a premonitory tap at the door, he entered, and at once began to speak:-\\u201cTo-morrow I want you to bring me, before night, a set of post-mortem knives.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82829,\n            \"I want to operate, but not as you think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82840,\n            \"Let me tell you now, but not a word to another.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82868,\n            \"you a surgeon, and so shocked!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82876,\n            \"You, whom I have seen with no tremble of hand or heart, do operations of life and death that make the rest shudder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82902,\n            \"Oh, but I must not forget, my dear friend John, that you loved her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83098,\n            \"\\u201d For answer he put his hand on my shoulder, and said, with infinite tenderness:-\\u201cFriend John, I pity your poor bleeding heart;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83184,\n            \"John, my child, you have been my friend now many years, and yet did you ever know me to do any without good cause?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87941,\n            \"He said:-\\u201cAh, you don\\u2019t comprehend, friend John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88219,\n            \"And yet when he say things that touch my husband-heart to the quick, and make my father-heart yearn to him as to no other man-not even to you, friend John, for we are more level in experiences than father and son-yet even at such moment King Laugh he come to me and shout and bellow in my ear, \\u2018 Here I am!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88398,\n            \"And believe me, friend John, that he is good to come, and kind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88915,\n            \"He laid his hand on my arm, and said:-\\u201cFriend John, forgive me if I pain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88937,\n            \"I showed not my feeling to others when it would wound, but only to you, my old friend, whom I can trust.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89825,\n            \"I am so glad that he has plenty of work to do, for that keeps his mind off the terrible things;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            96528,\n            \"Then, friend John, am I to take it that you simply accept fact, and are satisfied to let from premise to conclusion be a blank?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97796,\n            \"Oh, my friend, why, think you, did I go so far round, why take so long to tell you so simple a thing?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99593,\n            \"\\u201cAre you satisfied now, friend John?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101091,\n            \"Are you of belief now, friend John?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101322,\n            \"you do not know that, friend John, but you shall know it all later-and in trance could he best come to take more blood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102365,\n            \"\\u201cFriend John,-\\u201cI write this in case anything should happen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103197,\n            \"\\u201cOh,\\u201dsaid the Professor, \\u201cthen you are nearer the beginning, both of you, than friend John here, who has to go a long way back before he can even get so far as to begin.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104620,\n            \"at the first to please my friend John, and then to help a sweet young lady, whom, too, I came to love.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105334,\n            \"Did she not, friend John?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110112,\n            \"Then said the Professor as we moved off:-\\u201cTwo nights hence you shall meet with me and dine together at seven of the clock with friend John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110352,\n            \"She must go to your house, friend John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110362,\n            \"You must meet her at the station.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118438,\n            \"\\u201d When I went to the station to meet Van Helsing I left the boys behind me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118576,\n            \"And Arthur and my friend Quincey, they are with you, too?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118690,\n            \"Friend John, up to now fortune has made that woman of help to us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118832,\n            \"You tell me she has wrote all, then she must consult with us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123180,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cTake me with you, friend John,\\u201dsaid the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123537,\n            \"I grieve to know, by your holding the title, that he is no more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123675,\n            \"Sir, I make no apology for dropping all forms of conventional prefix.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125626,\n            \"Then Mr. Morris said to Dr. Seward:-\\u201cSay, Jack, if that man wasn\\u2019t attempting a bluff, he is about the sanest lunatic I ever saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125695,\n            \"\\u201d Lord Godalming and I were silent, but Dr. Van Helsing added:-\\u201cFriend John, you know more of lunatics than I do, and I\\u2019m glad of it, for I fear that if it had been to me to decide I would before that last hysterical outburst have given him free.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125958,\n            \"I only hope we have done what is best.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125988,\n            \"\\u201d The Professor stepped over, and laying his hand on his shoulder, said in his grave, kindly way:-\\u201cFriend John, have no fear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126431,\n            \"\\u201cNow,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cfriend John, where are the skeleton keys?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126474,\n            \"\\u201d Dr. Seward tried one or two skeleton keys, his mechanical dexterity as a surgeon standing him in good stead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129201,\n            \"After going over the adventure of the night he suddenly said:-\\u201cYour patient interests me much.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129361,\n            \"He said to Madam Mina, as I see in your diary of yesterday, that he had once had such a belief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            129843,\n            \"Friend John, it does rejoice me unspeakable that she is no more to be pained, no more to be worried with our terrible things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130078,\n            \"This morning I slept late after the fatigues of yesterday, and though Jonathan was late too, he was the earlier.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170469,\n            \"Judge Moneybag will settle this case, I think!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170574,\n            \"- Everything is pretty well fixed now, I think, to welcome the Count on his return from his tour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170745,\n            \"Morris and Godalming and I shall prevent interference, even if we have to use the arms which we shall have ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171545,\n            \"Van Helsing and I were a little alarmed about Mrs. Harker to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171757,\n            \"To his doom, I trust!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171930,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing is terribly anxious, and told me just now that he fears the Count is escaping us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172076,\n            \"- When the telegram came announcing the arrival in Galatz I do not think it was such a shock to any of us as might have been expected.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172124,\n            \"but I think we all expected that something strange would happen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172179,\n            \"I suppose that nature works on such a hopeful basis that we believe against ourselves that things will be as they ought to be, not as we should know that they will be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172470,\n            \"\\u201cYou forget-or perhaps you do not know, though Jonathan does and so does Dr. Van Helsing-that I am the train fiend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172705,\n            \"Do you, friend Jonathan, go to the agent of the ship and get from him letters to the agent in Galatz, with authority to make search the ship just as it was here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172783,\n            \"John will stay with Madam Mina and me, and we shall consult.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172995,\n            \"when the door was shut upon her he said to me:-\\u201cWe mean the same!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173024,\n            \"It is a hope that makes me sick, for it may deceive us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173044,\n            \"Do you know why I asked her to get the manuscript?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173301,\n            \"there I have hope that our man-brains that have been of man so long and that have not lost the grace of God, will come higher than his child-brain that lie in his tomb for centuries, that grow not yet to our stature, and that do only work selfish and therefore small.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173459,\n            \"Oh, John, my friend, we are in awful straits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173591,\n            \"Then holding the pages between his finger and thumb he said:-\\u201cFriend John, to you with so much of experience already-and you, too, dear Madam Mina, that are young-here is a lesson: do not fear ever to think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174385,\n            \"His finger and thumb closed on her pulse, as I thought instinctively and unconsciously, as she spoke:-\\u201cThe Count is a criminal and of criminal type.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175256,\n            \"You must be scribe and write him all down, so that when the others return from their work you can give it to them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180864,\n            \"Now let me say that what I would is this: while you, my Lord Godalming and friend Jonathan go in your so swift little steamboat up the river, and whilst John and Quincey guard the bank where perchance he might be landed, I will take Madam Mina right into the heart of the enemy\\u2019s country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189052,\n            \"but I go on searching until, presently, I find in a high great tomb as if made to one much beloved that other fair sister which, like Jonathan I had seen to gather herself out of the atoms of the mist.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 10]\": [\n        [\n            20920,\n            \"\\\"-he must have looked at it-\\\" one is from you, and to my friend Peter Hawkins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            21023,\n            \"Then he went on:-\\u201cThe letter to Hawkins-that I shall, of course, send on, since it is yours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77478,\n            \"when we arrived at Exeter there was a carriage waiting for us, and in it, though he had an attack of gout, Mr. Hawkins.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77507,\n            \"He took us to his house, where there were rooms for us all nice and comfortable, and we dined together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77530,\n            \"After dinner Mr. Hawkins said:-\\u201c\\u2018 My dears, I want to drink your health and prosperity;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77560,\n            \"I know you both from children, and have, with love and pride, seen you grow up.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77580,\n            \"Now I want you to make your home here with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77592,\n            \"I have left to me neither chick nor child;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77602,\n            \"all are gone, and in my will I have left you everything.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77616,\n            \"\\u2019 I cried, Lucy dear, as Jonathan and the old man clasped hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77742,\n            \"for, now that Jonathan is a partner, Mr. Hawkins wants to tell him all about the clients.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78298,\n            \"The man, who seemed a decent fellow enough, contented himself by telling him to \\u201cshut up for a foul-mouthed beggar,\\u201dwhereon our man accused him of robbing him and wanting to murder him and said that he would hinder him if he were to swing for it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78353,\n            \"I opened the window and signed to the man not to notice, so he contented himself after looking the place over and making up his mind as to what kind of a place he had got to by saying: \\u2018 Lor\\u2019bless yer, sir, I wouldn\\u2019t mind what was said to me in a bloomin\\u2019madhouse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78418,\n            \"I pity ye and the guv\\u2019nor for havin\\u2019to live in the house with a wild beast like that.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78441,\n            \"\\u2019 Then he asked his way civilly enough, and I told him where the gate of the empty house was;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 11]\": [\n        [\n            34398,\n            \"- The case of Renfield grows more interesting the more I get to understand the man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34444,\n            \"He seems to have some settled scheme of his own, but what it is I do not yet know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34465,\n            \"His redeeming quality is a love of animals, though, indeed, he has such curious turns in it that I sometimes imagine he is only abnormally cruel.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34510,\n            \"He has at present such a quantity that I have had myself to expostulate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34525,\n            \"To my astonishment, he did not break out into a fury, as I expected, but took the matter in simple seriousness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34583,\n            \"I must watch him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34651,\n            \"- His spiders are now becoming as great a nuisance as his flies, and to-day I told him that he must get rid of them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34680,\n            \"He looked very sad at this, so I said that he must clear out some of them, at all events.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34703,\n            \"He cheerfully acquiesced in this, and I gave him the same time as before for reduction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34721,\n            \"He disgusted me much while with him, for when a horrid blow-fly, bloated with some carrion food, buzzed into the room, he caught it, held it exultantly for a few moments between his finger and thumb, and, before I knew what he was going to do, put it in his mouth and ate it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34786,\n            \"I scolded him for it, but he argued quietly that it was very good and very wholesome;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34831,\n            \"I must watch how he gets rid of his spiders.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34869,\n            \"Whole pages of it are filled with masses of figures, generally single numbers added up in batches, and then the totals added in batches again, as though he were \\u201cfocussing\\u201dsome account, as the auditors put it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34916,\n            \"- There is a method in his madness, and the rudimentary idea in my mind is growing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34963,\n            \"I kept away from my friend for a few days, so that I might notice if there were any change.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35035,\n            \"Those that do remain, however, are well fed, for he still brings in the flies by tempting them with his food.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35087,\n            \"When I came in he ran to me and said he wanted to ask me a great favour-a very, very great favour;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35113,\n            \"and as he spoke he fawned on me like a dog.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35125,\n            \"I asked him what it was, and he said, with a sort of rapture in his voice and bearing:-\\u201cA kitten, a nice little, sleek playful kitten, that I can play with, and teach, and feed-and feed-and feed!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35178,\n            \"\\u201d I was not unprepared for this request, for I had noticed how his pets went on increasing in size and vivacity, but I did not care that his pretty family of tame sparrows should be wiped out in the same manner as the flies and the spiders;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35229,\n            \"so I said I would see about it, and asked him if he would not rather have a cat than a kitten.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35273,\n            \"I only asked for a kitten lest you should refuse me a cat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35287,\n            \"No one would refuse me a kitten, would they?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35325,\n            \"His face fell, and I could see a warning of danger in it, for there was a sudden fierce, sidelong look which meant killing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35353,\n            \"The man is an undeveloped homicidal maniac.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35361,\n            \"I shall test him with his present craving and see how it will work out;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35388,\n            \"- I have visited him again and found him sitting in a corner brooding.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35403,\n            \"When I came in he threw himself on his knees before me and implored me to let him have a cat;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35432,\n            \"I was firm, however, and told him that he could not have it, whereupon he went without a word, and sat down, gnawing his fingers, in the corner where I had found him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35472,\n            \"I shall see him in the morning early.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35541,\n            \"I looked around for his birds, and not seeing them, asked him where they were.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35590,\n            \"I said nothing, but went and told the keeper to report to me if there were anything odd about him during the day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35620,\n            \"- The attendant has just been to me to say that Renfield has been very sick and has disgorged a whole lot of feathers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35645,\n            \"\\u201cMy belief is, doctor,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cthat he has eaten his birds, and that he just took and ate them raw!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            35680,\n            \"- I gave Renfield a strong opiate to-night, enough to make even him sleep, and took away his pocket-book to look at it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54149,\n            \"He was still in the strait-waistcoat and in the padded room, but the suffused look had gone from his face, and his eyes had something of their old pleading-I might almost say, \\u201ccringing \\\"-softness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54194,\n            \"I was satisfied with his present condition, and directed him to be relieved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54222,\n            \"It was a strange thing that the patient had humour enough to see their distrust, for, coming close to me, he said in a whisper, all the while looking furtively at them:-\\u201cThey think I could hurt you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54268,\n            \"Fancy me hurting you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54276,\n            \"\\u201d It was soothing, somehow, to the feelings to find myself dissociated even in the mind of this poor madman from the others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54302,\n            \"but all the same I do not follow his thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54313,\n            \"Am I to take it that I have anything in common with him, so that we are, as it were, to stand together;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54340,\n            \"or has he to gain from me some good so stupendous that my well-being is needful to him?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54427,\n            \"\\u201d After a while I left him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54435,\n            \"The attendant tells me that he was quiet until just before dawn, and that then he began to get uneasy, and at length violent, until at last he fell into a paroxysm which exhausted him so that he swooned into a sort of coma.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54545,\n            \"He escaped before without our help;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54561,\n            \"We shall give him a chance, and have the men ready to follow in case they are required.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54601,\n            \"Our bird when he found the cage open would not fly, so all our subtle arrangements were for nought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54642,\n            \"We shall in future be able to ease his bonds for a few hours each day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54659,\n            \"I have given orders to the night attendant merely to shut him in the padded room, when once he is quiet, until an hour before sunrise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54730,\n            \"Renfield artfully waited until the attendant was entering the room to inspect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54743,\n            \"Then he dashed out past him and flew down the passage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54764,\n            \"Again he went into the grounds of the deserted house, and we found him in the same place, pressed against the old chapel door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54791,\n            \"When he saw me he became furious, and had not the attendants seized him in time, he would have tried to kill me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54817,\n            \"As we were holding him a strange thing happened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54850,\n            \"Then I caught the patient\\u2019s eye and followed it, but could trace nothing as it looked into the moonlit sky except a big bat, which was flapping its silent and ghostly way to the west.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54923,\n            \"The patient grew calmer every instant, and presently said:-\\u201cYou needn\\u2019t tie me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            54958,\n            \"I feel there is something ominous in his calm, and shall not forget this night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78181,\n            \"This afternoon a carrier\\u2019s cart with two men made a call at the empty house whose grounds abut on ours-the house to which, you will remember, the patient twice ran away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78298,\n            \"The man, who seemed a decent fellow enough, contented himself by telling him to \\u201cshut up for a foul-mouthed beggar,\\u201dwhereon our man accused him of robbing him and wanting to murder him and said that he would hinder him if he were to swing for it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78418,\n            \"I pity ye and the guv\\u2019nor for havin\\u2019to live in the house with a wild beast like that.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78478,\n            \"I went down to see if I could make out any cause for his anger, since he is usually such a well-behaved man, and except his violent fits nothing of the kind had ever occurred.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78518,\n            \"I found him, to my astonishment, quite composed and most genial in his manner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78535,\n            \"I tried to get him to talk of the incident, but he blandly asked me questions as to what I meant, and led me to believe that he was completely oblivious of the affair.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78572,\n            \"It was, I am sorry to say, however, only another instance of his cunning, for within half an hour I heard of him again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78621,\n            \"I called to the attendants to follow me, and ran after him, for I feared he was intent on some mischief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78692,\n            \"Before I could get up to him the patient rushed at them, and pulling one of them off the cart, began to knock his head against the ground.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78723,\n            \"If I had not seized him just at the moment I believe he would have killed the man there and then.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78745,\n            \"The other fellow jumped down and struck him over the head with the butt-end of his heavy whip.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78772,\n            \"but he did not seem to mind it, but seized him also, and struggled with the three of us, pulling us to and fro as if we were kittens.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78830,\n            \"but as we began to master him, and the attendants were putting a strait-waistcoat on him, he began to shout: \\u2018 I\\u2019ll frustrate them!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78862,\n            \"They shan\\u2019t rob me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78869,\n            \"they shan\\u2019t murder me by inches!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78897,\n            \"It was with very considerable difficulty that they got him back to the house and put him in the padded room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78975,\n            \"Their threats were, however, mingled with some sort of indirect apology for the defeat of the two of them by a feeble madman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79001,\n            \"They said that if it had not been for the way their strength had been spent in carrying and raising the heavy boxes to the cart they would have made short work of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113716,\n            \"Goodness knows that we had enough clues from the conduct of the patient Renfield!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113800,\n            \"He thinks that in the meantime I should see Renfield, as hitherto he has been a sort of index to the coming and going of the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113873,\n            \"I found Renfield sitting placidly in his room with his hands folded, smiling benignly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113889,\n            \"At the moment he seemed as sane as any one I ever saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113903,\n            \"I sat down and talked with him on a lot of subjects, all of which he treated naturally.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113923,\n            \"He then, of his own accord, spoke of going home, a subject he has never mentioned to my knowledge during his sojourn here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113964,\n            \"I believe that, had I not had the chat with Harker and read the letters and the dates of his outbursts, I should have been prepared to sign for him after a brief time of observation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114035,\n            \"Can it be that his instinct is satisfied as to the vampire\\u2019s ultimate triumph?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114134,\n            \"I mistrust these quiet moods of his;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            114142,\n            \"so I have given the attendant a hint to look closely after him, and to have a strait-waistcoat ready in case of need.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115244,\n            \"I shall try to see the carter who took away the boxes from Carfax when Renfield attacked them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115318,\n            \"It is, I suppose, the reaction from the haunting fear which I have had: that this terrible affair and the reopening of his old wound might act detrimentally on Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123012,\n            \"- Just as we were about to leave the house, an urgent message was brought to me from Renfield to know if I would see him at once, as he had something of the utmost importance to say to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123055,\n            \"I told the messenger to say that I would attend to his wishes in the morning;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123080,\n            \"The attendant added:-\\u201cHe seems very importunate, sir.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123093,\n            \"I have never seen him so eager.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123101,\n            \"I don\\u2019t know but what, if you don\\u2019t see him soon, he will have one of his violent fits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123156,\n            \"and I asked the others to wait a few minutes for me, as I had to go and see my \\u201cpatient.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123195,\n            \"\\u201cHis case in your diary interest me much, and it had bearing, too, now and again on our case.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123219,\n            \"I should much like to see him, and especial when his mind is disturbed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123277,\n            \"We found him in a state of considerable excitement, but far more rational in his speech and manner than I had ever seen him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123303,\n            \"There was an unusual understanding of himself, which was unlike anything I had ever met with in a lunatic;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123358,\n            \"His request was that I would at once release him from the asylum and send him home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124404,\n            \"He said to Renfield in a tone which did not surprise me at the time, but only when I thought of it afterwards-for it was as of one addressing an equal:-\\u201cCan you not tell frankly your real reason for wishing to be free to-night?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124458,\n            \"I will undertake that if you will satisfy even me-a stranger, without prejudice, and with the habit of keeping an open mind-Dr. Seward will give you, at his own risk and on his own responsibility, the privilege you seek.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124539,\n            \"You claim the privilege of reason in the highest degree, since you seek to impress us with your complete reasonableness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124561,\n            \"You do this, whose sanity we have reason to doubt, since you are not yet released from medical treatment for this very defect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124587,\n            \"If you will not help us in our effort to choose the wisest course, how can we perform the duty which you yourself put upon us?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124622,\n            \"and if we can we shall aid you to achieve your wish.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128643,\n            \"\\u201d The house was silent when we got back, save for some poor creature who was screaming away in one of the distant wards, and a low, moaning sound from Renfield\\u2019s room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136199,\n            \"- I am puzzled afresh about Renfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136207,\n            \"His moods change so rapidly that I find it difficult to keep touch of them, and as they always mean something more than his own well-being, they form a more than interesting study.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136245,\n            \"This morning, when I went to see him after his repulse of Van Helsing, his manner was that of a man commanding destiny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136296,\n            \"he was in the clouds and looked down on all the weaknesses and wants of us poor mortals.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136315,\n            \"I thought I would improve the occasion and learn something, so I asked him:-\\u201cWhat about the flies these times?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136340,\n            \"\\u201d He smiled on me in quite a superior sort of way-such a smile as would have become the face of Malvolio-as he answered me:-\\u201cThe fly, my dear sir, has one striking feature;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136410,\n            \"\\u201d I thought I would push his analogy to its utmost logically, so I said quickly:-\\u201cOh, it is a soul you are after now, is it?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136444,\n            \"\\u201d His madness foiled his reason, and a puzzled look spread over his face as, shaking his head with a decision which I had but seldom seen in him, he said:-\\u201cOh, no, oh no!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136542,\n            \"\\u201d This puzzled me a little, so I drew him on:-\\u201cThen you command life;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136562,\n            \"you are a god, I suppose?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136583,\n            \"Far be it from me to arrogate to myself the attributes of the Deity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136598,\n            \"I am not even concerned in His especially spiritual doings.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136609,\n            \"If I may state my intellectual position I am, so far as concerns things purely terrestrial, somewhat in the position which Enoch occupied spiritually!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136656,\n            \"so I had to ask a simple question, though I felt that by so doing I was lowering myself in the eyes of the lunatic:-\\u201cAnd why with Enoch?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136714,\n            \"so I harked back to what he had denied:-\\u201cSo you don\\u2019t care about life and you don\\u2019t want souls.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136745,\n            \"\\u201d I put my question quickly and somewhat sternly, on purpose to disconcert him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136765,\n            \"for an instant he unconsciously relapsed into his old servile manner, bent low before me, and actually fawned upon me as he replied:-\\u201cI don\\u2019t want any souls, indeed, indeed!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136821,\n            \"they would be no manner of use to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136831,\n            \"I couldn\\u2019t eat them or--\\u201dHe suddenly stopped and the old cunning look spread over his face, like a wind-sweep on the surface of the water.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136902,\n            \"I have friends-good friends-like you, Dr. Seward \\\";\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136940,\n            \"\\u201d I think that through the cloudiness of his insanity he saw some antagonism in me, for he at once fell back on the last refuge of such as he-a dogged silence.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136976,\n            \"After a short time I saw that for the present it was useless to speak to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136994,\n            \"He was sulky, and so I came away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137004,\n            \"Later in the day he sent for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137013,\n            \"Ordinarily I would not have come without special reason, but just at present I am so interested in him that I would gladly make an effort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137119,\n            \"I would have taken him with me to see the patient, only I thought that after his last repulse he might not care to go again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137147,\n            \"There was also another reason: Renfield might not speak so freely before a third person as when he and I were alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137171,\n            \"I found him sitting out in the middle of the floor on his stool, a pose which is generally indicative of some mental energy on his part.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137200,\n            \"When I came in, he said at once, as though the question had been waiting on his lips:-\\u201cWhat about souls?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137318,\n            \"The matter seemed preying on his mind, and so I determined to use it-to \\u201cbe cruel only to be kind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137343,\n            \"\\u201d So I said:-\\u201cYou like life, and you want life?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137400,\n            \"\\u201d This seemed to puzzle him, so I followed it up:-\\u201cA nice time you\\u2019ll have some time when you\\u2019re flying out there, with the souls of thousands of flies and spiders and birds and cats buzzing and twittering and miauing all round you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137454,\n            \"You\\u2019ve got their lives, you know, and you must put up with their souls!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137473,\n            \"\\u201d Something seemed to affect his imagination, for he put his fingers to his ears and shut his eyes, screwing them up tightly just as a small boy does when his face is being soaped.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137557,\n            \"It was evident that he was undergoing some process of mental disturbance, and, knowing how his past moods had interpreted things seemingly foreign to himself, I thought I would enter into his mind as well as I could and go with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137603,\n            \"The first step was to restore confidence, so I asked him, speaking pretty loud so that he would hear me through his closed ears:-\\u201cWould you like some sugar to get your flies round again?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137678,\n            \"\\u201d After a pause he added, \\u201cBut I don\\u2019t want their souls buzzing round me, all the same.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137724,\n            \"There isn\\u2019t anything in them to eat or \\\"-he stopped suddenly, as though reminded of a forbidden topic.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137753,\n            \"\\u201d I thought to myself, \\u201cthis is the second time he has suddenly stopped at the word \\u2018 drink \\u2019;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137781,\n            \"\\u201d Renfield seemed himself aware of having made a lapse, for he hurried on, as though to distract my attention from it:-\\u201cI don\\u2019t take any stock at all in such matters.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137859,\n            \"You might as well ask a man to eat molecules with a pair of chop-sticks, as to try to interest me about the lesser carnivora, when I know of what is before me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137906,\n            \"\\u201cYou want big things that you can make your teeth meet in?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137938,\n            \"\\u201d He was getting too wide awake, so I thought I would press him hard.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137974,\n            \"\\u201d The effect I desired was obtained, for he at once fell from his high-horse and became a child again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138061,\n            \"\\u201cWhy do you plague me about souls?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138092,\n            \"\\u201d He looked so hostile that I thought he was in for another homicidal fit, so I blew my whistle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138114,\n            \"The instant, however, that I did so he became calm, and said apologetically:-\\u201cForgive me, Doctor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138164,\n            \"If you only knew the problem I have to face, and that I am working out, you would pity, and tolerate, and pardon me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138219,\n            \"I am sure you will understand!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138250,\n            \"Renfield watched them go;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138255,\n            \"when the door was closed he said, with considerable dignity and sweetness:-\\u201cDr. Seward, you have been very considerate towards me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138283,\n            \"Believe me that I am very, very grateful to you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138295,\n            \"\\u201d I thought it well to leave him in this mood, and so I came away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138390,\n            \"Despises the meaner forms of life altogether, though he dreads being haunted by their souls.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138458,\n            \"the Count has been to him, and there is some new scheme of terror afoot!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138497,\n            \"and, after thinking the matter over for a while asked me to take him to Renfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138519,\n            \"As we came to the door we heard the lunatic within singing gaily, as he used to do in the time which now seems so long ago.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138548,\n            \"When we entered we saw with amazement that he had spread out his sugar as of old;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138582,\n            \"We tried to make him talk of the subject of our previous conversation, but he would not attend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138602,\n            \"He went on with his singing, just as though we had not been present.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138654,\n            \"we must watch him to-night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138749,\n            \"The purchaser is a foreign nobleman, Count de Ville, who effected the purchase himself paying the purchase money in notes \\u2018 over the counter,\\u2019if your Lordship will pardon us using so vulgar an expression.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138831,\n            \"- I placed a man in the corridor last night, and told him to make an accurate note of any sound he might hear from Renfield\\u2019s room, and gave him instructions that if there should be anything strange he was to call me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138912,\n            \"Harker was the only one who had any result, and we are in great hopes that his clue may be an important one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138937,\n            \"Before going to bed I went round to the patient\\u2019s room and looked in through the observation trap.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138973,\n            \"This morning the man on duty reported to me that a little after midnight he was restless and kept saying his prayers somewhat loudly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139015,\n            \"There was something about his manner so suspicious that I asked him point blank if he had been asleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139259,\n            \"His moods have so followed the doings of the Count, that the coming destruction of the monster may be carried to him in some subtle way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139287,\n            \"If we could only get some hint as to what passed in his mind, between the time of my argument with him to-day and his resumption of fly-catching, it might afford us a valuable clue.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139359,\n            \"The attendant came bursting into my room and told me that Renfield had somehow met with some accident.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139378,\n            \"He had heard him yell;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139384,\n            \"and when he went to him found him lying on his face on the floor, all covered with blood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139469,\n            \"When I came to Renfield\\u2019s room I found him lying on the floor on his left side in a glittering pool of blood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139495,\n            \"When I went to move him, it became at once apparent that he had received some terrible injuries;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139573,\n            \"The attendant who was kneeling beside the body said to me as we turned him over:-\\u201cI think, sir, his back is broken.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139696,\n            \"And I suppose he might have broke his neck by falling out of bed, if he got in an awkward kink.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139829,\n            \"When he saw Renfield on the ground, he looked keenly at him a moment, and then turned to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139968,\n            \"for, almost before he looked at the patient, he whispered to me:-\\u201cSend the attendant away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139990,\n            \"We must be alone with him when he becomes conscious, after the operation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140057,\n            \"\\u201d The man withdrew, and we went into a strict examination of the patient.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140363,\n            \"\\u201d I told him briefly, and added that we expected he would recover consciousness after the operation-for a short time, at all events.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140505,\n            \"I dreaded the words that Renfield might speak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140942,\n            \"but even with the effort his eyes seemed to grow glassy again so I gently put it back.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140961,\n            \"Then Van Helsing said in a quiet grave tone:-\\u201cTell us your dream, Mr. Renfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140982,\n            \"\\u201d As he heard the voice his face brightened, through its mutilation, and he said:-\\u201cThat is Dr. Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141029,\n            \"and I shall try to tell you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141037,\n            \"I dreamed \\\"-he stopped and seemed fainting, I called quietly to Quincey-\\\" The brandy-it is in my study-quick!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141084,\n            \"We moistened the parched lips, and the patient quickly revived.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141096,\n            \"It seemed, however, that his poor injured brain had been working in the interval, for, when he was quite conscious, he looked at me piercingly with an agonised confusion which I shall never forget, and said:-\\u201cI must not deceive myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142067,\n            \"I was about to call him back to the point, but Van Helsing whispered to me: \\u201cLet him go on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142365,\n            \"he went on:-\\u201cI didn\\u2019t know that she was here till she spoke;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142393,\n            \"I don\\u2019t care for the pale people;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142403,\n            \"I like them with lots of blood in them, and hers had all seemed to have run out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147094,\n            \"When Dr. Van Helsing and Dr. Seward had come back from seeing poor Renfield, we went gravely into what was to be done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147121,\n            \"First, Dr. Seward told us that when he and Dr. Van Helsing had gone down to the room below they had found Renfield lying on the floor, all in a heap.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147194,\n            \"He said that he had been sitting down-he confessed to half dozing-when he heard loud voices in the room, and then Renfield had called out loudly several times, \\u201cGod!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147235,\n            \"\\u201d after that there was a sound of falling, and when he entered the room he found him lying on the floor, face down, just as the doctors had seen him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147324,\n            \"He could swear to it, if required, that the word \\u201cGod\\u201dwas spoken by the patient.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 12]\": [\n        [\n            74855,\n            \"\\u201d The voice came from the sofa across the room, and its tones brought relief and joy to my heart, for they were those of Quincey Morris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74885,\n            \"Van Helsing started angrily at the first sound, but his face softened and a glad look came into his eyes as I cried out: \\u201cQuincey Morris!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75017,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing strode forward, and took his hand, looking him straight in the eyes as he said:-\\u201cA brave man\\u2019s blood is the best thing on this earth when a woman is in trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75060,\n            \"You\\u2019re a man and no mistake.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75206,\n            \"The Professor watched whilst I went downstairs with Quincey Morris, and sent one of the maids to pay off one of the cabmen who were waiting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75234,\n            \"I left Quincey lying down after having a glass of wine, and told the cook to get ready a good breakfast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75710,\n            \"\\u201d In the hall I met Quincey Morris, with a telegram for Arthur telling him that Mrs. Westenra was dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75757,\n            \"I told him where I was going, and he hurried me out, but as I was going said:-\\u201cWhen you come back, Jack, may I have two words with you all to ourselves?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75837,\n            \"When I got back Quincey was waiting for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75847,\n            \"I told him I would see him as soon as I knew about Lucy, and went up to her room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75914,\n            \"So I went down to Quincey and took him into the breakfast-room, where the blinds were not drawn down, and which was a little more cheerful, or rather less cheerless, than the other rooms.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75955,\n            \"When we were alone, he said to me:-\\u201cJack Seward, I don\\u2019t want to shove myself in anywhere where I\\u2019ve no right to be;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79157,\n            \"They are as follows:-Jack Smollet, of Dudding\\u2019s Rents, King George\\u2019s Road, Great Walworth, and Thomas Snelling, Peter Farley\\u2019s Row, Guide Court, Bethnal Green.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87483,\n            \"I believe in my heart of hearts that he suffered as much about Lucy\\u2019s death as any of us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87505,\n            \"but he bore himself through it like a moral Viking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87751,\n            \"Arthur and Quincey went away together to the station, and Van Helsing and I came on here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103145,\n            \"Quincey and I talked it over;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103420,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI thank you, sir,\\u201dsaid Van Helsing proudly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103434,\n            \"\\u201cI have done myself the honour of counting you one trusting friend, and such endorsement is dear to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105713,\n            \"Quincey Morris was phlegmatic in the way of a man who accepts all things, and accepts them in the spirit of cool bravery, with hazard of all he has to stake.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105894,\n            \"Arthur and Quincey drew near also, as they too were curious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107245,\n            \"Quincey and I simultaneously moved towards him, and took his arms.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107592,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur and Quincey came home with me, and we tried to cheer each other on the way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107641,\n            \"- A little before twelve o\\u2019clock we three-Arthur, Quincey Morris, and myself-called for the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108214,\n            \"To me, a doctor\\u2019s preparations for work of any kind are stimulating and bracing, but the effect of these things on both Arthur and Quincey was to cause them a sort of consternation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109093,\n            \"Van Helsing opened his missal and began to read, and Quincey and I followed as well as we could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109817,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur bent and kissed her, and then we sent him and Quincey out of the tomb;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118456,\n            \"Poor Art seemed more cheerful than he has been since Lucy first took ill, and Quincey is more like his own bright self than he has been for many a long day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118576,\n            \"And Arthur and my friend Quincey, they are with you, too?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135904,\n            \"I confess I don\\u2019t see how we are going to get in unless that agency duck can find us a key of some sort;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135962,\n            \"By-and-by he stopped and said, turning from one to another of us:-\\u201cQuincey\\u2019s head is level.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137064,\n            \"and so are Lord Godalming and Quincey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140363,\n            \"\\u201d I told him briefly, and added that we expected he would recover consciousness after the operation-for a short time, at all events.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141037,\n            \"I dreamed \\\"-he stopped and seemed fainting, I called quietly to Quincey-\\\" The brandy-it is in my study-quick!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141473,\n            \"Renfield proceeded:-\\u201cHe came up to the window in the mist, as I had seen him often before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142874,\n            \"Art and Quincey held back, and the latter said:-\\u201cShould we disturb her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143487,\n            \"and when the gaslight sprang up under Quincey\\u2019s match, we saw nothing but a faint vapour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143835,\n            \"and as I looked I could see Quincey Morris run across the lawn and hide himself in the shadow of a great yew-tree.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143861,\n            \"It puzzled me to think why he was doing this;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            150063,\n            \"that the two doctors and I should remain there, whilst Lord Godalming and Quincey found the lairs at Walworth and Mile End and destroyed them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152088,\n            \"- Just before we reached Fenchurch Street Lord Godalming said to me:-\\u201cQuincey and I will find a locksmith.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154347,\n            \"By my clock it is one hour and already, if all be well, friend Arthur and Quincey are on their way to us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154810,\n            \"What we must hope for is that my Lord Arthur and Quincey arrive first.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155031,\n            \"\\u201d We were silent for a minute, and then Quincey said:-\\u201cThere\\u2019s nothing to do but to wait here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155343,\n            \"In all our hunting parties and adventures in different parts of the world, Quincey Morris had always been the one to arrange the plan of action, and Arthur and I had been accustomed to obey him implicitly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157754,\n            \"When they had retired, Quincey, Godalming, and I arranged that we should sit up, dividing the night between us, and watch over the safety of the poor stricken lady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157789,\n            \"The first watch falls to Quincey, so the rest of us shall be off to bed as soon as we can.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160986,\n            \"Present: Professor Van Helsing, Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, Mr. Quincey Morris, Jonathan Harker, Mina Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161302,\n            \"and when Quincey give him something from his pocket which crackle as he roll it up, and put it in a so small bag which he have hid deep in his clothing, he still better fellow and humble servant to us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165372,\n            \"\\u201d Here Quincey Morris added:-\\u201cI understand that the Count comes from a wolf country, and it may be that he shall get there before us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165403,\n            \"I propose that we add Winchesters to our armament.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167234,\n            \"\\u201d I grasped his hand instinctively and found it as firm as a piece of steel.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167251,\n            \"I think he understood my look;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167258,\n            \"I hope he did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167278,\n            \"Quincey is all man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167283,\n            \"God bless him for it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168542,\n            \"\\u201d She looked again questioningly, but this time avoided her husband\\u2019s face.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168563,\n            \"he nodded, and her face lit up.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168597,\n            \"You must promise me, one and all-even you, my beloved husband-that, should the time come, you will kill me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168724,\n            \"He knelt down before her and taking her hand in his said solemnly:-\\u201cI\\u2019m only a rough fellow, who hasn\\u2019t, perhaps, lived as a man should to win such a distinction, but I swear to you by all that I hold sacred and dear that, should the time ever come, I shall not flinch from the duty that you have set us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168800,\n            \"And I promise you, too, that I shall make all certain, for if I am only doubtful I shall take it that the time has come!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            168836,\n            \"\\u201d was all she could say amid her fast-falling tears, as, bending over, she kissed his hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175632,\n            \"Quincey raised his eyebrows slightly and looked at her intently, whilst Harker\\u2019s hand instinctively closed round the hilt of his Kukri.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180510,\n            \"\\u201d Dr. Seward said:-\\u201cI think I had better go with Quincey.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180864,\n            \"Now let me say that what I would is this: while you, my Lord Godalming and friend Jonathan go in your so swift little steamboat up the river, and whilst John and Quincey guard the bank where perchance he might be landed, I will take Madam Mina right into the heart of the enemy\\u2019s country.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 13]\": [\n        [\n            55629,\n            \"\\u201d Telegram, Arthur Holmwood to Seward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55674,\n            \"\\u201d Letter from Dr. Seward to Arthur Holmwood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59245,\n            \"\\u201d CHAPTER X Letter, Dr. Seward to Hon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59459,\n            \"In haste Yours ever, \\u201cJohn Seward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71742,\n            \"I was not afraid, but I did wish that Dr. Seward was in the next room-as Dr. Van Helsing said he would be-so that I might have called him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74946,\n            \"\\u201d He handed me a telegram:-\\u201cHave not heard from Seward for three days, and am terribly anxious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111020,\n            \"At the door I paused a moment, for I thought I heard him talking with some one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111039,\n            \"As, however, he had pressed me to be quick, I knocked at the door, and on his calling out, \\u201cCome in,\\u201dI entered.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111071,\n            \"To my intense surprise, there was no one with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111083,\n            \"He was quite alone, and on the table opposite him was what I knew at once from the description to be a phonograph.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111119,\n            \"\\u201cI hope I did not keep you waiting,\\u201dI said;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111133,\n            \"\\u201cbut I stayed at the door as I heard you talking, and thought there was some one with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111179,\n            \"\\u201d I asked him in surprise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111291,\n            \"and as it is entirely-almost entirely-about my cases, it may be awkward-that is, I mean--\\u201dHe stopped, and I tried to help him out of his embarrassment:-\\u201cYou helped to attend dear Lucy at the end.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111373,\n            \"\\u201d To my surprise, he answered, with a horrorstruck look in his face:-\\u201cTell you of her death?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111423,\n            \"Again he paused, and I could see that he was trying to invent an excuse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111440,\n            \"At length he stammered out:-\\u201cYou see, I do not know how to pick out any particular part of the diary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111466,\n            \"\\u201d Even while he was speaking an idea dawned upon him, and he said with unconscious simplicity, in a different voice, and with the na\\u00efvet\\u00e9 of a child: \\u201cThat\\u2019s quite true, upon my honour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111512,\n            \"\\u201d I could not but smile, at which he grimaced.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111536,\n            \"\\u201cBut do you know that, although I have kept the diary for months past, it never once struck me how I was going to find any particular part of it in case I wanted to look it up?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111578,\n            \"\\u201d By this time my mind was made up that the diary of a doctor who attended Lucy might have something to add to the sum of our knowledge of that terrible Being, and I said boldly:-\\u201cThen, Dr. Seward, you had better let me copy it out for you on my typewriter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111659,\n            \"For all the world, I wouldn\\u2019t let you know that terrible story!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111723,\n            \"His eyes caught the look in mine, and, without his thinking, followed their direction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111741,\n            \"As they saw the parcel he realised my meaning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111751,\n            \"\\u201cYou do not know me,\\u201dI said.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111762,\n            \"\\u201cWhen you have read those papers-my own diary and my husband\\u2019s also, which I have typed-you will know me better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111807,\n            \"but, of course, you do not know me-yet;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111820,\n            \"and I must not expect you to trust me so far.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111832,\n            \"\\u201d He is certainly a man of noble nature;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111850,\n            \"He stood up and opened a large drawer, in which were arranged in order a number of hollow cylinders of metal covered with dark wax, and said:-\\u201cYou are quite right.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111887,\n            \"I did not trust you because I did not know you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111899,\n            \"But I know you now;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111905,\n            \"and let me say that I should have known you long ago.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111918,\n            \"I know that Lucy told you of me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111934,\n            \"May I make the only atonement in my power?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112069,\n            \"- I was so absorbed in that wonderful diary of Jonathan Harker and that other of his wife that I let the time run on without thinking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112796,\n            \"- After dinner I came with Dr. Seward to his study.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112809,\n            \"He brought back the phonograph from my room, and I took my typewriter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112824,\n            \"He placed me in a comfortable chair, and arranged the phonograph so that I could touch it without getting up, and showed me how to stop it in case I should want to pause.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112861,\n            \"Then he very thoughtfully took a chair, with his back to me, so that I might be as free as possible, and began to read.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112938,\n            \"When Dr. Seward saw me he jumped up with a horrified exclamation, and hurriedly taking a case-bottle from a cupboard, gave me some brandy, which in a few minutes somewhat restored me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113083,\n            \"I took the cover off my typewriter, and said to Dr. Seward:-\\u201cLet me write this all out now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113174,\n            \"You tell me that Lord Godalming and Mr. Morris are coming too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113199,\n            \"\\u201d He accordingly set the phonograph at a slow pace, and I began to typewrite from the beginning of the seventh cylinder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113246,\n            \"It was late when I got through, but Dr. Seward went about his work of going his round of the patients;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113270,\n            \"when he had finished he came back and sat near me, reading, so that I did not feel too lonely whilst I worked.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113319,\n            \"Before I left him I remembered what Jonathan put in his diary of the Professor\\u2019s perturbation at reading something in an evening paper at the station at Exeter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113350,\n            \"so, seeing that Dr. Seward keeps his newspapers, I borrowed the files of \\u201cThe Westminster Gazette\\u201dand \\u201cThe Pall Mall Gazette,\\u201dand took them to my room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117531,\n            \"\\u201cYou see, I know you, for Dr. Seward has told me of you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117584,\n            \"then, to my intense astonishment, he said:-\\u201cYou\\u2019re not the girl the doctor wanted to marry, are you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117641,\n            \"I have a husband of my own, to whom I was married before I ever saw Dr. Seward, or he me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117681,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cMy husband and I are staying on a visit with Dr. Seward.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117817,\n            \"He replied to her with as much courtesy and respect as he had shown contempt to me:-\\u201cYou will, of course, understand, Mrs. Harker, that when a man is so loved and honoured as our host is, everything regarding him is of interest in our little community.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117874,\n            \"Dr. Seward is loved not only by his household and his friends, but even by his patients, who, being some of them hardly in mental equilibrium, are apt to distort causes and effects.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119360,\n            \"- When we met in Dr. Seward\\u2019s study two hours after dinner, which had been at six o\\u2019clock, we unconsciously formed a sort of board or committee.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119395,\n            \"Professor Van Helsing took the head of the table, to which Dr. Seward motioned him as he came into the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119444,\n            \"Opposite us were Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, and Mr. Morris-Lord Godalming being next the Professor, and Dr. Seward in the centre.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            123991,\n            \"This did not at all satisfy him, for he said quickly:-\\u201cBut I fear, Dr. Seward, that you hardly apprehend my wish.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124065,\n            \"I am sure it is only necessary to put before so admirable a practitioner as Dr. Seward so simple, yet so momentous a wish, to ensure its fulfilment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124458,\n            \"I will undertake that if you will satisfy even me-a stranger, without prejudice, and with the habit of keeping an open mind-Dr. Seward will give you, at his own risk and on his own responsibility, the privilege you seek.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188100,\n            \"Oh, if only Morris and Seward were with us.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 14]\": [\n        [\n            117056,\n            \"- I got home at five o\\u2019clock, and found that Godalming and Morris had not only arrived, but had already studied the transcript of the various diaries and letters which Harker and his wonderful wife had made and arranged.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138677,\n            \"\\u201cMy Lord, \\u201cWe are at all times only too happy to meet your wishes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            138695,\n            \"We beg, with regard to the desire of your Lordship, expressed by Mr. Harker on your behalf, to supply the following information concerning the sale and purchase of No.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144838,\n            \"To which Lord Godalming answered:-\\u201cI could not see him anywhere in the passage, or in any of our rooms.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144863,\n            \"I looked in the study but, though he had been there, he had gone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144880,\n            \"He had, however--\\u201dHe stopped suddenly, looking at the poor drooping figure on the bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145020,\n            \"\\u201d His face lit for a moment, but fell again as he went on: \\u201cI ran downstairs then, but could see no sign of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            156395,\n            \"Godalming and Morris had rushed out into the yard, and Harker had lowered himself from the window to follow the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157754,\n            \"When they had retired, Quincey, Godalming, and I arranged that we should sit up, dividing the night between us, and watch over the safety of the poor stricken lady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158660,\n            \"In two or three minutes later Van Helsing was in the room in his dressing-gown, and Mr. Morris and Lord Godalming were with Dr. Seward at the door asking questions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            169838,\n            \"Lord Godalming went to the Consulate to see if any telegram had arrived for him, whilst the rest of us came on to this hotel-\\\" the Odessus.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170143,\n            \"He had four telegrams, one each day since we started, and all to the same effect: that the Czarina Catherine had not been reported to Lloyd\\u2019s from anywhere.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170177,\n            \"He had arranged before leaving London that his agent should send him every day a telegram saying if the ship had been reported.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170201,\n            \"He was to have a message even if she were not reported, so that he might be sure that there was a watch being kept at the other end of the wire.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170596,\n            \"Godalming told the shippers that he fancied that the box sent aboard might contain something stolen from a friend of his, and got a half consent that he might open it at his own risk.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170633,\n            \"The owner gave him a paper telling the Captain to give him every facility in doing whatever he chose on board the ship, and also a similar authorisation to his agent at Varna.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170668,\n            \"We have seen the agent, who was much impressed with Godalming\\u2019s kindly manner to him, and we are all satisfied that whatever he can do to aid our wishes will be done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170745,\n            \"Morris and Godalming and I shall prevent interference, even if we have to use the arms which we shall have ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170955,\n            \"Rufus Smith, Lloyd\\u2019s, London, to Lord Godalming, care of H.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171027,\n            \"We were all wild with excitement yesterday when Godalming got his telegram from Lloyd\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181628,\n            \"I felt so thankful that Lord Godalming is rich, and that both he and Mr. Morris, who also has plenty of money, are willing to spend it so freely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182017,\n            \"- I am writing this in the light from the furnace door of the steam launch: Lord Godalming is firing up.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182190,\n            \"Lord Godalming tells me to sleep for a while, as it is enough for the present for one to be on watch.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182851,\n            \"God bless him for all his goodness to poor dear Mina and me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182876,\n            \"That good fellow would not wake me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182884,\n            \"He says it would have been a sin to, for I slept peacefully and was forgetting my trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182904,\n            \"It seems brutally selfish to me to have slept so long, and let him watch all night;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            182937,\n            \"and, as I sit here and watch him sleeping, I can do all that is necessary both as to minding the engine, steering, and keeping watch.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183373,\n            \"Godalming is an amateur fitter himself, and evidently it was he who put the launch in trim again.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 15]\": [\n        [\n            49455,\n            \"Before she answered, that sweet, puckered look came into her forehead, which Arthur-I call him Arthur from her habit-says he loves;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49484,\n            \"and, indeed, I don\\u2019t wonder that he does.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53906,\n            \"Arthur says I am getting fat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53913,\n            \"By the way, I forgot to tell you that Arthur is here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53947,\n            \"and I love him more than ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53955,\n            \"He tells me that he loves me more, but I doubt that, for at first he told me that he couldn\\u2019t love me more than he did then.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55092,\n            \"When Arthur came to lunch he looked quite grieved when he saw me, and I hadn\\u2019t the spirit to try to be cheerful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55294,\n            \"I shall try to cheer up when Arthur comes, or else I know he will be miserable to see me so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56088,\n            \"\\u2018 Tell Arthur everything you choose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            56095,\n            \"I do not care for myself, but all for him!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60753,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI am younger and stronger, Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60809,\n            \"When we reached the hall the maid had just opened the door, and Arthur was stepping quickly in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60829,\n            \"He rushed up to me, saying in an eager whisper:-\\u201cJack, I was so anxious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60850,\n            \"I read between the lines of your letter, and have been in an agony.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60866,\n            \"The dad was better, so I ran down here to see for myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60890,\n            \"I am so thankful to you, sir, for coming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60902,\n            \"\\u201d When first the Professor\\u2019s eye had lit upon him he had been angry at his interruption at such a time;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60926,\n            \"but now, as he took in his stalwart proportions and recognised the strong young manhood which seemed to emanate from him, his eyes gleamed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60953,\n            \"Without a pause he said to him gravely as he held out his hand:-\\u201cSir, you have come in time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60978,\n            \"You are the lover of our dear miss.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61029,\n            \"You can do more than any that live, and your courage is your best help.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61058,\n            \"\\u201cTell me, and I shall do it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61196,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur looked bewildered, and the Professor went on by explaining in a kindly way:-\\u201cYoung miss is bad, very bad.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61272,\n            \"John was to give his blood, as he is the more young and strong than me \\\"-here Arthur took my hand and wrung it hard in silence-\\\" but, now you are here, you are more good than us, old or young, who toil much in the world of thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61346,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur turned to him and said:-\\u201cIf you only knew how gladly I would die for her you would understand--\\u201dHe stopped, with a sort of choke in his voice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61728,\n            \"Van Helsing turning to me, said: \\u201cHe is so young and strong and of blood so pure that we need not defibrinate it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61807,\n            \"After a bit I began to grow anxious, for the loss of blood was telling on Arthur, strong man as he was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61832,\n            \"It gave me an idea of what a terrible strain Lucy\\u2019s system must have undergone that what weakened Arthur only partially restored her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61914,\n            \"You attend him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61924,\n            \"\\u201d When all was over I could see how much Arthur was weakened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61938,\n            \"I dressed the wound and took his arm to bring him away, when Van Helsing spoke without turning round-the man seems to have eyes in the back of his head:-\\u201cThe brave lover, I think, deserve another kiss, which he shall have presently.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62059,\n            \"Arthur did not notice it, but I could hear the deep hiss of indrawn breath which is one of Van Helsing\\u2019s ways of betraying emotion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62088,\n            \"He said nothing at the moment, but turned to me, saying: \\u201cNow take down our brave young lover, give him of the port wine, and let him lie down a while.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62246,\n            \"\\u201d When Arthur had gone I went back to the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63272,\n            \"I sent a short wire to Van Helsing and to Arthur, telling them of the excellent result of the operation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63755,\n            \"Somehow Arthur feels very, very close to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63765,\n            \"I seem to feel his presence warm about me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65593,\n            \"\\u201cNay, but they are not to take in a decoction or in nauseous form, so you need not snub that so charming nose, or I shall point out to my friend Arthur what woes he may have to endure in seeing so much beauty that he so loves so much distort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65649,\n            \"Aha, my pretty miss, that bring the so nice nose all straight again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65676,\n            \"I put him in your window, I make pretty wreath, and hang him round your neck, so that you sleep well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            68166,\n            \"Thank God for mother\\u2019s sake, and dear Arthur\\u2019s, and for all our friends who have been so kind!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72974,\n            \"Good-bye, dear Arthur, if I should not survive this night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            72989,\n            \"God keep you, dear, and God help me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75710,\n            \"\\u201d In the hall I met Quincey Morris, with a telegram for Arthur telling him that Mrs. Westenra was dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75757,\n            \"I told him where I was going, and he hurried me out, but as I was going said:-\\u201cWhen you come back, Jack, may I have two words with you all to ourselves?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75955,\n            \"When we were alone, he said to me:-\\u201cJack Seward, I don\\u2019t want to shove myself in anywhere where I\\u2019ve no right to be;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75996,\n            \"You know I loved that girl and wanted to marry her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76139,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThat\\u2019s so,\\u201dI said, and he went on:-\\u201cI take it that both you and Van Helsing had done already what I did to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76302,\n            \"Jack, if you may tell me without betraying confidence, Arthur was the first, is not that so?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76476,\n            \"Then I guess, Jack Seward, that that poor pretty creature that we all love has had put into her veins within that time the blood of four strong men.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76643,\n            \"\\u201cYou and the Dutchman will tell me what to do, and I\\u2019ll do it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77147,\n            \"In the afternoon she asked for Arthur, and we telegraphed for him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77209,\n            \"When he saw her, Arthur was simply choking with emotion, and none of us could speak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77279,\n            \"she rallied a little, and spoke to him more brightly than she had done since we arrived.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77405,\n            \"Letter, Mina Harker to Lucy Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77423,\n            \"\\u201cMy dearest Lucy,-\\u201cIt seems an age since I heard from you, or indeed since I wrote.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77446,\n            \"You will pardon me, I know, for all my faults when you have read all my budget of news.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77530,\n            \"After dinner Mr. Hawkins said:-\\u201c\\u2018 My dears, I want to drink your health and prosperity;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79820,\n            \"We wanted Arthur to go to rest also, but he refused at first.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79835,\n            \"It was only when I told him that we should want him to help us during the day, and that we must not all break down for want of rest, lest Lucy should suffer, that he agreed to go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80004,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur went off with him, casting back a longing look on Lucy\\u2019s face, which lay in her pillow, almost whiter than the lawn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80685,\n            \"he trusts us, and we have promised him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80820,\n            \"\\u201cCome,\\u201dI said, \\u201cmy dear old fellow, summon all your fortitude: it will be best and easiest for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80904,\n            \"When we came into the room she opened her eyes, and seeing him, whispered softly:-\\u201cArthur!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80926,\n            \"Oh, my love, I am so glad you have come!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80939,\n            \"\\u201d He was stooping to kiss her, when Van Helsing motioned him back.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80975,\n            \"\\u201d So Arthur took her hand and knelt beside her, and she looked her best, with all the soft lines matching the angelic beauty of her eyes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81082,\n            \"In a sort of sleep-waking, vague, unconscious way she opened her eyes, which were now dull and hard at once, and said in a soft, voluptuous voice, such as I had never heard from her lips:-\\u201cArthur!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81131,\n            \"Oh, my love, I am so glad you have come!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81147,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur bent eagerly over to kiss her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81156,\n            \"but at that instant Van Helsing, who, like me, had been startled by her voice, swooped upon him, and catching him by the neck with both hands, dragged him back with a fury of strength which I never thought he could have possessed, and actually hurled him almost across the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81225,\n            \"\\u201cnot for your living soul and hers!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81401,\n            \"Oh, guard him, and give me peace!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81438,\n            \"Then he turned to Arthur, and said to him: \\u201cCome, my child, take her hand in yours, and kiss her on the forehead, and only once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81957,\n            \"and as Arthur had to be back the next day to attend at his father\\u2019s funeral, we were unable to notify any one who should have been bidden.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82941,\n            \"I would like to do it to-night, but for Arthur I must not;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82958,\n            \"he will be free after his father\\u2019s funeral to-morrow, and he will want to see her-to see it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83248,\n            \"Were you not amazed, nay horrified, when I would not let Arthur kiss his love-though she was dying-and snatched him away by all my strength?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84374,\n            \"Arthur was expected at five o\\u2019clock, so a little before that time we visited the death-chamber.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84490,\n            \"The undertaker seemed shocked at his own stupidity and exerted himself to restore things to the condition in which we left them the night before, so that when Arthur came such shocks to his feelings as we could avoid were saved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84627,\n            \"The Professor noticed it, too, and motioned me to bring him upstairs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84946,\n            \"At last, after a long pause, he said to me in a faint whisper:-\\u201cJack, is she really dead?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85181,\n            \"When he came out of the room again I told him of Arthur\\u2019s question, and he replied:-\\u201cI am not surprised.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85266,\n            \"but Arthur interrupted him:-\\u201cNo, no, not that, for God\\u2019s sake!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85335,\n            \"I must not call you \\u2018 Mr.,\\u2019and I have grown to love you-yes, my dear boy, to love you-as Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85382,\n            \"\\u201cCall me what you will,\\u201dhe said.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85453,\n            \"and if I was rude or in any way wanting at that time you acted so-you remember \\\"-the Professor nodded-\\\" you must forgive me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85484,\n            \"\\u201d He answered with a grave kindness:-\\u201cI know it was hard for you to quite trust me then, for to trust such violence needs to understand;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85516,\n            \"and I take it that you do not-that you cannot-trust me now, for you do not yet understand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85628,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cAnd, indeed, indeed, sir,\\u201dsaid Arthur warmly, \\u201cI shall in all ways trust you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85911,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur spoke out heartily, like his old self:-\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, you may do what you will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86007,\n            \"We and you too-you most of all, my dear boy-will have to pass through the bitter water before we reach the sweet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86056,\n            \"\\u201d I slept on a sofa in Arthur\\u2019s room that night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87652,\n            \"When it was all over, we were standing beside Arthur, who, poor fellow, was speaking of his part in the operation where his blood had been transfused to his Lucy\\u2019s veins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87705,\n            \"Arthur was saying that he felt since then as if they two had been really married and that she was his wife in the sight of God.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87751,\n            \"Arthur and Quincey went away together to the station, and Van Helsing and I came on here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95699,\n            \"Quincey wrote me a line too, and from him I hear that Arthur is beginning to recover something of his old buoyancy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98257,\n            \"I had it from the coffin-man to give to Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101798,\n            \"But then we may have to want Arthur, and how shall we tell him of this?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101844,\n            \"if you, who saw the coffin empty last night and full to-day with a woman who have not change only to be more rose and more beautiful in a whole week, after she die-if you know of this and know of the white figure last night that brought the child to the churchyard, and yet of your own senses you did not believe, how, then, can I expect Arthur, who know none of those things, to believe?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101934,\n            \"He doubted me when I took him from her kiss when she was dying.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101949,\n            \"I know he has forgiven me because in some mistaken idea I have done things that prevent him say good-bye as he ought;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102003,\n            \"He will then argue back that it is we, mistaken ones, that have killed her by our ideas;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102048,\n            \"And he will sometimes think that she he loved was buried alive, and that will paint his dreams with horrors of what she must have suffered;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102248,\n            \"I shall send for Arthur to come too, and also that so fine young man of America that gave his blood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103022,\n            \"he told us all that he wanted us to do, but especially addressing himself to Arthur, as if all our wills were centred in his.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103467,\n            \"Then Arthur spoke out:-\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, I don\\u2019t quite like to \\u2018 buy a pig in a poke,\\u2019as they say in Scotland, and if it be anything in which my honour as a gentleman or my faith as a Christian is concerned, I cannot make such a promise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103529,\n            \"If you can assure me that what you intend does not violate either of these two, then I give my consent at once;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103570,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI accept your limitation,\\u201dsaid Van Helsing, \\u201cand all I ask of you is that if you feel it necessary to condemn any act of mine, you will first consider it well and be satisfied that it does not violate your reservations.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103634,\n            \"And now that the pourparlers are over, may I ask what it is we are to do?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103653,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI want you to come with me, and to come in secret, to the churchyard at Kingstead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103751,\n            \"\\u201d He sat down again, but I could see that he sat firmly and proudly, as one who is on his dignity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104226,\n            \"What have I done to you that you should torture me so?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104386,\n            \"All I ask you now is that you come with me, that you look and listen;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104404,\n            \"and if when later I make the same request you do not be more eager for its fulfilment even than I am, then-then I shall do my duty, whatever it may seem to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104443,\n            \"And then, to follow of your Lordship\\u2019s wishes I shall hold myself at your disposal to render an account to you, when and where you will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104474,\n            \"\\u201d His voice broke a little, and he went on with a voice full of pity:-\\u201cBut, I beseech you, do not go forth in anger with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104542,\n            \"Believe me that if the time comes for you to change your mind towards me, one look from you will wipe away all this so sad hour, for I would do what a man can to save you from sorrow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104742,\n            \"\\u201d He said this with a very grave, sweet pride, and Arthur was much affected by it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104762,\n            \"He took the old man\\u2019s hand and said in a broken voice:-\\u201cOh, it is hard to think of it, and I cannot understand;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104794,\n            \"but at least I shall go with you and wait.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104878,\n            \"When we had come close to the tomb I looked well at Arthur, for I feared that the proximity to a place laden with so sorrowful a memory would upset him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104917,\n            \"I took it that the very mystery of the proceeding was in some way a counteractant to his grief.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105528,\n            \"\\u201d He opened the door, and we filed out, he coming last and locking the door behind him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105666,\n            \"Arthur was silent, and was, I could see, striving to grasp the purpose and the inner meaning of the mystery.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105894,\n            \"Arthur and Quincey drew near also, as they too were curious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106082,\n            \"I pitied the others, especially Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106399,\n            \"My own heart grew cold as ice, and I could hear the gasp of Arthur, as we recognised the features of Lucy Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106558,\n            \"Arthur was next to me, and if I had not seized his arm and held him up, he would have fallen.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106791,\n            \"when she advanced to him with outstretched arms and a wanton smile he fell back and hid his face in his hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106814,\n            \"She still advanced, however, and with a languorous, voluptuous grace, said:-\\u201cCome to me, Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106846,\n            \"My arms are hungry for you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106926,\n            \"She was leaping for them, when Van Helsing sprang forward and held between them his little golden crucifix.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106946,\n            \"She recoiled from it, and, with a suddenly distorted face, full of rage, dashed past him as if to enter the tomb.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107245,\n            \"Quincey and I simultaneously moved towards him, and took his arms.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107592,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur and Quincey came home with me, and we tried to cheer each other on the way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107641,\n            \"- A little before twelve o\\u2019clock we three-Arthur, Quincey Morris, and myself-called for the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107682,\n            \"Of course, Arthur wore black, for he was in deep mourning, but the rest of us wore it by instinct.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107889,\n            \"When he again lifted the lid off Lucy\\u2019s coffin we all looked-Arthur trembling like an aspen-and saw that the body lay there in all its death-beauty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107952,\n            \"I could see even Arthur\\u2019s face grow hard as he looked.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108214,\n            \"To me, a doctor\\u2019s preparations for work of any kind are stimulating and bracing, but the effect of these things on both Arthur and Quincey was to cause them a sort of consternation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108415,\n            \"or again, last night when you open your arms to her, you would in time, when you had died, have become nosferatu, as they call it in Eastern Europe, and would all time make more of those Un-Deads that so have fill us with horror.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108751,\n            \"\\u201d We all looked at Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108758,\n            \"He saw, too, what we all did, the infinite kindness which suggested that his should be the hand which would restore Lucy to us as a holy, and not an unholy, memory;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108944,\n            \"Only think that we, your true friends, are round you, and that we pray for you all the time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109114,\n            \"Arthur placed the point over the heart, and as I looked I could see its dint in the white flesh.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109204,\n            \"He looked like a figure of Thor as his untrembling arm rose and fell, driving deeper and deeper the mercy-bearing stake, whilst the blood from the pierced heart welled and spurted up around it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109321,\n            \"He reeled and would have fallen had we not caught him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109384,\n            \"For a few minutes we were so taken up with him that we did not look towards the coffin.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109424,\n            \"We gazed so eagerly that Arthur rose, for he had been seated on the ground, and came and looked too;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109470,\n            \"There, in the coffin lay no longer the foul Thing that we had so dreaded and grown to hate that the work of her destruction was yielded as a privilege to the one best entitled to it, but Lucy as we had seen her in her life, with her face of unequalled sweetness and purity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109678,\n            \"God bless you that you have given my dear one her soul again, and me peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109696,\n            \"\\u201d He put his hands on the Professor\\u2019s shoulder, and laying his head on his breast, cried for a while silently, whilst we stood unmoving.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109727,\n            \"When he raised his head Van Helsing said to him:-\\u201cAnd now, my child, you may kiss her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109751,\n            \"Kiss her dead lips if you will, as she would have you to, if for her to choose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109817,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur bent and kissed her, and then we sent him and Quincey out of the tomb;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118576,\n            \"And Arthur and my friend Quincey, they are with you, too?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            128449,\n            \"for look, these rats that would come to his call, just as from his castle top he summon the wolves to your going and to that poor mother\\u2019s cry, though they come to him, they run pell-mell from the so little dogs of my friend Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144932,\n            \"\\u201d So Art went on:-\\u201cHe had been there, and though it could only have been for a few seconds, he made rare hay of the place.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145020,\n            \"\\u201d His face lit for a moment, but fell again as he went on: \\u201cI ran downstairs then, but could see no sign of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145135,\n            \"\\u201d I could not but feel that Art was keeping back something;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155343,\n            \"In all our hunting parties and adventures in different parts of the world, Quincey Morris had always been the one to arrange the plan of action, and Arthur and I had been accustomed to obey him implicitly.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 16]\": [\n        [\n            26654,\n            \"CHAPTER V Letter from Miss Mina Murray to Miss Lucy Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26670,\n            \"\\u201cMy dearest Lucy,-\\u201cForgive my long delay in writing, but I have been simply overwhelmed with work.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27082,\n            \"\\u201cYour loving \\u201cMina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27128,\n            \"\\u201d Letter, Lucy Westenra to Mina Murray.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27844,\n            \"\\u201d Letter, Lucy Westenra to Mina Murray.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27857,\n            \"\\u201cMy dearest Mina,-\\u201cThanks, and thanks, and thanks again for your sweet letter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28645,\n            \"My dear, I must stop here at present, I feel so miserable, though I am so happy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28816,\n            \"No, I don\\u2019t, for there was Mr. Morris telling us his stories, and Arthur never told any, and yet-- My dear, I am somewhat previous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28907,\n            \"I must tell you beforehand that Mr. Morris doesn\\u2019t always speak slang-that is to say, he never does so to strangers or before them, for he is really well educated and has exquisite manners-but he found out that it amused me to hear him talk American slang, and whenever I was present, and there was no one to be shocked, he said such funny things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28985,\n            \"I am afraid, my dear, he has to invent it all, for it fits exactly into whatever else he has to say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29051,\n            \"Well, Mr. Morris sat down beside me and looked as happy and jolly as he could, but I could see all the same that he was very nervous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29083,\n            \"He took my hand in his, and said ever so sweetly:-\\u201c\\u2018 Miss Lucy, I know I ain\\u2019t good enough to regulate the fixin\\u2019s of your little shoes, but I guess if you wait till you find a man that is you will go join them seven young women with the lamps when you quit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29149,\n            \"Won\\u2019t you just hitch up alongside of me and let us go down the long road together, driving in double harness?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29282,\n            \"He really did look serious when he was saying it, and I couldn\\u2019t help feeling a bit serious too-I know, Mina, you will think me a horrid flirt-though I couldn\\u2019t help feeling a sort of exultation that he was number two in one day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29338,\n            \"And then, my dear, before I could say a word he began pouring out a perfect torrent of love-making, laying his very heart and soul at my feet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29540,\n            \"\\u2019 \\u201cMy dear Mina, why are men so noble when we women are so little worthy of them?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29576,\n            \"I burst into tears-I am afraid, my dear, you will think this a very sloppy letter in more ways than one-and I really felt very badly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29704,\n            \"\\u2019 I was right to speak to him so frankly, for quite a light came into his face, and he put out both his hands and took mine-I think I put them into his-and said in a hearty way:-\\u201c\\u2018 That\\u2019s my brave girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29760,\n            \"It\\u2019s better worth being late for a chance of winning you than being in time for any other girl in the world.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29848,\n            \"Little girl, your honesty and pluck have made me a friend, and that\\u2019s rarer than a lover;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29896,\n            \"Won\\u2019t you give me one kiss?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29919,\n            \"You can, you know, if you like, for that other good fellow-he must be a good fellow, my dear, and a fine fellow, or you could not love him-hasn\\u2019t spoken yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29963,\n            \"\\u2019 That quite won me, Mina, for it was brave and sweet of him, and noble, too, to a rival-wasn\\u2019t it?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30008,\n            \"He stood up with my two hands in his, and as he looked down into my face-I am afraid I was blushing very much-he said:-\\u201c\\u2018 Little girl, I hold your hand, and you\\u2019ve kissed me, and if these things don\\u2019t make us friends nothing ever will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30071,\n            \"Thank you for your sweet honesty to me, and good-bye.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30172,\n            \"My dear, this quite upset me, and I feel I cannot write of happiness just at once, after telling you of it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30766,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear Art,-\\u201cWe\\u2019ve told yarns by the camp-fire in the prairies;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30833,\n            \"Won\\u2019t you let this be at my camp-fire to-morrow night?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30850,\n            \"I have no hesitation in asking you, as I know a certain lady is engaged to a certain dinner-party, and that you are free.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            30975,\n            \"We shall both swear to leave you at home if you drink too deep to a certain pair of eyes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31061,\n            \"- Lucy met me at the station, looking sweeter and lovelier than ever, and we drove up to the house at the Crescent in which they have rooms.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31778,\n            \"He is, I am afraid, a very sceptical person, for when I asked him about the bells at sea and the White Lady at the abbey he said very brusquely:-\\u201cI wouldn\\u2019t fash masel\\u2019about them, miss.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31858,\n            \"They be all very well for comers and trippers, an\\u2019the like, but not for a nice young lady like you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            31981,\n            \"He was just settling himself to begin when the clock struck six, whereupon he laboured to get up, and said:-\\u201cI must gang ageeanwards home now, miss.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32054,\n            \"an \\u2019, miss, I lack belly-timber sairly by the clock.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32169,\n            \"Lucy went out visiting with her mother, and as they were only duty calls, I did not go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32200,\n            \"- I came up here an hour ago with Lucy, and we had a most interesting talk with my old friend and the two others who always come and join him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32314,\n            \"I noticed that the old men did not lose any time in coming up and sitting near her when we sat down.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32337,\n            \"She is so sweet with old people;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32345,\n            \"I think they all fell in love with her on the spot.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            32358,\n            \"Even my old man succumbed and did not contradict her, but gave me double share instead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33450,\n            \"Answer me that, miss!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33559,\n            \"The letters were upside down to me from where I sat, but Lucy was more opposite to them, so she leant over and read:-\\u201cSacred to the memory of George Canon, who died, in the hope of a glorious resurrection, on July, 29, 1873, falling from the rocks at Kettleness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33926,\n            \"\\u201d I did not know what to say, but Lucy turned the conversation as she said, rising up:-\\u201cOh, why did you tell us of this?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33959,\n            \"It is my favourite seat, and I cannot leave it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            33987,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThat won\\u2019t harm ye, my pretty;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34131,\n            \"Lucy and I sat awhile, and it was all so beautiful before us that we took hands as we sat;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36089,\n            \"Oh, Lucy, Lucy, I cannot be angry with you, nor can I be angry with my friend whose happiness is yours;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36216,\n            \"I am unhappy about Lucy and about Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36412,\n            \"Poor dear, she is naturally anxious about Lucy, and she tells me that her husband, Lucy\\u2019s father, had the same habit;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36461,\n            \"Lucy is to be married in the autumn, and she is already planning out her dresses and how her house is to be arranged.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36532,\n            \"Arthur Holmwood, only son of Lord Godalming-is coming up here very shortly-as soon as he can leave town, for his father is not very well, and I think dear Lucy is counting the moments till he comes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36577,\n            \"She wants to take him up to the seat on the churchyard cliff and show him the beauty of Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36598,\n            \"I daresay it is the waiting which disturbs her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36608,\n            \"she will be all right when he arrives.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36660,\n            \"Lucy walks more than ever, and each night I am awakened by her moving about the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36717,\n            \"Thank God, Lucy\\u2019s health keeps up.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36748,\n            \"Lucy frets at the postponement of seeing him, but it does not touch her looks;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36879,\n            \"Lucy has not walked much in her sleep the last week, but there is an odd concentration about her which I do not understand;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36905,\n            \"even in her sleep she seems to be watching me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            38010,\n            \"We\\u2019ll hear more of her before this time to-morrow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43619,\n            \"- Lucy was very restless all night, and I, too, could not sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43688,\n            \"Fortunately, each time I awoke in time and managed to undress her without waking her, and got her back to bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43952,\n            \"Lucy came with me, and we went early to our old seat, whilst the cort\\u00e8ge of boats went up the river to the Viaduct and came down again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44029,\n            \"She was restless and uneasy all the time, and I cannot but think that her dreaming at night is telling on her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44053,\n            \"She is quite odd in one thing: she will not admit to me that there is any cause for restlessness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44168,\n            \"Lucy is so sweet and sensitive that she feels influences more acutely than other people do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44185,\n            \"Just now she was quite upset by a little thing which I did not much heed, though I am myself very fond of animals.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44449,\n            \"Lucy was full of pity, too, but she did not attempt to touch the dog, but looked at it in an agonised sort of way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44478,\n            \"I greatly fear that she is of too super-sensitive a nature to go through the world without trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44499,\n            \"She will be dreaming of this to-night, I am sure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44546,\n            \"the dog, now furious and now in terror-will all afford material for her dreams.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44564,\n            \"I think it will be best for her to go to bed tired out physically, so I shall take her for a long walk by the cliffs to Robin Hood\\u2019s Bay and back.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44667,\n            \"Lucy, after a while, was in gay spirits, owing, I think, to some dear cows who came nosing towards us in a field close to the lighthouse, and frightened the wits out of us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44826,\n            \"Lucy was really tired, and we intended to creep off to bed as soon as we could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44864,\n            \"Lucy and I had both a fight for it with the dusty miller;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            44966,\n            \"If Mr. Holmwood fell in love with her seeing her only in the drawing-room, I wonder what he would say if he saw her now.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45069,\n            \"I am so happy to-night, because dear Lucy seems better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45083,\n            \"I really believe she has turned the corner, and that we are over her troubles with dreaming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45208,\n            \"The room was dark, so I could not see Lucy\\u2019s bed;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45223,\n            \"I stole across and felt for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45236,\n            \"I lit a match and found that she was not in the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45265,\n            \"I feared to wake her mother, who has been more than usually ill lately, so threw on some clothes and got ready to look for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45294,\n            \"As I was leaving the room it struck me that the clothes she wore might give me some clue to her dreaming intention.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45340,\n            \"\\u201cThank God,\\u201dI said to myself, \\u201cshe cannot be far, as she is only in her nightdress.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45430,\n            \"The people of the house are careful to lock the door every night, so I feared that Lucy must have gone out as she was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45676,\n            \"Whatever my expectation was, it was not disappointed, for there, on our favourite seat, the silver light of the moon struck a half-reclining figure, snowy white.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45733,\n            \"but it seemed to me as though something dark stood behind the seat where the white figure shone, and bent over it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45825,\n            \"I rejoiced that it was so, for I wanted no witness of poor Lucy\\u2019s condition.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45903,\n            \"When I got almost to the top I could see the seat and the white figure, for I was now close enough to distinguish it even through the spells of shadow.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45954,\n            \"I called in fright, \\u201cLucy!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45988,\n            \"Lucy did not answer, and I ran on to the entrance of the churchyard.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46004,\n            \"As I entered, the church was between me and the seat, and for a minute or so I lost sight of her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46029,\n            \"When I came in view again the cloud had passed, and the moonlight struck so brilliantly that I could see Lucy half reclining with her head lying over the back of the seat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46081,\n            \"When I bent over her I could see that she was still asleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46131,\n            \"As I came close, she put up her hand in her sleep and pulled the collar of her nightdress close around her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46175,\n            \"I flung the warm shawl over her, and drew the edges tight round her neck, for I dreaded lest she should get some deadly chill from the night air, unclad as she was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46212,\n            \"I feared to wake her all at once, so, in order to have my hands free that I might help her, I fastened the shawl at her throat with a big safety-pin;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46250,\n            \"but I must have been clumsy in my anxiety and pinched or pricked her with it, for by-and-by, when her breathing became quieter, she put her hand to her throat again and moaned.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46291,\n            \"When I had her carefully wrapped up I put my shoes on her feet and then began very gently to wake her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46338,\n            \"At last, as time was passing fast, and, for many other reasons, I wished to get her home at once, I shook her more forcibly, till finally she opened her eyes and awoke.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46378,\n            \"She did not seem surprised to see me, as, of course, she did not realise all at once where she was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46446,\n            \"She trembled a little, and clung to me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46456,\n            \"when I told her to come at once with me home she rose without a word, with the obedience of a child.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46480,\n            \"As we passed along, the gravel hurt my feet, and Lucy noticed me wince.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46497,\n            \"She stopped and wanted to insist upon my taking my shoes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46664,\n            \"I was filled with anxiety about Lucy, not only for her health, lest she should suffer from the exposure, but for her reputation in case the story should get wind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46698,\n            \"When we got in, and had washed our feet, and had said a prayer of thankfulness together, I tucked her into bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46724,\n            \"Before falling asleep she asked-even implored-me not to say a word to any one, even her mother, about her sleep-walking adventure.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46761,\n            \"but on thinking of the state of her mother\\u2019s health, and how the knowledge of such a thing would fret her, and thinking, too, of how such a story might become distorted-nay, infallibly would-in case it should leak out, I thought it wiser to do so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46881,\n            \"Lucy slept till I woke her and seemed not to have even changed her side.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46932,\n            \"I was sorry to notice that my clumsiness with the safety-pin hurt her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            46965,\n            \"I must have pinched up a piece of loose skin and have transfixed it, for there are two little red points like pin-pricks, and on the band of her nightdress was a drop of blood.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47005,\n            \"When I apologised and was concerned about it, she laughed and petted me, and said she did not even feel it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47071,\n            \"We took our lunch to Mulgrave Woods, Mrs. Westenra driving by the road and Lucy and I walking by the cliff-path and joining her at the gate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47210,\n            \"- My expectations were wrong, for twice during the night I was wakened by Lucy trying to get out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47277,\n            \"Lucy woke, too, and, I was glad to see, was even better than on the previous morning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47299,\n            \"All her old gaiety of manner seemed to have come back, and she came and snuggled in beside me and told me all about Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47326,\n            \"I told her how anxious I was about Jonathan, and then she tried to comfort me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47389,\n            \"Again I awoke in the night, and found Lucy sitting up in bed, still asleep, pointing to the window.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47505,\n            \"When I came back from the window Lucy had lain down again, and was sleeping peacefully.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47546,\n            \"Lucy seems to have become as much in love with the spot as I am, and it is hard to get her away from it when it is time to come home for lunch or tea or dinner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47670,\n            \"We were silent for a while, and suddenly Lucy murmured as if to herself:-\\u201cHis red eyes again!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47718,\n            \"I slewed round a little, so as to see Lucy well without seeming to stare at her, and saw that she was in a half-dreamy state, with an odd look on her face that I could not quite make out;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47764,\n            \"so I said nothing, but followed her eyes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47774,\n            \"She appeared to be looking over at our own seat, whereon was a dark figure seated alone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47869,\n            \"I called Lucy\\u2019s attention to the peculiar effect, and she became herself with a start, but she looked sad all the same;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47939,\n            \"I saw her asleep, and went out for a little stroll myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47976,\n            \"When coming home-it was then bright moonlight, so bright that, though the front of our part of the Crescent was in shadow, everything could be well seen-I threw a glance up at our window, and saw Lucy\\u2019s head leaning out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48027,\n            \"I thought that perhaps she was looking out for me, so I opened my handkerchief and waved it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48127,\n            \"I was afraid she might get a chill, so I ran upstairs, but as I came into the room she was moving back to her bed, fast asleep, and breathing heavily;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48180,\n            \"I did not wake her, but tucked her up warmly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48215,\n            \"but she is paler than is her wont, and there is a drawn, haggard look under her eyes which I do not like.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48241,\n            \"I fear she is fretting about something.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48268,\n            \"Lucy was languid and tired, and slept on after we had been called.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48307,\n            \"Lucy is full of quiet joy, and her mother is glad and sorry at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48335,\n            \"She is grieved to lose Lucy as her very own, but she is rejoiced that she is soon to have some one to protect her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48381,\n            \"She has not told Lucy, and made me promise secrecy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48434,\n            \"Ah, we were wise to keep from her the affair of the dreadful night of Lucy\\u2019s sleep-walking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48490,\n            \"No news from Jonathan, and Lucy seems to be growing weaker, whilst her mother\\u2019s hours are numbering to a close.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48515,\n            \"I do not understand Lucy\\u2019s fading away as she is doing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49800,\n            \"I did not quite like it, and thought it better not to keep her mind on the subject, so we drifted on to other subjects, and Lucy was like her old self again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50059,\n            \"Lucy will bring my trunk to London and keep it till I send for it, for it may be that.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50607,\n            \"Mary, many, many, happy years for you both.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51203,\n            \"I cannot but think of Lucy, and how different things might have been.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51260,\n            \"I have thought of Lucy, and I shall not dishonour her by mixing the two.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52132,\n            \"CHAPTER IX Letter, Mina Harker to Lucy Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52150,\n            \"\\u201cMy dearest Lucy,-\\u201cI know you will be anxious to hear all that has happened since we parted at the railway station at Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52179,\n            \"Well, my dear, I got to Hull all right, and caught the boat to Hamburg, and then the train on here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52389,\n            \"I wanted her to tell me what they were;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52443,\n            \"She is a sweet, good soul, and the next day, when she saw I was troubled, she opened up the subject again, and after saying that she could never mention what my poor dear raved about, added: \\u2018 I can tell you this much, my dear: that it was not about anything which he has done wrong himself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52555,\n            \"\\u2019 I do believe the dear soul thought I might be jealous lest my poor dear should have fallen in love with any other girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52667,\n            \"I asked Sister Agatha, and she brought all his things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52750,\n            \"Then he called me back, and when I came he had his hand over the note-book, and he said to me very solemnly:-\\u201c\\u2018 Wilhelmina\\u2019- I knew then that he was in deadly earnest, for he has never called me by that name since he asked me to marry him-\\u2018 you know, dear, my ideas of the trust between husband and wife: there should be no secret, no concealment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52939,\n            \"\\u2018 Are you willing, Wilhelmina, to share my ignorance?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53023,\n            \"I have asked Sister Agatha to beg the Superior to let our wedding be this afternoon, and am waiting her reply.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53204,\n            \"When the chaplain and the sisters had left me alone with my husband-oh, Lucy, it is the first time I have written the words \\u2018 my husband\\u2019- left me alone with my husband, I took the book from under his pillow, and wrapped it up in white paper, and tied it with a little bit of pale blue ribbon which was round my neck, and sealed it over the knot with sealing-wax, and for my seal I used my wedding ring.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53364,\n            \"Then he took my hand in his, and oh, Lucy, it was the first time he took his wife\\u2019s hand, and said that it was the dearest thing in all the wide world, and that he would go through all the past again to win it, if need be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53560,\n            \"\\u201cLucy dear, do you know why I tell you all this?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53574,\n            \"It is not only because it is all sweet to me, but because you have been, and are, very dear to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53624,\n            \"I want you to see now, and with the eyes of a very happy wife, whither duty has led me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53647,\n            \"so that in your own married life you too may be all happy as I am.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53766,\n            \"\\u201cYour ever-loving \\u201cMina Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55150,\n            \"Mother did not seem to take to my proposal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55160,\n            \"She seems not too well herself, and doubtless she fears to worry me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55374,\n            \"I have asked her if there is any cause;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55384,\n            \"I do not dare to ask her mother, for to disturb the poor lady\\u2019s mind about her daughter in her present state of health would be fatal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55415,\n            \"Mrs. Westenra has confided to me that her doom is spoken-disease of the heart-though poor Lucy does not know it yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55442,\n            \"I am sure that there is something preying on my dear girl\\u2019s mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55458,\n            \"I am almost distracted when I think of her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55468,\n            \"to look at her gives me a pang.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55477,\n            \"I told her I should ask you to see her, and though she demurred at first-I know why, old fellow-she finally consented.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55506,\n            \"It will be a painful task for you, I know, old friend, but it is for her sake, and I must not hesitate to ask, or you to act.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55541,\n            \"You are to come to lunch at Hillingham to-morrow, two o\\u2019clock, so as not to arouse any suspicion in Mrs. Westenra, and after lunch Lucy will take an opportunity of being alone with you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55598,\n            \"I am filled with anxiety, and want to consult with you alone as soon as I can after you have seen her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55730,\n            \"At the same time, I am not by any means satisfied with her appearance;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55746,\n            \"she is woefully different from what she was when I saw her last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55844,\n            \"Her mother was present, and in a few seconds I made up my mind that she was trying all she knew to mislead her mother and prevent her from being anxious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55877,\n            \"I have no doubt she guesses, if she does not know, what need of caution there is.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            55929,\n            \"Then Mrs. Westenra went to lie down, and Lucy was left with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57004,\n            \"He came on with me to Hillingham, and found that, by Lucy\\u2019s discretion, her mother was lunching out, so that we were alone with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57332,\n            \"Lucy was more cheerful than on the day I first saw her, and certainly looked better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57392,\n            \"though I could see that the poor girl was making a hard struggle for it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57826,\n            \"I have asked her to send me her maid, that I may ask just one or two question, that so I may not chance to miss nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57856,\n            \"I know well what she will say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57905,\n            \"The disease-for not to be all well is a disease-interest me, and the sweet young dear, she interest me too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            57932,\n            \"She charm me, and for her, if not for you or disease, I come.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            58048,\n            \"but, if need be, I shall send you word to come at once to Lucy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59303,\n            \"Mrs. Westenra was naturally anxious concerning Lucy, and has consulted me professionally about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59320,\n            \"I took advantage of the opportunity, and told her that my old master, Van Helsing, the great specialist, was coming to stay with me, and that I would put her in his charge conjointly with myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59362,\n            \"so now we can come and go without alarming her unduly, for a shock to her would mean sudden death, and this, in Lucy\\u2019s weak condition, might be disastrous to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59535,\n            \"I wrote him a letter simply telling him that you were coming, as Miss Westenra was not so well, and that I should let him know if need be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60234,\n            \"\\u201d When I described Lucy\\u2019s symptoms-the same as before, but infinitely more marked-he looked very grave, but said nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60475,\n            \"I used my knowledge of this phase of spiritual pathology, and laid down a rule that she should not be present with Lucy or think of her illness more than was absolutely required.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60528,\n            \"Van Helsing and I were shown up to Lucy\\u2019s room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60541,\n            \"If I was shocked when I saw her yesterday, I was horrified when I saw her to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60623,\n            \"Lucy lay motionless, and did not seem to have strength to speak, so for a while we were all silent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61068,\n            \"My life is hers, and I would give the last drop of blood in my body for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61196,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur looked bewildered, and the Professor went on by explaining in a kindly way:-\\u201cYoung miss is bad, very bad.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61394,\n            \"\\u201cIn the not-so-far-off you will be happy that you have done all for her you love.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61424,\n            \"You shall kiss her once before it is done, but then you must go;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61454,\n            \"you know how it is with her!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61478,\n            \"\\u201d We all went up to Lucy\\u2019s room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61495,\n            \"Lucy turned her head and looked at us, but said nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61524,\n            \"Her eyes spoke to us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61716,\n            \"\\u201d So neither of us looked whilst he bent over her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61832,\n            \"It gave me an idea of what a terrible strain Lucy\\u2019s system must have undergone that what weakened Arthur only partially restored her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62012,\n            \"As he did so the narrow black velvet band which she seems always to wear round her throat, buckled with an old diamond buckle which her lover had given her, was dragged a little up, and showed a red mark on her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62194,\n            \"You have saved her life this time, and you can go home and rest easy in mind that all that can be is.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62219,\n            \"I shall tell her all when she is well;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62229,\n            \"she shall love you none the less for what you have done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62269,\n            \"I could see the counterpane move as her breast heaved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62301,\n            \"I asked the Professor in a whisper:-\\u201cWhat do you make of that mark on her throat?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62527,\n            \"You must remain here all the night, and you must not let your sight pass from her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62653,\n            \"He came back a moment later and put his head inside the door and said with warning finger held up:-\\u201cRemember, she is your charge.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62683,\n            \"If you leave her, and harm befall, you shall not sleep easy hereafter!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62712,\n            \"- I sat up all night with Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62748,\n            \"Her spirits even were good, and she was full of a happy vivacity, but I could see evidences of the absolute prostration which she had undergone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62777,\n            \"When I told Mrs. Westenra that Dr. Van Helsing had directed that I should sit up with her she almost pooh-poohed the idea, pointing out her daughter\\u2019s renewed strength and excellent spirits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62831,\n            \"When her maid had prepared her for the night I came in, having in the meantime had supper, and took a seat by the bedside.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62859,\n            \"She did not in any way make objection, but looked at me gratefully whenever I caught her eye.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62923,\n            \"It was apparent that she did not want to sleep, so I tackled the subject at once:-\\u201cYou do not want to go to sleep?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63447,\n            \"When she shook hands with me she looked sharply in my face and said:-\\u201cNo sitting up to-night for you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63524,\n            \"Lucy came with me, and, enlivened by her charming presence, I made an excellent meal, and had a couple of glasses of the more than excellent port.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63556,\n            \"Then Lucy took me upstairs, and showed me a room next her own, where a cozy fire was burning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63578,\n            \"\\u201cNow,\\u201dshe said, \\u201cyou must stay here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63591,\n            \"I shall leave this door open and my door too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63602,\n            \"You can lie on the sofa for I know that nothing would induce any of you doctors to go to bed whilst there is a patient above the horizon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63966,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cWell, when I left her, or rather when she left me,\\u201dI answered.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64652,\n            \"\\u201d When we stopped the operation, he attended to Lucy, whilst I applied digital pressure to my own incision.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64888,\n            \"I fell asleep on the sofa, however, wondering over and over again how Lucy had made such a retrograde movement, and how she could have been drained of so much blood with no sign anywhere to show for it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64976,\n            \"Lucy slept well into the day, and when she woke she was fairly well and strong, though not nearly so much so as the day before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65056,\n            \"Lucy chatted with me freely, and seemed quite unconscious that anything had happened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65158,\n            \"\\u201d As she spoke, Lucy turned crimson, though it was only momentarily, for her poor wasted veins could not stand for long such an unwonted drain to the head.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65328,\n            \"\\u201d In the hall two of the maids came to me, and asked if they or either of them might not sit up with Miss Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65407,\n            \"Perhaps it is because I am weak at present, and perhaps because it was on Lucy\\u2019s account, that their devotion was manifested;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66260,\n            \"We then waited whilst Lucy made her toilet for the night, and when she was in bed he came and himself fixed the wreath of garlic round her neck.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66330,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI promise,\\u201dsaid Lucy, \\u201cand thank you both a thousand times for all your kindness to me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66883,\n            \"When we entered we met Mrs. Westenra coming out of the morning room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66905,\n            \"She greeted us warmly and said:-\\u201cYou will be glad to know that Lucy is better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66984,\n            \"My treatment is working,\\u201dto which she answered:-\\u201cYou must not take all the credit to yourself, doctor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67038,\n            \"\\u201cWell, I was anxious about the dear child in the night, and went into her room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67058,\n            \"She was sleeping soundly-so soundly that even my coming did not wake her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67371,\n            \"\\u201cWhat have we done, what has this poor thing done, that we are so sore beset?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67545,\n            \"and together we went up to Lucy\\u2019s room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67572,\n            \"This time he did not start as he looked on the poor face with the same awful, waxen pallor as before.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67761,\n            \"Presently he took an opportunity of telling Mrs. Westenra that she must not remove anything from Lucy\\u2019s room without consulting him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            67840,\n            \"After another hour Lucy waked from her sleep, fresh and bright and seemingly not much the worse for her terrible ordeal.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71015,\n            \"- I was engaged after dinner in my study posting up my books, which, through press of other work and the many visits to Lucy, had fallen sadly into arrear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71583,\n            \"I shall take this cylinder with me, and then I can complete my entry on Lucy\\u2019s phonograph.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71706,\n            \"I was waked by the flapping at the window, which had begun after that sleep-walking on the cliff at Whitby when Mina saved me, and which now I know so well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73036,\n            \"I knocked gently and rang as quietly as possible, for I feared to disturb Lucy or her mother, and hoped to only bring a servant to the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73179,\n            \"I knew that minutes, even seconds of delay, might mean hours of danger to Lucy, if she had had again one of those frightful relapses;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73642,\n            \"\\u201d Then we ascended to Lucy\\u2019s room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73701,\n            \"On the bed lay two women, Lucy and her mother.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73760,\n            \"By her side lay Lucy, with face white and still more drawn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73774,\n            \"The flowers which had been round her neck we found upon her mother\\u2019s bosom, and her throat was bare, showing the two little wounds which we had noticed before, but looking horribly white and mangled.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74040,\n            \"She will need be heated before we can do anything more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74137,\n            \"I told them that one life was bad enough to lose, and that if they delayed they would sacrifice Miss Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74204,\n            \"We got a bath and carried Lucy out as she was and placed her in it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74221,\n            \"Whilst we were busy chafing her limbs there was a knock at the hall door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74358,\n            \"He answered me in a way that I did not understand, but with the sternest look that his face could wear:-\\u201cIf that were all, I would stop here where we are now, and let her fade away into peace, for I see no light in life over her horizon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74473,\n            \"Van Helsing\\u2019s face almost beamed, and as we lifted her from the bath and rolled her in a hot sheet to dry her he said to me:-\\u201cThe first gain is ours!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74517,\n            \"\\u201d We took Lucy into another room, which had by now been prepared, and laid her in bed and forced a few drops of brandy down her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74548,\n            \"I noticed that Van Helsing tied a soft silk handkerchief round her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74562,\n            \"She was still unconscious, and was quite as bad as, if not worse than, we had ever seen her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74585,\n            \"Van Helsing called in one of the women, and told her to stay with her and not to take her eyes off her till we returned, and then beckoned me out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74771,\n            \"We must have another transfusion of blood, and that soon, or that poor girl\\u2019s life won\\u2019t be worth an hour\\u2019s purchase.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74827,\n            \"What are we to do for some one who will open his veins for her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74978,\n            \"Send me word how Lucy is.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75257,\n            \"Then a thought struck me, and I went back to the room where Lucy now was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75340,\n            \"He handed me the paper saying only: \\u201cIt dropped from Lucy\\u2019s breast when we carried her to the bath.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75539,\n            \"I am in hopes that we need have no inquest, for if we had it would surely kill poor Lucy, if nothing else did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75566,\n            \"I know, and you know, and the other doctor who attended her knows, that Mrs. Westenra had disease of the heart, and we can certify that she died of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75666,\n            \"One, two, three, all open their veins for her, besides one old man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75747,\n            \"and that Van Helsing and I were with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75847,\n            \"I told him I would see him as soon as I knew about Lucy, and went up to her room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75888,\n            \"From his putting his finger to his lips, I gathered that he expected her to wake before long and was afraid of forestalling nature.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75996,\n            \"You know I loved that girl and wanted to marry her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76008,\n            \"but, although that\\u2019s all past and gone, I can\\u2019t help feeling anxious about her all the same.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76334,\n            \"He was in a torture of suspense regarding the woman he loved, and his utter ignorance of the terrible mystery which seemed to surround her intensified his pain.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76476,\n            \"Then I guess, Jack Seward, that that poor pretty creature that we all love has had put into her veins within that time the blood of four strong men.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76508,\n            \"Man alive, her whole body wouldn\\u2019t hold it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76587,\n            \"There has been a series of little circumstances which have thrown out all our calculations as to Lucy being properly watched.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76662,\n            \"\\u201d When she woke late in the afternoon, Lucy\\u2019s first movement was to feel in her breast, and, to my surprise, produced the paper which Van Helsing had given me to read.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76721,\n            \"Her eye then lit on Van Helsing and on me too, and gladdened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76768,\n            \"We both understood what that meant-that she had realised to the full her mother\\u2019s death;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76788,\n            \"so we tried what we could to comfort her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76824,\n            \"We told her that either or both of us would now remain with her all the time, and that seemed to comfort her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76975,\n            \"The Professor and I took it in turns to watch, and we never left her for a moment unattended.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77061,\n            \"At times she slept, and both Van Helsing and I noticed the difference in her, between sleeping and waking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77122,\n            \"when she woke the softness of her eyes evidently changed the expression, for she looked her own self, although a dying one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77147,\n            \"In the afternoon she asked for Arthur, and we telegraphed for him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77209,\n            \"When he saw her, Arthur was simply choking with emotion, and none of us could speak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77279,\n            \"she rallied a little, and spoke to him more brightly than she had done since we arrived.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77340,\n            \"I am to relieve them in a quarter of an hour, and I am entering this on Lucy\\u2019s phonograph.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77616,\n            \"\\u2019 I cried, Lucy dear, as Jonathan and the old man clasped hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77717,\n            \"I am busy, I need not tell you, arranging things and housekeeping.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77772,\n            \"I wish I could run up to town for a day or two to see you, dear, but I dare not go yet, with so much on my shoulders;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77890,\n            \"And now I have told you my news, let me ask yours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77941,\n            \"Tell me all about it, dear;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77949,\n            \"tell me all about everything, for there is nothing which interests you which will not be dear to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78002,\n            \"and so, as you love me, and he loves me, and I love you with all the moods and tenses of the verb, I send you simply his \\u2018 love\\u2019instead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79262,\n            \"\\u201d Letter, Mina Harker to Lucy Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79281,\n            \"\\u201cMy dearest Lucy,-\\u201cSuch a sad blow has befallen us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79569,\n            \"but, Lucy dear, I must tell some one, for the strain of keeping up a brave and cheerful appearance to Jonathan tries me, and I have no one here that I can confide in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79809,\n            \"I duly relieved Van Helsing in his watch over Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79835,\n            \"It was only when I told him that we should want him to help us during the day, and that we must not all break down for want of rest, lest Lucy should suffer, that he agreed to go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80004,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur went off with him, casting back a longing look on Lucy\\u2019s face, which lay in her pillow, almost whiter than the lawn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80080,\n            \"the whole of the window-sashes reeked with it, and round Lucy\\u2019s neck, over the silk handkerchief which Van Helsing made her keep on, was a rough chaplet of the same odorous flowers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80120,\n            \"Lucy was breathing somewhat stertorously, and her face was at its worst, for the open mouth showed the pale gums.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80278,\n            \"When I came back to my seat, I found that Lucy had moved slightly, and had torn away the garlic flowers from her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80523,\n            \"\\u201d Then he bent down, and, with his face almost touching Lucy\\u2019s, examined her carefully.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80847,\n            \"\\u201d When we came into Lucy\\u2019s room I could see that Van Helsing had, with his usual forethought, been putting matters straight and making everything look as pleasing as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81288,\n            \"I kept my eyes fixed on Lucy, as did Van Helsing, and we saw a spasm as of rage flit like a shadow over her face;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81699,\n            \"\\u201d I stood beside Van Helsing, and said:-\\u201cAh, well, poor girl, there is peace for her at last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81801,\n            \"THE funeral was arranged for the next succeeding day, so that Lucy and her mother might be buried together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82490,\n            \"\\u201d Before turning in we went to look at poor Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82588,\n            \"All Lucy\\u2019s loveliness had come back to her in death, and the hours that had passed, instead of leaving traces of \\u201cdecay\\u2019s effacing fingers,\\u201dhad but restored the beauty of life, till positively I could not believe my eyes that I was looking at a corpse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82902,\n            \"Oh, but I must not forget, my dear friend John, that you loved her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83248,\n            \"Were you not amazed, nay horrified, when I would not let Arthur kiss his love-though she was dying-and snatched him away by all my strength?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83282,\n            \"And yet you saw how she thanked me, with her so beautiful dying eyes, her voice, too, so weak, and she kiss my rough old hand and bless me?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83319,\n            \"And did you not hear me swear promise to her, that so she closed her eyes grateful?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83541,\n            \"As I stood without moving, I saw one of the maids pass silently along the passage-she had her back towards me, so did not see me-and go into the room where Lucy lay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83914,\n            \"During lunch he told us that Mrs. Westenra had for some time expected sudden death from her heart, and had put her affairs in absolute order;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83997,\n            \"When he had told us so much he went on:-\\u201cFrankly we did our best to prevent such a testamentary disposition, and pointed out certain contingencies that might leave her daughter either penniless or not so free as she should be to act regarding a matrimonial alliance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84049,\n            \"Indeed, we pressed the matter so far that we almost came into collision, for she asked us if we were or were not prepared to carry out her wishes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84125,\n            \"Frankly, however, I must admit that in this case any other form of disposition would have rendered impossible the carrying out of her wishes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84152,\n            \"For by her predeceasing her daughter the latter would have come into possession of the property, and, even had she only survived her mother by five minutes, her property would, in case there were no will-and a will was a practical impossibility in such a case-have been treated at her decease as under intestacy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84642,\n            \"I did so, and left him at the door of the room, as I felt he would like to be quite alone with her, but he took my arm and led me in, saying huskily:-\\u201cYou loved her too, old fellow;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84692,\n            \"she told me all about it, and there was no friend had a closer place in her heart than you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84714,\n            \"I don\\u2019t know how to thank you for all you have done for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84856,\n            \"I stood still and silent till his sobs died away, and then I said softly to him:-\\u201cCome and look at her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84883,\n            \"\\u201d Together we moved over to the bed, and I lifted the lawn from her face.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84946,\n            \"At last, after a long pause, he said to me in a faint whisper:-\\u201cJack, is she really dead?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85095,\n            \"so he went back and took her dead hand in his and kissed it, and bent over and kissed her forehead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85118,\n            \"He came away, fondly looking back over his shoulder at her as he came.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85134,\n            \"I left him in the drawing-room, and told Van Helsing that he had said good-bye;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85155,\n            \"so the latter went to the kitchen to tell the undertaker\\u2019s men to proceed with the preparations and to screw up the coffin.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85181,\n            \"When he came out of the room again I told him of Arthur\\u2019s question, and he replied:-\\u201cI am not surprised.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85250,\n            \"but when we had lit our cigars he said-\\u201cLord-- \\\";\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85315,\n            \"\\u201d The Professor answered very sweetly:-\\u201cI only used that name because I was in doubt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85406,\n            \"And let me say that I am at a loss for words to thank you for your goodness to my poor dear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85429,\n            \"\\u201d He paused a moment, and went on: \\u201cI know that she understood your goodness even better than I do;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85596,\n            \"Then you shall bless me from first to last for your own sake, and for the sake of others and for her dear sake to whom I swore to protect.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85652,\n            \"I know and believe you have a very noble heart, and you are Jack\\u2019s friend, and you were hers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85792,\n            \"I have a motive of which, be sure, she would have approved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85813,\n            \"I took them before we knew that all was yours, so that no strange hand might touch them-no strange eye look through words into her soul.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85886,\n            \"It\\u2019s a hard thing I ask, but you will do it, will you not, for Lucy\\u2019s sake?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85936,\n            \"I feel that in saying this I am doing what my dear one would have approved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86080,\n            \"He went to and fro, as if patrolling the house, and was never out of sight of the room where Lucy lay in her coffin, strewn with the wild garlic flowers, which sent, through the odour of lily and rose, a heavy, overpowering smell into the night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86657,\n            \"He was looking at her so hard that he did not see either of us, and so I had a good view of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87342,\n            \"and now a telegram from Van Helsing, whoever he may be:-\\u201cYou will be grieved to hear that Mrs. Westenra died five days ago, and that Lucy died the day before yesterday.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87483,\n            \"I believe in my heart of hearts that he suffered as much about Lucy\\u2019s death as any of us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87652,\n            \"When it was all over, we were standing beside Arthur, who, poor fellow, was speaking of his part in the operation where his blood had been transfused to his Lucy\\u2019s veins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87690,\n            \"I could see Van Helsing\\u2019s face grow white and purple by turns.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88530,\n            \"As he answered me his face grew stern, and he said in quite a different tone:-\\u201cOh, it was the grim irony of it all-this so lovely lady garlanded with flowers, that looked so fair as life, till one by one we wondered if she were truly dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88588,\n            \"she laid in that so fine marble house in that lonely churchyard, where rest so many of her kin, laid there with the mother who loved her, and whom she loved;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88767,\n            \"Said he not that the transfusion of his blood to her veins had made her truly his bride?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            88829,\n            \"Then this so sweet maid is a polyandrist, and me, with my poor wife dead to me, but alive by Church\\u2019s law, though no wits, all gone-even I, who am faithful husband to this now-no-wife, am bigamist.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90325,\n            \"(Confidence) \\u201cDear Madam,-\\u201cI pray you to pardon my writing, in that I am so far friend as that I sent to you sad news of Miss Lucy Westenra\\u2019s death.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90365,\n            \"By the kindness of Lord Godalming, I am empowered to read her letters and papers, for I am deeply concerned about certain matters vitally important.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90393,\n            \"In them I find some letters from you, which show how great friends you were and how you love her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90477,\n            \"I am friend of Dr. John Seward and of Lord Godalming (that was Arthur of Miss Lucy).\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90541,\n            \"I have read your letters to poor Lucy, and know how good you are and how your husband suffer;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90684,\n            \"and as he attended poor dear Lucy in her last illness, he can tell me all about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90789,\n            \"I had almost forgotten in my own affairs how ill she was afterwards.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90803,\n            \"She must have told him of her sleep-walking adventure on the cliff, and that I knew all about it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90826,\n            \"and now he wants me to tell him what she knows, so that he may understand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90860,\n            \"I should never forgive myself if any act of mine, were it even a negative one, brought harm on poor dear Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91030,\n            \"I am so glad I have type-written out my own journal, so that, in case he asks about Lucy, I can hand it to him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91260,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing must be a good man as well as a clever one if he is Arthur\\u2019s friend and Dr. Seward\\u2019s, and if they brought him all the way from Holland to look after Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91869,\n            \"I know that you were with her at Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91879,\n            \"She sometimes kept a diary-you need not look surprised, Madam Mina;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92254,\n            \"but I had been thinking that it was of dear Lucy that you wished to ask, and so that you might not have time to wait-not on my account, but because I know your time must be precious-I have written it out on the typewriter for you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95090,\n            \"And you, sir-I have read all the letters to poor Miss Lucy, and some of them speak of you, so I know you since some days from the knowing of others;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97565,\n            \"You think then that those so small holes in the children\\u2019s throats were made by the same that made the hole in Miss Lucy?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97887,\n            \"He went on:-\\u201cMy friend, it was because I wished to be gentle in the breaking to you, for I know you have loved that so sweet lady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98141,\n            \"Dr. Vincent, of the North Hospital, where the papers say the child is, is friend of mine, and I think of yours since you were in class at Amsterdam.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98229,\n            \"\\u201cAnd then we spend the night, you and I, in the churchyard where Lucy lies.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98321,\n            \"We found the child awake.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98344,\n            \"Dr. Vincent took the bandage from its throat, and showed us the punctures.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            98612,\n            \"When she asked him why he wanted to go, he said he wanted to play with the \\u2018 bloofer lady.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99221,\n            \"Holding his candle so that he could read the coffin plates, and so holding it that the sperm dropped in white patches which congealed as they touched the metal, he made assurance of Lucy\\u2019s coffin.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99330,\n            \"It seemed to be as much an affront to the dead as it would have been to have stripped off her clothing in her sleep whilst living;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99432,\n            \"I had expected a rush of gas from the week-old corpse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99606,\n            \"I felt all the dogged argumentativeness of my nature awake within me as I answered him:-\\u201cI am satisfied that Lucy\\u2019s body is not in that coffin;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            99710,\n            \"\\u201cSome of the undertaker\\u2019s people may have stolen it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100772,\n            \"Outrageous as it was to open a leaden coffin, to see if a woman dead nearly a week were really dead, it now seemed the height of folly to open the tomb again, when we knew, from the evidence of our own eyesight, that the coffin was empty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100896,\n            \"Van Helsing walked over to Lucy\\u2019s coffin, and I followed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100933,\n            \"There lay Lucy, seemingly just as we had seen her the night before her funeral.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100962,\n            \"and I could not believe that she was dead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101122,\n            \"so, with an attempt to argue of which I was even at the moment ashamed, I said:-\\u201cShe may have been placed here since last night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101233,\n            \"He was looking intently at the face of the dead woman, raising the eyelids and looking at the eyes, and once more opening the lips and examining the teeth.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101377,\n            \"Usually when the Un-Dead sleep at home \\\"-as he spoke he made a comprehensive sweep of his arm to designate what to a vampire was \\u201chome \\\"-\\\" their face show what they are, but this so sweet that was when she not Un-Dead she go back to the nothings of the common dead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101441,\n            \"There is no malign there, see, and so it make hard that I must kill her in her sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101564,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI shall cut off her head and fill her mouth with garlic, and I shall drive a stake through her body.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101589,\n            \"\\u201d It made me shudder to think of so mutilating the body of the woman whom I had loved.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101844,\n            \"if you, who saw the coffin empty last night and full to-day with a woman who have not change only to be more rose and more beautiful in a whole week, after she die-if you know of this and know of the white figure last night that brought the child to the churchyard, and yet of your own senses you did not believe, how, then, can I expect Arthur, who know none of those things, to believe?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101934,\n            \"He doubted me when I took him from her kiss when she was dying.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101991,\n            \"and that in most mistake of all we have killed her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102003,\n            \"He will then argue back that it is we, mistaken ones, that have killed her by our ideas;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102048,\n            \"And he will sometimes think that she he loved was buried alive, and that will paint his dreams with horrors of what she must have suffered;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102076,\n            \"and again, he will think that we may be right, and that his so beloved was, after all, an Un-Dead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102389,\n            \"It pleases me that the Un-Dead, Miss Lucy, shall not leave to-night, that so on the morrow night she may be more eager.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102420,\n            \"Therefore I shall fix some things she like not-garlic and a crucifix-and so seal up the door of the tomb.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102531,\n            \"For Miss Lucy or from her, I have no fear;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102543,\n            \"but that other to whom is there that she is Un-Dead, he have now the power to seek her tomb and find shelter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102570,\n            \"He is cunning, as I know from Mr. Jonathan and from the way that all along he have fooled us when he played with us for Miss Lucy\\u2019s life, and we lost;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102631,\n            \"even we four who gave our strength to Miss Lucy it also is all to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102708,\n            \"his hunting ground is more full of game than the churchyard where the Un-Dead woman sleep, and the one old man watch.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104071,\n            \"\\u201cI did not say she was alive, my child;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104089,\n            \"I go no further than to say that she might be Un-Dead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104170,\n            \"May I cut off the head of dead Miss Lucy?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104299,\n            \"I have a duty to do in protecting her grave from outrage;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106635,\n            \"but Lucy\\u2019s eyes unclean and full of hell-fire, instead of the pure, gentle orbs we knew.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107924,\n            \"But there was no love in my own heart, nothing but loathing for the foul Thing which had taken Lucy\\u2019s shape without her soul.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108003,\n            \"But wait a while, and you all see her as she was, and is.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108020,\n            \"\\u201d She seemed like a nightmare of Lucy as she lay there;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108415,\n            \"or again, last night when you open your arms to her, you would in time, when you had died, have become nosferatu, as they call it in Eastern Europe, and would all time make more of those Un-Deads that so have fill us with horror.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108570,\n            \"But of the most blessed of all, when this now Un-Dead be made to rest as true dead, then the soul of the poor lady whom we love shall again be free.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108677,\n            \"Will it be no joy to think of hereafter in the silence of the night when sleep is not: \\u2018 It was my hand that sent her to the stars;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108709,\n            \"it was the hand of him that loved her best;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108758,\n            \"He saw, too, what we all did, the infinite kindness which suggested that his should be the hand which would restore Lucy to us as a holy, and not an unholy, memory;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109470,\n            \"There, in the coffin lay no longer the foul Thing that we had so dreaded and grown to hate that the work of her destruction was yielded as a privilege to the one best entitled to it, but Lucy as we had seen her in her life, with her face of unequalled sweetness and purity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109552,\n            \"but these were all dear to us, for they marked her truth to what we knew.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109678,\n            \"God bless you that you have given my dear one her soul again, and me peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109727,\n            \"When he raised his head Van Helsing said to him:-\\u201cAnd now, my child, you may kiss her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109751,\n            \"Kiss her dead lips if you will, as she would have you to, if for her to choose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110327,\n            \"\\u201cAh, that wonderful Madam Mina,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cpearl among women!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110395,\n            \"over it he told me of a diary kept by Jonathan Harker when abroad, and gave me a typewritten copy of it, as also of Mrs. Harker\\u2019s diary at Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110743,\n            \"\\u201cI knew you from the description of poor dear Lucy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111291,\n            \"and as it is entirely-almost entirely-about my cases, it may be awkward-that is, I mean--\\u201dHe stopped, and I tried to help him out of his embarrassment:-\\u201cYou helped to attend dear Lucy at the end.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111343,\n            \"Let me hear how she died;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111350,\n            \"for all that I know of her, I shall be very grateful.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111364,\n            \"She was very, very dear to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111373,\n            \"\\u201d To my surprise, he answered, with a horrorstruck look in his face:-\\u201cTell you of her death?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111918,\n            \"I know that Lucy told you of me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111927,\n            \"she told me of you too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112507,\n            \"and I see already, though your diary only took me to 7 September, how poor Lucy was beset, and how her terrible doom was being wrought out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112672,\n            \"but if you have so far travelled on the road to poor Lucy\\u2019s death, you will not be content, I know, to remain in the dark.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112901,\n            \"When the terrible story of Lucy\\u2019s death, and-and all that followed, was done, I lay back in my chair powerless.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112977,\n            \"My brain was all in a whirl, and only that there came through all the multitude of horrors, the holy ray of light that my dear, dear Lucy was at last at peace, I do not think I could have borne it without making a scene.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115277,\n            \"- Mina and I have worked all day, and we have put all the papers into order.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115566,\n            \"It was to me a painful meeting, for it brought back all poor dear Lucy\\u2019s hopes of only a few months ago.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115592,\n            \"Of course they had heard Lucy speak of me, and it seemed that Dr. Van Helsing, too, has been quite \\u201cblowing my trumpet,\\u201das Mr. Morris expressed it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115629,\n            \"Poor fellows, neither of them is aware that I know all about the proposals they made to Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115712,\n            \"I knew from Dr. Seward\\u2019s diary that they had been at Lucy\\u2019s death-her real death-and that I need not fear to betray any secret before the time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116093,\n            \"I said to him, for I could see that his heart was breaking:-\\u201cI loved dear Lucy, and I know what she was to you, and what you were to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116131,\n            \"She and I were like sisters;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116138,\n            \"and now she is gone, will you not let me be like a sister to you in your trouble?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116176,\n            \"If sympathy and pity can help in your affliction, won\\u2019t you let me be of some little service-for Lucy\\u2019s sake?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116562,\n            \"You will let me be like a brother, will you not, for all our lives-for dear Lucy\\u2019s sake?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116587,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cFor dear Lucy\\u2019s sake,\\u201dI said as we clasped hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117024,\n            \"\\\"-the very words he had used to Lucy, and oh, but he proved himself a friend!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118456,\n            \"Poor Art seemed more cheerful than he has been since Lucy first took ill, and Quincey is more like his own bright self than he has been for many a long day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118924,\n            \"\\u201d he said, \\u201cfor then we might have reached him in time to save poor Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131458,\n            \"till, as I looked, the fire divided, and seemed to shine on me through the fog like two red eyes, such as Lucy told me of in her momentary mental wandering when, on the cliff, the dying sunlight struck the windows of St.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170369,\n            \"for we can open the box and make sure of him, as we did of poor Lucy, before he wakes.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[1, 17]\": [\n        [\n            26730,\n            \"I have been working very hard lately, because I want to keep up with Jonathan\\u2019s studies, and I have been practising shorthand very assiduously.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26759,\n            \"When we are married I shall be able to be useful to Jonathan, and if I can stenograph well enough I can take down what he wants to say in this way and write it out for him on the typewriter, at which also I am practising very hard.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26811,\n            \"He and I sometimes write letters in shorthand, and he is keeping a stenographic journal of his travels abroad.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            26915,\n            \"I may show it to Jonathan some day if there is in it anything worth sharing, but it is really an exercise book.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27006,\n            \"I have just had a few hurried lines from Jonathan from Transylvania.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27032,\n            \"I am longing to hear all his news.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27051,\n            \"I wonder if we-I mean Jonathan and I-shall ever see them together.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27295,\n            \"We met some time ago a man that would just do for you, if you were not already engaged to Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27644,\n            \"I love him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27648,\n            \"I am blushing as I write, for although I think he loves me, he has not told me so in words.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27672,\n            \"But oh, Mina, I love him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27681,\n            \"I love him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            27685,\n            \"I love him!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28084,\n            \"Well, I must tell you about the three, but you must keep it a secret, dear, from every one, except, of course, Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28115,\n            \"You will tell him, because I would, if I were in your place, certainly tell Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28669,\n            \"\\u201cArthur has just gone, and I feel in better spirits than when I left off, so I can go on telling you about the day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28816,\n            \"No, I don\\u2019t, for there was Mr. Morris telling us his stories, and Arthur never told any, and yet-- My dear, I am somewhat previous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28874,\n            \"No, he doesn\\u2019t, for Arthur tried twice to make a chance, and I helping him all I could;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29031,\n            \"I do not know if Arthur likes it, as I have never heard him use any as yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34153,\n            \"and she told me all over again about Arthur and their coming marriage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34167,\n            \"That made me just a little heart-sick, for I haven\\u2019t heard from Jonathan for a whole month.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34213,\n            \"I hope there cannot be anything the matter with Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34369,\n            \"I wonder where Jonathan is and if he is thinking of me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            34382,\n            \"I wish he were here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36216,\n            \"I am unhappy about Lucy and about Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36225,\n            \"I had not heard from Jonathan for some time, and was very concerned;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36240,\n            \"but yesterday dear Mr. Hawkins, who is always so kind, sent me a letter from him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36487,\n            \"I sympathise with her, for I do the same, only Jonathan and I will start in life in a very simple way, and shall have to try to make both ends meet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36626,\n            \"I am getting quite uneasy about him, though why I should I do not know;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36643,\n            \"but I do wish that he would write, if it were only a single line.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36801,\n            \"- Another week gone, and no news from Jonathan, not even to Mr. Hawkins, from whom I have heard.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36825,\n            \"Oh, I do hope he is not ill.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36841,\n            \"I look at that last letter of his, but somehow it does not satisfy me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36972,\n            \"but no one has heard a word of Jonathan since that last letter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43847,\n            \"Somehow I felt glad that Jonathan was not on the sea last night, but on land.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            43883,\n            \"I am getting fearfully anxious about him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45102,\n            \"I should be quite happy if I only knew if Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            45117,\n            \"God bless and keep him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47299,\n            \"All her old gaiety of manner seemed to have come back, and she came and snuggled in beside me and told me all about Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47326,\n            \"I told her how anxious I was about Jonathan, and then she tried to comfort me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47953,\n            \"I walked along the cliffs to the westward, and was full of sweet sadness, for I was thinking of Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48490,\n            \"No news from Jonathan, and Lucy seems to be growing weaker, whilst her mother\\u2019s hours are numbering to a close.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            49947,\n            \"I am to leave in the morning and go over to Jonathan, and to help to nurse him if necessary, and to bring him home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50019,\n            \"It is of Jonathan, and must be next my heart, for he is in my heart.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50089,\n            \"I must keep it to say to Jonathan, my husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50101,\n            \"The letter that he has seen and touched must comfort me till we meet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50144,\n            \"\\u201cDear Madam,-\\u201cI write by desire of Mr. Jonathan Harker, who is himself not strong enough to write, though progressing well, thanks to God and St.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50185,\n            \"He has been under our care for nearly six weeks, suffering from a violent brain fever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50203,\n            \"He wishes me to convey his love, and to say that by this post I write for him to Mr. Peter Hawkins, Exeter, to say, with his dutiful respects, that he is sorry for his delay, and that all of his work is completed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50255,\n            \"He will require some few weeks\\u2019 rest in our sanatorium in the hills, but will then return.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50275,\n            \"He wishes me to say that he has not sufficient money with him, and that he would like to pay for his staying here, so that others who need shall not be wanting for help.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50335,\n            \"- My patient being asleep, I open this to let you know something more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50351,\n            \"He has told me all about you, and that you are shortly to be his wife.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50375,\n            \"He has had some fearful shock-so says our doctor-and in his delirium his ravings have been dreadful;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50454,\n            \"We should have written long ago, but we knew nothing of his friends, and there was on him nothing that any one could understand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50481,\n            \"He came in the train from Klausenburg, and the guard was told by the station-master there that he rushed into the station shouting for a ticket for home.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50513,\n            \"Seeing from his violent demeanour that he was English, they gave him a ticket for the furthest station on the way thither that the train reached.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50562,\n            \"He is truly getting on well, and I have no doubt will in a few weeks be all himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50660,\n            \"The attendant was struck by his manner, and knowing my interest in him, encouraged him to talk.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50680,\n            \"He is usually respectful to the attendant and at times servile;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50692,\n            \"but to-night, the man tells me, he was quite haughty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50717,\n            \"All he would say was:-\\u201cI don\\u2019t want to talk to you: you don\\u2019t count now;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50748,\n            \"\\u201d The attendant thinks it is some sudden form of religious mania which has seized him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50797,\n            \"At nine o\\u2019clock I visited him myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50807,\n            \"His attitude to me was the same as that to the attendant;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50820,\n            \"in his sublime self-feeling the difference between myself and attendant seemed to him as nothing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50838,\n            \"It looks like religious mania, and he will soon think that he himself is God.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50927,\n            \"I did not pretend to be watching him, but I kept strict observation all the same.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            50945,\n            \"All at once that shifty look came into his eyes which we always see when a madman has seized an idea, and with it the shifty movement of the head and back which asylum attendants come to know so well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51014,\n            \"I thought I would find out if his apathy were real or only assumed, and tried to lead him to talk of his pets, a theme which had never failed to excite his attention.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51088,\n            \"\\u201cYou don\\u2019t mean to tell me you don\\u2019t care about spiders?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51127,\n            \") To this he answered enigmatically:-\\u201cThe bride-maidens rejoice the eyes that wait the coming of the bride;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51170,\n            \"\\u201d He would not explain himself, but remained obstinately seated on his bed all the time I remained with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51307,\n            \"I had lain tossing about, and had heard the clock strike only twice, when the night-watchman came to me, sent up from the ward, to say that Renfield had escaped.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51367,\n            \"Those ideas of his might work out dangerously with strangers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51385,\n            \"He said he had seen him not ten minutes before, seemingly asleep in his bed, when he had looked through the observation-trap in the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51429,\n            \"He ran back and saw his feet disappear through the window, and had at once sent up for me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51465,\n            \"The attendant thought it would be more useful to watch where he should go than to follow him, as he might lose sight of him whilst getting out of the building by the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51605,\n            \"I ran back at once, told the watchman to get three or four men immediately and follow me into the grounds of Carfax, in case our friend might be dangerous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51656,\n            \"I could see Renfield\\u2019s figure just disappearing behind the angle of the house, so I ran after him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51678,\n            \"On the far side of the house I found him pressed close against the old ironbound oak door of the chapel.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51700,\n            \"He was talking, apparently to some one, but I was afraid to go near enough to hear what he was saying, lest I might frighten him, and he should run off.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            51759,\n            \"After a few minutes, however, I could see that he did not take note of anything around him, and so ventured to draw nearer to him-the more so as my men had now crossed the wall and were closing him in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52205,\n            \"I feel that I can hardly recall anything of the journey, except that I knew I was coming to Jonathan, and, that as I should have to do some nursing, I had better get all the sleep I could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52252,\n            \"I found my dear one, oh, so thin and pale and weak-looking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52269,\n            \"All the resolution has gone out of his dear eyes, and that quiet dignity which I told you was in his face has vanished.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52320,\n            \"At least, he wants me to believe so, and I shall never ask.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52336,\n            \"He has had some terrible shock, and I fear it might tax his poor brain if he were to try to recall it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52361,\n            \"Sister Agatha, who is a good creature and a born nurse, tells me that he raved of dreadful things whilst he was off his head.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52443,\n            \"She is a sweet, good soul, and the next day, when she saw I was troubled, she opened up the subject again, and after saying that she could never mention what my poor dear raved about, added: \\u2018 I can tell you this much, my dear: that it was not about anything which he has done wrong himself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52527,\n            \"He has not forgotten you or what he owes to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52555,\n            \"\\u2019 I do believe the dear soul thought I might be jealous lest my poor dear should have fallen in love with any other girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52581,\n            \"The idea of my being jealous about Jonathan!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52621,\n            \"I am now sitting by his bedside, where I can see his face while he sleeps.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52646,\n            \"\\u201cWhen he woke he asked me for his coat, as he wanted to get something from the pocket;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52667,\n            \"I asked Sister Agatha, and she brought all his things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52679,\n            \"I saw that amongst them was his note-book, and was going to ask him to let me look at it-for I knew then that I might find some clue to his trouble-but I suppose he must have seen my wish in my eyes, for he sent me over to the window, saying he wanted to be quite alone for a moment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52750,\n            \"Then he called me back, and when I came he had his hand over the note-book, and he said to me very solemnly:-\\u201c\\u2018 Wilhelmina\\u2019- I knew then that he was in deadly earnest, for he has never called me by that name since he asked me to marry him-\\u2018 you know, dear, my ideas of the trust between husband and wife: there should be no secret, no concealment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52836,\n            \"I have had a great shock, and when I try to think of what it is I feel my head spin round, and I do not know if it was all real or the dreaming of a madman.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52877,\n            \"You know I have had brain fever, and that is to be mad.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52906,\n            \"I want to take up my life here, with our marriage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52939,\n            \"\\u2018 Are you willing, Wilhelmina, to share my ignorance?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53004,\n            \"\\u2019 He fell back exhausted, and I put the book under his pillow, and kissed him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53069,\n            \"We are to be married in an hour, or as soon after as Jonathan awakes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53204,\n            \"When the chaplain and the sisters had left me alone with my husband-oh, Lucy, it is the first time I have written the words \\u2018 my husband\\u2019- left me alone with my husband, I took the book from under his pillow, and wrapped it up in white paper, and tied it with a little bit of pale blue ribbon which was round my neck, and sealed it over the knot with sealing-wax, and for my seal I used my wedding ring.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53299,\n            \"Then I kissed it and showed it to my husband, and told him that I would keep it so, and then it would be an outward and visible sign for us all our lives that we trusted each other;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53341,\n            \"that I would never open it unless it were for his own dear sake or for the sake of some stern duty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53364,\n            \"Then he took my hand in his, and oh, Lucy, it was the first time he took his wife\\u2019s hand, and said that it was the dearest thing in all the wide world, and that he would go through all the past again to win it, if need be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53422,\n            \"The poor dear meant to have said a part of the past, but he cannot think of time yet, and I shall not wonder if at first he mixes up not only the month, but the year.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53463,\n            \"\\u201cWell, my dear, what could I say?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53474,\n            \"I could only tell him that I was the happiest woman in all the wide world, and that I had nothing to give him except myself, my life, and my trust, and that with these went my love and duty for all the days of my life.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53526,\n            \"And, my dear, when he kissed me, and drew me to him with his poor weak hands, it was like a very solemn pledge between us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53750,\n            \"I must stop, for Jonathan is waking-I must attend to my husband!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53790,\n            \"\\u201cMy dearest Mina,-\\u201cOceans of love and millions of kisses, and may you soon be in your own home with your husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77468,\n            \"Well, I got my husband back all right;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77616,\n            \"\\u2019 I cried, Lucy dear, as Jonathan and the old man clasped hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77742,\n            \"for, now that Jonathan is a partner, Mr. Hawkins wants to tell him all about the clients.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77834,\n            \"even now he sometimes starts out of his sleep in a sudden way and awakes all trembling until I can coax him back to his usual placidity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77970,\n            \"Jonathan asks me to send his \\u2018 respectful duty,\\u2019but I do not think that is good enough from the junior partner of the important firm Hawkins & Harker;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78002,\n            \"and so, as you love me, and he loves me, and I love you with all the moods and tenses of the verb, I send you simply his \\u2018 love\\u2019instead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79364,\n            \"It is not only that he feels sorrow, deep sorrow, for the dear, good man who has befriended him all his life, and now at the end has treated him like his own son and left him a fortune which to people of our modest bringing up is wealth beyond the dream of avarice, but Jonathan feels it on another account.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79473,\n            \"But it is here that the grave shock that he experienced tells upon him the most.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79569,\n            \"but, Lucy dear, I must tell some one, for the strain of keeping up a brave and cheerful appearance to Jonathan tries me, and I have no one here that I can confide in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79648,\n            \"As there are no relations at all, Jonathan will have to be chief mourner.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86154,\n            \"It seems only yesterday that the last entry was made, and yet how much between then, in Whitby and all the world before me, Jonathan away and no news of him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86189,\n            \"and now, married to Jonathan, Jonathan a solicitor, a partner, rich, master of his business, Mr. Hawkins dead and buried, and Jonathan with another attack that may harm him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86227,\n            \"Some day he may ask me about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86284,\n            \"There were only ourselves and the servants there, one or two old friends of his from Exeter, his London agent, and a gentleman representing Sir John Paxton, the President of the Incorporated Law Society.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86323,\n            \"Jonathan and I stood hand in hand, and we felt that our best and dearest friend was gone from us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86364,\n            \"Jonathan thought it would interest me to go into the Row for a while, so we sat down;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86427,\n            \"Jonathan was holding me by the arm, the way he used to in old days before I went to school.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86483,\n            \"but it was Jonathan, and he was my husband, and we didn\\u2019t know anybody who saw us-and we didn\\u2019t care if they did-so on we walked.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86520,\n            \"I was looking at a very beautiful girl, in a big cart-wheel hat, sitting in a victoria outside Guiliano\\u2019s, when I felt Jonathan clutch my arm so tight that he hurt me, and he said under his breath: \\u201cMy God!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86571,\n            \"\\u201d I am always anxious about Jonathan, for I fear that some nervous fit may upset him again;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86591,\n            \"so I turned to him quickly, and asked him what it was that disturbed him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86727,\n            \"Jonathan kept staring at him, till I was afraid he would notice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86741,\n            \"I feared he might take it ill, he looked so fierce and nasty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86756,\n            \"I asked Jonathan why he was disturbed, and he answered, evidently thinking that I knew as much about it as he did: \\u201cDo you see who it is?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86789,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cNo, dear,\\u201dI said;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86811,\n            \"\\u201d His answer seemed to shock and thrill me, for it was said as if he did not know that it was to me, Mina, to whom he was speaking:-\\u201cIt is the man himself!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86867,\n            \"I do believe that if he had not had me to lean on and to support him he would have sunk down.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86947,\n            \"Jonathan kept looking after him, and said, as if to himself:-\\u201cI believe it is the Count, but he has grown young.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87002,\n            \"\\u201d He was distressing himself so much that I feared to keep his mind on the subject by asking him any questions, so I remained silent.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87030,\n            \"I drew him away quietly, and he, holding my arm, came easily.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87085,\n            \"After a few minutes\\u2019 staring at nothing, Jonathan\\u2019s eyes closed, and he went quietly into a sleep, with his head on my shoulder.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87115,\n            \"I thought it was the best thing for him, so did not disturb him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87131,\n            \"In about twenty minutes he woke up, and said to me quite cheerfully:-\\u201cWhy, Mina, have I been asleep!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87180,\n            \"\\u201d He had evidently forgotten all about the dark stranger, as in his illness he had forgotten all that this episode had reminded him of.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87228,\n            \"I must not ask him, for fear I shall do more harm than good;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87244,\n            \"but I must somehow learn the facts of his journey abroad.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87277,\n            \"Oh, Jonathan, you will, I know, forgive me if I do wrong, but it is for your own dear sake.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89825,\n            \"I am so glad that he has plenty of work to do, for that keeps his mind off the terrible things;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89848,\n            \"and oh, I am rejoiced that he is not now weighed down with the responsibility of his new position.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89869,\n            \"I knew he would be true to himself, and now how proud I am to see my Jonathan rising to the height of his advancement and keeping pace in all ways with the duties that come upon him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89928,\n            \"My household work is done, so I shall take his foreign journal, and lock myself up in my room and read it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89971,\n            \"that terrible record of Jonathan\\u2019s upset me so.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90035,\n            \"I suppose I shall never know, for I dare not open the subject to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90063,\n            \"He seemed quite certain of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90076,\n            \"I suppose it was the funeral upset him and sent his mind back on some train of thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90240,\n            \"then, perhaps, if I am ready, poor Jonathan may not be upset, for I can speak for him and never let him be troubled or worried with it at all.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90275,\n            \"If ever Jonathan quite gets over the nervousness he may want to tell me of it all, and I can ask him questions and find out things, and see how I may comfort him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90646,\n            \"- I cannot help feeling terribly excited as the time draws near for the visit of Dr. Van Helsing, for somehow I expect that it will throw some light upon Jonathan\\u2019s sad experience;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90939,\n            \"Perhaps it was reading the journal yesterday that upset me, and then Jonathan went away this morning to stay away from me a whole day and night, the first time we have been parted since our marriage.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91322,\n            \"When he comes to-morrow I shall ask him about Jonathan;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92802,\n            \"Your husband is noble nature, and you are noble too, for you trust, and trust cannot be where there is mean nature.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92855,\n            \"\\u201d I saw here an opening to ask him about Jonathan, so I said:-\\u201cHe was almost recovered, but he has been greatly upset by Mr. Hawkins\\u2019 s death.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92916,\n            \"\\u201d I went on:-\\u201cI suppose this upset him, for when we were in town on Thursday last he had a sort of shock.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93005,\n            \"The pity for Jonathan, the horror which he experienced, the whole fearful mystery of his diary, and the fear that has been brooding over me ever since, all came in a tumult.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93042,\n            \"I suppose I was hysterical, for I threw myself on my knees and held up my hands to him, and implored him to make my husband well again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93286,\n            \"I promise you that I will gladly do all for him that I can-all to make his life strong and manly, and your life a happy one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93331,\n            \"Husband Jonathan would not like to see you so pale;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93357,\n            \"Therefore for his sake you must eat and smile.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93426,\n            \"And then, too, you will tell me of husband Jonathan\\u2019s trouble so far as you can, but not yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93463,\n            \"\\u201d After lunch, when we went back to the drawing-room, he said to me:-\\u201cAnd now tell me all about him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93492,\n            \"\\u201d When it came to speaking to this great learned man, I began to fear that he would think me a weak fool, and Jonathan a madman-that journal is all so strange-and I hesitated to go on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93536,\n            \"But he was so sweet and kind, and he had promised to help, and I trusted him, so I said:-\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, what I have to tell you is so queer that you must not laugh at me or at my husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93782,\n            \"It will tell you my trouble and Jonathan\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93860,\n            \"\\u201cI shall in the morning, so soon as I can, come to see you and your husband, if I may.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93885,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cJonathan will be here at half-past eleven, and you must come to lunch with us and see him then;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93929,\n            \"\\u201d He was surprised at my knowledge of the trains off-hand, but he does not know that I have made up all the trains to and from Exeter, so that I may help Jonathan in case he is in a hurry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94022,\n            \"\\u201cDear Madam Mina,-\\u201cI have read your husband\\u2019s so wonderful diary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94072,\n            \"but for him and you there is no dread.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94082,\n            \"He is a noble fellow;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94088,\n            \"and let me tell you from experience of men, that one who would do as he did in going down that wall and to that room-ay, and going a second time-is not one to be injured in permanence by a shock.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110395,\n            \"over it he told me of a diary kept by Jonathan Harker when abroad, and gave me a typewritten copy of it, as also of Mrs. Harker\\u2019s diary at Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112538,\n            \"Jonathan and I have been working day and night since Professor Van Helsing saw us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113028,\n            \"It is all so wild, and mysterious, and strange that if I had not known Jonathan\\u2019s experience in Transylvania I could not have believed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113121,\n            \"I have sent a telegram to Jonathan to come on here when he arrives in London from Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113319,\n            \"Before I left him I remembered what Jonathan put in his diary of the Professor\\u2019s perturbation at reading something in an evening paper at the station at Exeter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115318,\n            \"It is, I suppose, the reaction from the haunting fear which I have had: that this terrible affair and the reopening of his old wound might act detrimentally on Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115352,\n            \"I saw him leave for Whitby with as brave a face as I could, but I was sick with apprehension.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115405,\n            \"It is just as that dear, good Professor Van Helsing said: he is true grit, and he improves under strain that would kill a weaker nature.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115544,\n            \"Dr. Seward was out on business, and had taken Jonathan with him, so I had to see them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            119438,\n            \"Jonathan sat next to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120222,\n            \"\\u201d Whilst he was speaking, Jonathan had taken my hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120234,\n            \"I feared, oh so much, that the appalling nature of our danger was overcoming him when I saw his hand stretch out;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120259,\n            \"but it was life to me to feel its touch-so strong, so self-reliant, so resolute.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120307,\n            \"When the Professor had done speaking my husband looked in my eyes, and I in his;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120430,\n            \"Jonathan held my right with his left and stretched across to Mr. Morris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121093,\n            \"he make in the mirror no reflect, as again Jonathan observe.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121106,\n            \"He has the strength of many of his hand-witness again Jonathan when he shut the door against the wolfs, and when he help him from the diligence too.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            121251,\n            \"He come on moonlight rays as elemental dust-as again Jonathan saw those sisters in the castle of Dracula.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122190,\n            \"We know from the inquiry of Jonathan that from the castle to Whitby came fifty boxes of earth, all of which were delivered at Carfax;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126935,\n            \"He turned to me and said:-\\u201cYou know this place, Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            126951,\n            \"You have copied maps of it, and you know it at least more than we do.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130078,\n            \"This morning I slept late after the fatigues of yesterday, and though Jonathan was late too, he was the earlier.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130101,\n            \"He spoke to me before he went out, never more sweetly or tenderly, but he never mentioned a word of what had happened in the visit to the Count\\u2019s house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130136,\n            \"And yet he must have known how terribly anxious I was.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130152,\n            \"I suppose it must have distressed him even more than it did me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130189,\n            \"But to think that he keeps anything from me!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130240,\n            \"Well, some day Jonathan will tell me all;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130250,\n            \"and lest it should ever be that he should think for a moment that I kept anything from him, I still keep my journal as usual.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130278,\n            \"Then if he has feared of my trust I shall show it to him, with every thought of my heart put down for his dear eyes to read.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130366,\n            \"I kept thinking over everything that has been ever since Jonathan came to see me in London, and it all seems like a horrible tragedy, with fate pressing on relentlessly to some destined end.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130488,\n            \"and if she hadn\\u2019t gone there at night and asleep, that monster couldn\\u2019t have destroyed her as he did.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130540,\n            \"I must hide it from Jonathan, for if he knew that I had been crying twice in one morning-I, who never cried on my own account, and whom he has never caused to shed a tear-the dear fellow would fret his heart out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130591,\n            \"I shall put a bold face on, and if I do feel weepy, he shall never see it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130874,\n            \"The poor man was more loud than ever, and though I could not distinguish a word he said, I could in some way recognise in his tones some passionate entreaty on his part.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130910,\n            \"Then there was the sound of a struggle, and I knew that the attendants were dealing with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130969,\n            \"but I must have fallen asleep, for, except dreams, I do not remember anything until the morning, when Jonathan woke me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            130995,\n            \"I think that it took me an effort and a little time to realise where I was, and that it was Jonathan who was bending over me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131050,\n            \"I thought that I was asleep, and waiting for Jonathan to come back.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131065,\n            \"I was very anxious about him, and I was powerless to act;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131513,\n            \"Suddenly the horror burst upon me that it was thus that Jonathan had seen those awful women growing into reality through the whirling mist in the moonlight, and in my dream I must have fainted, for all became black darkness.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131781,\n            \"In the afternoon Mr. Renfield asked if he might see me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131794,\n            \"Poor man, he was very gentle, and when I came away he kissed my hand and bade God bless me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131824,\n            \"I am crying when I think of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131846,\n            \"Jonathan would be miserable if he knew I had been crying.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            131944,\n            \"I could see from Jonathan\\u2019s manner that he had something important to communicate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            132000,\n            \"He very kindly made me up a sleeping draught, which he gave to me, telling me that it would do me no harm, as it was very mild.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143772,\n            \"\\u201d He dipped the end of a towel in cold water and with it began to flick him on the face, his wife all the while holding her face between her hands and sobbing in a way that was heart-breaking to hear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144176,\n            \"\\u201d His wife, through her terror and horror and distress, saw some sure danger to him: instantly forgetting her own grief, she seized hold of him and cried out:-\\u201cNo!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144216,\n            \"Jonathan, you must not leave me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144224,\n            \"I have suffered enough to-night, God knows, without the dread of his harming you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144243,\n            \"You must stay with me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144268,\n            \"and, he yielding to her, she pulled him down sitting on the bed side, and clung to him fiercely.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144360,\n            \"\\u201d She shuddered and was silent, holding down her head on her husband\\u2019s breast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144378,\n            \"When she raised it, his white night-robe was stained with blood where her lips had touched, and where the thin open wound in her neck had sent forth drops.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144412,\n            \"The instant she saw it she drew back, with a low wail, and whispered, amidst choking sobs:-\\u201cUnclean, unclean!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144439,\n            \"I must touch him or kiss him no more.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144449,\n            \"Oh, that it should be that it is I who am now his worst enemy, and whom he may have most cause to fear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144476,\n            \"\\u201d To this he spoke out resolutely:-\\u201cNonsense, Mina.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144502,\n            \"I would not hear it of you;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144510,\n            \"and I shall not hear it from you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144519,\n            \"May God judge me by my deserts, and punish me with more bitter suffering than even this hour, if by any act or will of mine anything ever come between us!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144553,\n            \"\\u201d He put out his arms and folded her to his breast;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144575,\n            \"He looked at us over her bowed head, with eyes that blinked damply above his quivering nostrils;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144601,\n            \"After a while her sobs became less frequent and more faint, and then he said to me, speaking with a studied calmness which I felt tried his nervous power to the utmost:-\\u201cAnd now, Dr. Seward, tell me all about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144682,\n            \"but his nostrils twitched and his eyes blazed as I told how the ruthless hands of the Count had held his wife in that terrible and horrid position, with her mouth to the open wound in his breast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144822,\n            \"so on nodding acquiescence to him he asked them what they had seen or done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145454,\n            \"\\u201d The poor, dear lady shivered, and I could see the tension of her nerves as she clasped her husband closer to her and bent her head lower and lower still on his breast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145525,\n            \"The other hand was locked in that of her husband, who held his other arm thrown round her protectingly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145625,\n            \"\\u201d Her husband involuntarily groaned as she turned to him and said lovingly: \\u201cDo not fret, dear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145646,\n            \"You must be brave and strong, and help me through the horrible task.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145661,\n            \"If you only knew what an effort it is to me to tell of this fearful thing at all, you would understand how much I need your help.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145742,\n            \"Jonathan coming in had not waked me, for he lay by my side when next I remember.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145821,\n            \"I turned to wake Jonathan, but found that he slept so soundly that it seemed as if it was he who had taken the sleeping draught, and not I.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145853,\n            \"I tried, but I could not wake him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145876,\n            \"Then indeed, my heart sank within me: beside the bed, as if he had stepped out of the mist-or rather as if the mist had turned into his figure, for it had entirely disappeared-stood a tall, thin man, all in black.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145928,\n            \"I knew him at once from the description of the others.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            145999,\n            \"I knew, too, the red scar on his forehead where Jonathan had struck him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146096,\n            \"With a mocking smile, he placed one hand upon my shoulder and, holding me tight, bared my throat with the other, saying as he did so, \\u2018 First, a little refreshment to reward my exertions.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146145,\n            \"it is not the first time, or the second, that your veins have appeased my thirst!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146164,\n            \"\\u2019 I was bewildered, and, strangely enough, I did not want to hinder him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146216,\n            \"He placed his reeking lips upon my throat!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146231,\n            \"She clasped his hand harder, and looked at him pityingly, as if he were the injured one, and went on:-\\u201cI felt my strength fading away, and I was in a half swoon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146313,\n            \"\\u201d The remembrance seemed for a while to overpower her, and she drooped and would have sunk down but for her husband\\u2019s sustaining arm.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146341,\n            \"With a great effort she recovered herself and went on:-\\u201cThen he spoke to me mockingly, \\u2018 And so you, like the others, would play your brains against mine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146377,\n            \"You would help these men to hunt me and frustrate me in my designs!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146392,\n            \"You know now, and they know in part already, and will know in full before long, what it is to cross my path.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146431,\n            \"Whilst they played wits against me-against me who commanded nations, and intrigued for them, and fought for them, hundreds of years before they were born-I was countermining them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146467,\n            \"And you, their best beloved one, are now to me, flesh of my flesh;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146548,\n            \"You have aided in thwarting me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146555,\n            \"now you shall come to my call.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146570,\n            \"\\u201d to you, you shall cross land or sea to do my bidding;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            146613,\n            \"When the blood began to spurt out, he took my hands in one of his, holding them tight, and with the other seized my neck and pressed my mouth to the wound, so that I must either suffocate or swallow some of the-- Oh my God!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157095,\n            \"\\u201cJonathan,\\u201dshe said, and the word sounded like music on her lips it was so full of love and tenderness, \\u201cJonathan dear, and you all my true, true friends, I want you to bear something in mind through all this dreadful time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157226,\n            \"You must be pitiful to him, too, though it may not hold your hands from his destruction.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157246,\n            \"\\u201d As she spoke I could see her husband\\u2019s face darken and draw together, as though the passion in him were shrivelling his being to its core.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157429,\n            \"Just think, my dear-I have been thinking all this long, long day of it-that.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158738,\n            \"friend Jonathan, we have got our dear Madam Mina, as of old, back to us to-day!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            159736,\n            \"We can know now what was in the Count\\u2019s mind, when he seize that money, though Jonathan\\u2019s so fierce knife put him in the danger that even he dread.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162548,\n            \"I dread Jonathan leaving me, and I know that he would surely go if the others went.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165927,\n            \"All at once Mina opened her eyes, and looking at me tenderly, said:-\\u201cJonathan, I want you to promise me something on your word of honour.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165960,\n            \"A promise made to me, but made holily in God\\u2019s hearing, and not to be broken though I should go down on my knees and implore you with bitter tears.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165995,\n            \"Quick, you must make it to me at once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166035,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cBut, dear one,\\u201dshe said, with such spiritual intensity that her eyes were like pole stars, \\u201cit is I who wish it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166073,\n            \"You can ask Dr. Van Helsing if I am not right;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166096,\n            \"Nay, more, if you all agree, later, you are absolved from the promise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166149,\n            \"She said:-\\u201cPromise me that you will not tell me anything of the plans formed for the campaign against the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173762,\n            \"See I read here what Jonathan have written:-\\u201cThat other of his race who, in a later age, again and again, brought his forces over The Great River into Turkey Land;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            178768,\n            \"Poor fellow, maybe he is thinking, and I can see his face all wrinkled up with the concentration of his thoughts.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180174,\n            \"When I had done reading, Jonathan took me in his arms and kissed me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180243,\n            \"Our enemy is at his most helpless;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180251,\n            \"and if we can come on him by day, on the water, our task will be over.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180271,\n            \"He has a start, but he is powerless to hasten, as he may not leave his box lest those who carry him may suspect;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180298,\n            \"for them to suspect would be to prompt them to throw him in the stream where he perish.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180350,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI shall get a steam launch and follow him,\\u201dsaid Lord Godalming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180627,\n            \"\\u201d He looked at Jonathan as he spoke, and Jonathan looked at me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180642,\n            \"I could see that the poor dear was torn about in his mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180656,\n            \"Of course he wanted to be with me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180756,\n            \"and again that it is your right to destroy him-that-which has wrought such woe to you and yours.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180864,\n            \"Now let me say that what I would is this: while you, my Lord Godalming and friend Jonathan go in your so swift little steamboat up the river, and whilst John and Quincey guard the bank where perchance he might be landed, I will take Madam Mina right into the heart of the enemy\\u2019s country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180926,\n            \"Whilst the old fox is tied in his box, floating on the running stream whence he cannot escape to land-where he dares not raise the lid of his coffin-box lest his Slovak carriers should in fear leave him to perish-we shall go in the track where Jonathan went,-from Bistritz over the Borgo, and find our way to the Castle of Dracula.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181060,\n            \"\\u201d Here Jonathan interrupted him hotly:-\\u201cDo you mean to say, Professor Van Helsing, that you would bring Mina, in her sad case and tainted as she is with that devil\\u2019s illness, right into the jaws of his death-trap?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181181,\n            \"Have you felt the Vampire\\u2019s lips upon your throat?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181193,\n            \"\\u201d Here he turned to me, and as his eyes lit on my forehead he threw up his arms with a cry: \\u201cOh, my God, what have we done to have this terror upon us!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181248,\n            \"The Professor\\u2019s voice, as he spoke in clear, sweet tones, which seemed to vibrate in the air, calmed us all:-\\u201cOh, my friend, it is because I would save Madam Mina from that awful place that I would go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181329,\n            \"We men here, all save Jonathan, have seen with their own eyes what is to be done before that place can be purify.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181363,\n            \"If the Count escape us this time-and he is strong and subtle and cunning-he may choose to sleep him for a century, and then in time our dear one \\\"-he took my hand-\\\" would come to him to keep him company, and would be as those others that you, Jonathan, saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181427,\n            \"You have told us of their gloating lips;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181436,\n            \"you heard their ribald laugh as they clutched the moving bag that the Count threw to them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181478,\n            \"My friend, is it not a dire need for the which I am giving, possibly my life?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181524,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo as you will,\\u201dsaid Jonathan, with a sob that shook him all over, \\u201cwe are in the hands of God!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181870,\n            \"Jonathan would not be happy unless I was armed like the rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183826,\n            \"He alone knows what may be, and I pray Him, with all the strength of my sad and humble soul, that He will watch over my beloved husband;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            183858,\n            \"that whatever may happen, Jonathan may know that I loved him and honoured him more than I can say, and that my latest and truest thought will be always for him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184240,\n            \"I am afraid to think of Jonathan, but somehow I have now no fear for him, or for myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            185432,\n            \"By-and-by we find all the things which Jonathan have note in that wonderful diary of him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            186407,\n            \"the frowning mountains seemed further away, and we were near the top of a steep-rising hill, on summit of which was such a castle as Jonathan tell of in his diary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187420,\n            \"Then they began to materialise till-if God have not take away my reason, for I saw it through my eyes-there were before me in actual flesh the same three women that Jonathan saw in the room, when they would have kissed his throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187503,\n            \"and as their laugh came through the silence of the night, they twined their arms and pointed to her, and said in those so sweet tingling tones that Jonathan said were of the intolerable sweetness of the water-glasses:-\\u201cCome, sister.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189865,\n            \"- It was late in the afternoon when the Professor and I took our way towards the east whence I knew Jonathan was coming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190227,\n            \"\\u201d he said, \\u201chere you will be in shelter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190239,\n            \"and if the wolves do come I can meet them one by one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190253,\n            \"\\u201d He brought in our furs, and made a snug nest for me, and got out some provisions and forced them upon me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190641,\n            \"In fear I turned to the Professor;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190649,\n            \"to my consternation, however, he was not there.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190660,\n            \"An instant later, I saw him below me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190670,\n            \"Round the rock he had drawn a circle, such as we had found shelter in last night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190689,\n            \"When he had completed it he stood beside me again, saying:-\\u201cAt least you shall be safe here from him!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190714,\n            \"\\u201d He took the glasses from me, and at the next lull of the snow swept the whole space below us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190737,\n            \"\\u201cSee,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cthey come quickly;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190763,\n            \"\\u201d He paused and went on in a hollow voice:-\\u201cThey are racing for the sunset.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190898,\n            \"I knew at all events that neither of them was Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190910,\n            \"At the same time I knew that Jonathan was not far off;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190946,\n            \"One of them I knew was Jonathan, and the other I took, of course, to be Lord Godalming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190980,\n            \"When I told the Professor he shouted in glee like a schoolboy, and, after looking intently till a snow fall made sight impossible, he laid his Winchester rifle ready for use against the boulder at the opening of our shelter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191024,\n            \"\\u201cThey are all converging,\\u201dhe said.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191402,\n            \"The Professor and I crouched down behind our rock, and held our weapons ready;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191418,\n            \"I could see that he was determined that they should not pass.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191507,\n            \"Instinctively they reined in, and at the instant Lord Godalming and Jonathan dashed up at one side and Dr. Seward and Mr. Morris on the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191745,\n            \"I should have felt terrible fear at seeing Jonathan in such danger, but that the ardour of battle must have been upon me as well as the rest of them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191840,\n            \"In the midst of this I could see that Jonathan on one side of the ring of men, and Quincey on the other, were forcing a way to the cart;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191929,\n            \"Jonathan\\u2019s impetuosity, and the manifest singleness of his purpose, seemed to overawe those in front of him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191951,\n            \"instinctively they cowered, aside and let him pass.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192018,\n            \"All the time I had been breathlessly watching Jonathan I had, with the tail of my eye, seen him pressing desperately forward, and had seen the knives of the gypsies flash as he won a way through them, and they cut at him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192089,\n            \"but as he sprang beside Jonathan, who had by now jumped from the cart, I could see that with his left hand he was clutching at his side, and that the blood was spurting through his fingers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192130,\n            \"He did not delay notwithstanding this, for as Jonathan, with desperate energy, attacked one end of the chest, attempting to prize off the lid with his great Kukri knife, he attacked the other frantically with his bowie.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192260,\n            \"I saw the Count lying within the box upon the earth, some of which the rude falling from the cart had scattered over him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192612,\n            \"Jonathan knelt behind him and the wounded man laid back his head on his shoulder.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 5]\": [\n        [\n            115592,\n            \"Of course they had heard Lucy speak of me, and it seemed that Dr. Van Helsing, too, has been quite \\u201cblowing my trumpet,\\u201das Mr. Morris expressed it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120346,\n            \"\\u201cCount me in, Professor,\\u201dsaid Mr. Quincey Morris, laconically as usual.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            122558,\n            \"\\u201d Without saying any more he took his seat, and the Professor began to resume his statement:-\\u201cWe must trace each of these boxes;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152298,\n            \"Godalming and Morris hurried off in a cab, we following in another.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152420,\n            \"Out of it, in leisurely fashion, got Lord Godalming and Morris;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153233,\n            \"When we had examined this last find, Lord Godalming and Quincey Morris taking accurate notes of the various addresses of the houses in the East and the South, took with them the keys in a great bunch, and set out to destroy the boxes in these places.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            153318,\n            \"- The time seemed terrible long whilst we were waiting for the coming of Godalming and Quincey Morris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166925,\n            \"We went to his room, and within a minute Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, and Mr. Morris were with us also.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 6]\": [\n        [\n            117056,\n            \"- I got home at five o\\u2019clock, and found that Godalming and Morris had not only arrived, but had already studied the transcript of the various diaries and letters which Harker and his wonderful wife had made and arranged.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 9]\": [\n        [\n            170745,\n            \"Morris and Godalming and I shall prevent interference, even if we have to use the arms which we shall have ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172315,\n            \"Quincey Morris tightened his belt with that quick movement which I knew so well;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 10]\": [\n        [\n            76996,\n            \"Quincey Morris said nothing about his intention, but I knew that all night long he patrolled round and round the house.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 11]\": [\n        [\n            145237,\n            \"but I saw a bat rise from Renfield\\u2019s window, and flap westward.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 12]\": [\n        [\n            167182,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI shall not wait for any opportunity,\\u201dsaid Morris.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 13]\": [\n        [\n            188100,\n            \"Oh, if only Morris and Seward were with us.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 14]\": [\n        [\n            117056,\n            \"- I got home at five o\\u2019clock, and found that Godalming and Morris had not only arrived, but had already studied the transcript of the various diaries and letters which Harker and his wonderful wife had made and arranged.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            170745,\n            \"Morris and Godalming and I shall prevent interference, even if we have to use the arms which we shall have ready.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181628,\n            \"I felt so thankful that Lord Godalming is rich, and that both he and Mr. Morris, who also has plenty of money, are willing to spend it so freely.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 16]\": [\n        [\n            28816,\n            \"No, I don\\u2019t, for there was Mr. Morris telling us his stories, and Arthur never told any, and yet-- My dear, I am somewhat previous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28907,\n            \"I must tell you beforehand that Mr. Morris doesn\\u2019t always speak slang-that is to say, he never does so to strangers or before them, for he is really well educated and has exquisite manners-but he found out that it amused me to hear him talk American slang, and whenever I was present, and there was no one to be shocked, he said such funny things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            28985,\n            \"I am afraid, my dear, he has to invent it all, for it fits exactly into whatever else he has to say.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29051,\n            \"Well, Mr. Morris sat down beside me and looked as happy and jolly as he could, but I could see all the same that he was very nervous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29083,\n            \"He took my hand in his, and said ever so sweetly:-\\u201c\\u2018 Miss Lucy, I know I ain\\u2019t good enough to regulate the fixin\\u2019s of your little shoes, but I guess if you wait till you find a man that is you will go join them seven young women with the lamps when you quit.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29149,\n            \"Won\\u2019t you just hitch up alongside of me and let us go down the long road together, driving in double harness?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29282,\n            \"He really did look serious when he was saying it, and I couldn\\u2019t help feeling a bit serious too-I know, Mina, you will think me a horrid flirt-though I couldn\\u2019t help feeling a sort of exultation that he was number two in one day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29338,\n            \"And then, my dear, before I could say a word he began pouring out a perfect torrent of love-making, laying his very heart and soul at my feet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            29704,\n            \"\\u2019 I was right to speak to him so frankly, for quite a light came into his face, and he put out both his hands and took mine-I think I put them into his-and said in a hearty way:-\\u201c\\u2018 That\\u2019s my brave girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115592,\n            \"Of course they had heard Lucy speak of me, and it seemed that Dr. Van Helsing, too, has been quite \\u201cblowing my trumpet,\\u201das Mr. Morris expressed it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            117024,\n            \"\\\"-the very words he had used to Lucy, and oh, but he proved himself a friend!\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[4, 17]\": [\n        [\n            28816,\n            \"No, I don\\u2019t, for there was Mr. Morris telling us his stories, and Arthur never told any, and yet-- My dear, I am somewhat previous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120430,\n            \"Jonathan held my right with his left and stretched across to Mr. Morris.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191507,\n            \"Instinctively they reined in, and at the instant Lord Godalming and Jonathan dashed up at one side and Dr. Seward and Mr. Morris on the other.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            191840,\n            \"In the midst of this I could see that Jonathan on one side of the ring of men, and Quincey on the other, were forcing a way to the cart;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            192089,\n            \"but as he sprang beside Jonathan, who had by now jumped from the cart, I could see that with his left hand he was clutching at his side, and that the blood was spurting through his fingers.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 6]\": [\n        [\n            94242,\n            \"\\u201cMy dear Dr. Van Helsing,-\\u201cA thousand thanks for your kind letter, which has taken a great weight off my mind.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110673,\n            \"and I was beginning to feel uneasy, lest I might miss my guest, when a sweet-faced, dainty-looking girl stepped up to me, and, after a quick glance, said: \\u201cDr. Seward, is it not?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115801,\n            \"When Lord Godalming got his and turned it over-it does make a pretty good pile-he said:-\\u201cDid you write all this, Mrs. Harker?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115856,\n            \"but you people are all so good and kind, and have been working so earnestly and so energetically, that all I can do is to accept your ideas blindfold and try to help you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115916,\n            \"Besides, I know you loved my poor Lucy-\\u201d Here he turned away and covered his face with his hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118334,\n            \"Looking at my watch, I saw that I should go to the station to meet Van Helsing, so I told Mrs. Harker that it was time to leave.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118592,\n            \"\\u201d As I drove to the house I told him of what had passed, and of how my own diary had come to be of some use through Mrs. Harker\\u2019s suggestion;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154563,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing turned to him quickly and said:-\\u201cGod will act in His own way and time.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155429,\n            \"Van Helsing, Harker, and I were just behind the door, so that when it was opened the Professor could guard it whilst we two stepped between the incomer and the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157662,\n            \"Before they retired the Professor fixed up the room against any coming of the Vampire, and assured Mrs. Harker that she might rest in peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            165654,\n            \"\\u201d I thought that now was the time for Van Helsing to warn him not to disclose our plans to her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171979,\n            \"\\u201d I was about to ask him more, but Harker just then came in, and he held up a warning hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172950,\n            \"When the three men had gone out to their tasks Van Helsing asked Mrs. Harker to look up the copy of the diaries and find him the part of Harker\\u2019s journal at the Castle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173495,\n            \"\\u201d I thought that the Professor was going to break down and have hysterics, just as he had when Lucy died, but with a great effort he controlled himself and was at perfect nervous poise when Mrs. Harker tripped into the room, bright and happy-looking and, in the doing of work, seemingly forgetful of her misery.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173560,\n            \"As she came in, she handed a number of sheets of typewriting to Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174306,\n            \"Oh, my dear, I see that your eyes are opened, and that to you the lightning flash show all the leagues,\\u201dfor Mrs. Harker began to clap her hands and her eyes sparkled.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176046,\n            \"at last, in obedience to his will she made reply:-\\u201cAll is dark.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176431,\n            \"She said no more, even in answer to the Professor\\u2019s imperative questioning.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176662,\n            \"Speak, I command you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176677,\n            \"At the same time there was despair in his eyes, for the risen sun was reddening even Mrs. Harker\\u2019s pale face.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176703,\n            \"She opened her eyes, and we all started as she said, sweetly and seemingly with the utmost unconcern:-\\u201cOh, Professor, why ask me to do what you know I can\\u2019t?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176788,\n            \"I know nothing, only that I was lying here, half asleep, and heard you say go on!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176809,\n            \"speak, I command you!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176815,\n            \"\\u2019 It seemed so funny to hear you order me about, as if I were a bad child!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            176835,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cOh, Madam Mina,\\u201dhe said, sadly, \\u201cit is proof, if proof be needed, of how I love and honour you, when a word for your good, spoken more earnest than ever, can seem so strange because it is to order her whom I am proud to obey!\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 7]\": [\n        [\n            160726,\n            \"For my own part, now that his horrible danger is not face to face with us, it seems almost impossible to believe in it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161010,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing described what steps were taken during the day to discover on what boat and whither bound Count Dracula made his escape:-\\u201cAs I knew that he wanted to get back to Transylvania, I felt sure that he must go by the Danube mouth;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            161222,\n            \"\\u2019 said I, \\u2018 this is the ship whereon is the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162477,\n            \"\\u201d When Dr. Van Helsing had done speaking, I asked him if he were certain that the Count had remained on board the ship.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162528,\n            \"\\u201d I asked him again if it were really necessary that they should pursue the Count, for oh!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            162722,\n            \"I have told them how the measure of leaving his own barren land-barren of peoples-and coming to a new land where life of man teems till they are like the multitude of standing corn, was the work of centuries.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163035,\n            \"He have infect you-oh, forgive me, my dear, that I must say such;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            163225,\n            \"\\u201d He paused and I said:-\\u201cBut will not the Count take his rebuff wisely?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189303,\n            \"Before I began to restore these women to their dead selves through my awful work, I laid in Dracula\\u2019s tomb some of the Wafer, and so banished him from it, Un-Dead, for ever.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 8]\": [\n        [\n            118628,\n            \"at which the Professor interrupted me:-\\u201cAh, that wonderful Madam Mina!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118670,\n            \"The good God fashioned her for a purpose, believe me, when He made that so good combination.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171951,\n            \"He added significantly:-\\u201cI did not like that lethargy of Madam Mina\\u2019s.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173124,\n            \"In the moment when Madam Mina said those words that arrest both our understanding, an inspiration came to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173495,\n            \"\\u201d I thought that the Professor was going to break down and have hysterics, just as he had when Lucy died, but with a great effort he controlled himself and was at perfect nervous poise when Mrs. Harker tripped into the room, bright and happy-looking and, in the doing of work, seemingly forgetful of her misery.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173591,\n            \"Then holding the pages between his finger and thumb he said:-\\u201cFriend John, to you with so much of experience already-and you, too, dear Madam Mina, that are young-here is a lesson: do not fear ever to think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            184451,\n            \"he says I answered \\u201cdarkness, creaking wood and roaring water,\\u201dso the river is changing as they ascend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187680,\n            \"They could not approach, me, whilst so armed, nor Madam Mina whilst she remained within the ring, which she could not leave no more than they could enter.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187833,\n            \"Instinctively, with the dawn coming, I turned to Madam Mina, intending to hypnotise her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188320,\n            \"When I left Madam Mina sleeping within the Holy circle, I took my way to the castle.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189706,\n            \"When I stepped into the circle where Madam Mina slept, she woke from her sleep, and, seeing, me, cried out in pain that I had endured too much.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 9]\": [\n        [\n            59320,\n            \"I took advantage of the opportunity, and told her that my old master, Van Helsing, the great specialist, was coming to stay with me, and that I would put her in his charge conjointly with myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59479,\n            \"- The first thing Van Helsing said to me when we met at Liverpool Street was:-\\u201cHave you said anything to our young friend the lover of her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59611,\n            \"And, my good friend John, let me caution you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59713,\n            \"You and I shall keep as yet what we know here, and here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59758,\n            \"Later I shall unfold to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60054,\n            \"Then he went on, and very gravely:-\\u201cYou were always a careful student, and your case-book was ever more full than the rest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60091,\n            \"now you are master, and I trust that good habit have not fail.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64316,\n            \"I have to call on you yourself this time, friend John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65229,\n            \"Van Helsing returned in a couple of hours, and presently said to me: \\u201cNow you go home, and eat much and drink enough.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65278,\n            \"You and I must watch the case, and we must have none other to know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66000,\n            \"Come with me, friend John, and you shall help me deck the room with my garlic, which is all the way from Haarlem, where my friend Vanderpool raise herb in his glass-houses all the year.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66433,\n            \"To-morrow in the morning early you call for me, and we come together to see our pretty miss, so much more strong for my \\u2018 spell\\u2019which I have work.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79809,\n            \"I duly relieved Van Helsing in his watch over Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80055,\n            \"I could see that the Professor had carried out in this room, as in the other, his purpose of using the garlic;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80319,\n            \"Presently she woke, and I gave her food, as Van Helsing had prescribed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80458,\n            \"At six o\\u2019clock Van Helsing came to relieve me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80486,\n            \"When he saw Lucy\\u2019s face I could hear the sissing indraw of his breath, and he said to me in a sharp whisper: \\u201cDraw up the blind;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80557,\n            \"As he did so he started back, and I could hear his ejaculation, \\u201cMein Gott!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80631,\n            \"Then he turned to me and said calmly:-\\u201cShe is dying.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80739,\n            \"I assured him that Lucy was still asleep, but told him as gently as I could that both Van Helsing and I feared that the end was near.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80847,\n            \"\\u201d When we came into Lucy\\u2019s room I could see that Van Helsing had, with his usual forethought, been putting matters straight and making everything look as pleasing as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81156,\n            \"but at that instant Van Helsing, who, like me, had been startled by her voice, swooped upon him, and catching him by the neck with both hands, dragged him back with a fury of strength which I never thought he could have possessed, and actually hurled him almost across the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81288,\n            \"I kept my eyes fixed on Lucy, as did Van Helsing, and we saw a spasm as of rage flit like a shadow over her face;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81589,\n            \"I went back to the room, and found Van Helsing looking at poor Lucy, and his face was sterner than ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81699,\n            \"\\u201d I stood beside Van Helsing, and said:-\\u201cAh, well, poor girl, there is peace for her at last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81731,\n            \"\\u201d He turned to me, and said with grave solemnity:-\\u201cNot so;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81759,\n            \"\\u201d When I asked him what he meant, he only shook his head and answered:-\\u201cWe can do nothing as yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81822,\n            \"I attended to all the ghastly formalities, and the urbane undertaker proved that his staff were afflicted-or blessed-with something of his own obsequious suavity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81926,\n            \"\\u201d I noticed that Van Helsing never kept far away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81989,\n            \"Under the circumstances, Van Helsing and I took it upon ourselves to examine papers, etc.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82018,\n            \"I asked him why, for I feared that he, being a foreigner, might not be quite aware of English legal requirements, and so might in ignorance make some unnecessary trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82053,\n            \"He answered me:-\\u201cI know;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82065,\n            \"You forget that I am a lawyer as well as a doctor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82275,\n            \"I had hardly sealed the letter, when, to my surprise, Van Helsing walked into the room, saying:-\\u201cCan I help you, friend John?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82307,\n            \"I am free, and if I may, my service is to you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82332,\n            \"\\u201d I asked, to which he replied:-\\u201cI did not look for any specific thing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82421,\n            \"\\u201d When we had finished the work in hand, he said to me:-\\u201cAnd now, friend John, I think we may to bed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82451,\n            \"We want sleep, both you and I, and rest to recuperate.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82651,\n            \"He had not loved her as I had, and there was no need for tears in his eyes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82671,\n            \"He said to me: \\u201cRemain till I return,\\u201dand left the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82761,\n            \"I was undressing in my own room, when, with a premonitory tap at the door, he entered, and at once began to speak:-\\u201cTo-morrow I want you to bring me, before night, a set of post-mortem knives.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83098,\n            \"\\u201d For answer he put his hand on my shoulder, and said, with infinite tenderness:-\\u201cFriend John, I pity your poor bleeding heart;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103197,\n            \"\\u201cOh,\\u201dsaid the Professor, \\u201cthen you are nearer the beginning, both of you, than friend John here, who has to go a long way back before he can even get so far as to begin.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110112,\n            \"Then said the Professor as we moved off:-\\u201cTwo nights hence you shall meet with me and dine together at seven of the clock with friend John.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110172,\n            \"Friend John, you come with me home, for I have much to consult about, and you can help me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110218,\n            \"But first I shall have much to say, so that you may know what is to do and to dread.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118438,\n            \"\\u201d When I went to the station to meet Van Helsing I left the boys behind me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118504,\n            \"He saw me at once, and rushed up to me, saying:-\\u201cAh, friend John, how goes all?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            125695,\n            \"\\u201d Lord Godalming and I were silent, but Dr. Van Helsing added:-\\u201cFriend John, you know more of lunatics than I do, and I\\u2019m glad of it, for I fear that if it had been to me to decide I would before that last hysterical outburst have given him free.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171545,\n            \"Van Helsing and I were a little alarmed about Mrs. Harker to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171930,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing is terribly anxious, and told me just now that he fears the Count is escaping us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171979,\n            \"\\u201d I was about to ask him more, but Harker just then came in, and he held up a warning hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172470,\n            \"\\u201cYou forget-or perhaps you do not know, though Jonathan does and so does Dr. Van Helsing-that I am the train fiend.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172922,\n            \"but Van Helsing and I, turning to each other, met each a grave and troubled glance.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172995,\n            \"when the door was shut upon her he said to me:-\\u201cWe mean the same!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173044,\n            \"Do you know why I asked her to get the manuscript?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173093,\n            \"I want to tell you something.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173100,\n            \"And oh, my friend, I am taking a great-a terrible-risk;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173301,\n            \"there I have hope that our man-brains that have been of man so long and that have not lost the grace of God, will come higher than his child-brain that lie in his tomb for centuries, that grow not yet to our stature, and that do only work selfish and therefore small.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173495,\n            \"\\u201d I thought that the Professor was going to break down and have hysterics, just as he had when Lucy died, but with a great effort he controlled himself and was at perfect nervous poise when Mrs. Harker tripped into the room, bright and happy-looking and, in the doing of work, seemingly forgetful of her misery.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173591,\n            \"Then holding the pages between his finger and thumb he said:-\\u201cFriend John, to you with so much of experience already-and you, too, dear Madam Mina, that are young-here is a lesson: do not fear ever to think.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174385,\n            \"His finger and thumb closed on her pulse, as I thought instinctively and unconsciously, as she spoke:-\\u201cThe Count is a criminal and of criminal type.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            174687,\n            \"John and I know.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175256,\n            \"You must be scribe and write him all down, so that when the others return from their work you can give it to them;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180864,\n            \"Now let me say that what I would is this: while you, my Lord Godalming and friend Jonathan go in your so swift little steamboat up the river, and whilst John and Quincey guard the bank where perchance he might be landed, I will take Madam Mina right into the heart of the enemy\\u2019s country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188390,\n            \"Jonathan\\u2019s bitter experience served me here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            188399,\n            \"By memory of his diary I found my way to the old chapel, for I knew that here my work lay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189052,\n            \"but I go on searching until, presently, I find in a high great tomb as if made to one much beloved that other fair sister which, like Jonathan I had seen to gather herself out of the atoms of the mist.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189626,\n            \"For, friend John, hardly had my knife severed the head of each, before the whole body began to melt away and crumble in to its native dust, as though the death that should have come centuries agone had at last assert himself and say at once and loud \\u201cI am here!\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 11]\": [\n        [\n            124378,\n            \"Van Helsing was gazing at him with a look of utmost intensity, his bushy eyebrows almost meeting with the fixed concentration of his look.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124404,\n            \"He said to Renfield in a tone which did not surprise me at the time, but only when I thought of it afterwards-for it was as of one addressing an equal:-\\u201cCan you not tell frankly your real reason for wishing to be free to-night?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124458,\n            \"I will undertake that if you will satisfy even me-a stranger, without prejudice, and with the habit of keeping an open mind-Dr. Seward will give you, at his own risk and on his own responsibility, the privilege you seek.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124525,\n            \"The Professor went on:-\\u201cCome, sir, bethink yourself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            136245,\n            \"This morning, when I went to see him after his repulse of Van Helsing, his manner was that of a man commanding destiny.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            137119,\n            \"I would have taken him with me to see the patient, only I thought that after his last repulse he might not care to go again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            139968,\n            \"for, almost before he looked at the patient, he whispered to me:-\\u201cSend the attendant away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140865,\n            \"He moved convulsively, and as he did so, said:-\\u201cI\\u2019ll be quiet, Doctor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140961,\n            \"Then Van Helsing said in a quiet grave tone:-\\u201cTell us your dream, Mr. Renfield.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140982,\n            \"\\u201d As he heard the voice his face brightened, through its mutilation, and he said:-\\u201cThat is Dr. Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142067,\n            \"I was about to call him back to the point, but Van Helsing whispered to me: \\u201cLet him go on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142315,\n            \"Renfield went on without noticing:-\\u201cWhen Mrs. Harker came in to see me this afternoon she wasn\\u2019t the same;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142365,\n            \"he went on:-\\u201cI didn\\u2019t know that she was here till she spoke;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142403,\n            \"I like them with lots of blood in them, and hers had all seemed to have run out.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147094,\n            \"When Dr. Van Helsing and Dr. Seward had come back from seeing poor Renfield, we went gravely into what was to be done.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            147121,\n            \"First, Dr. Seward told us that when he and Dr. Van Helsing had gone down to the room below they had found Renfield lying on the floor, all in a heap.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 12]\": [\n        [\n            74885,\n            \"Van Helsing started angrily at the first sound, but his face softened and a glad look came into his eyes as I cried out: \\u201cQuincey Morris!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75017,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing strode forward, and took his hand, looking him straight in the eyes as he said:-\\u201cA brave man\\u2019s blood is the best thing on this earth when a woman is in trouble.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75206,\n            \"The Professor watched whilst I went downstairs with Quincey Morris, and sent one of the maids to pay off one of the cabmen who were waiting.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79157,\n            \"They are as follows:-Jack Smollet, of Dudding\\u2019s Rents, King George\\u2019s Road, Great Walworth, and Thomas Snelling, Peter Farley\\u2019s Row, Guide Court, Bethnal Green.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87751,\n            \"Arthur and Quincey went away together to the station, and Van Helsing and I came on here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103385,\n            \"\\u201cI\\u2019ll answer for the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103394,\n            \"I don\\u2019t quite see his drift, but I swear he\\u2019s honest;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103420,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI thank you, sir,\\u201dsaid Van Helsing proudly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103456,\n            \"\\u201d He held out a hand, which Quincey took.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107641,\n            \"- A little before twelve o\\u2019clock we three-Arthur, Quincey Morris, and myself-called for the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109093,\n            \"Van Helsing opened his missal and began to read, and Quincey and I followed as well as we could.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            135962,\n            \"By-and-by he stopped and said, turning from one to another of us:-\\u201cQuincey\\u2019s head is level.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141473,\n            \"Renfield proceeded:-\\u201cHe came up to the window in the mist, as I had seen him often before;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            142874,\n            \"Art and Quincey held back, and the latter said:-\\u201cShould we disturb her?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144760,\n            \"Just as I had finished, Quincey and Godalming knocked at the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152088,\n            \"- Just before we reached Fenchurch Street Lord Godalming said to me:-\\u201cQuincey and I will find a locksmith.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            152776,\n            \"It was immediately opened by Quincey Morris, beside whom stood Lord Godalming lighting a cigar.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            154347,\n            \"By my clock it is one hour and already, if all be well, friend Arthur and Quincey are on their way to us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            160986,\n            \"Present: Professor Van Helsing, Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, Mr. Quincey Morris, Jonathan Harker, Mina Harker.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            167263,\n            \"\\u201cGood boy,\\u201dsaid Dr. Van Helsing.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180864,\n            \"Now let me say that what I would is this: while you, my Lord Godalming and friend Jonathan go in your so swift little steamboat up the river, and whilst John and Quincey guard the bank where perchance he might be landed, I will take Madam Mina right into the heart of the enemy\\u2019s country.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 13]\": [\n        [\n            59141,\n            \"Telegram, Seward, London, to Van Helsing, Amsterdam.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59165,\n            \"\\u201d Telegram, Seward, London, to Van Helsing, Amsterdam.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59200,\n            \"\\u201d Telegram, Seward, London, to Van Helsing, Amsterdam.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71409,\n            \"Telegram, Van Helsing, Antwerp, to Seward, Carfax.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            71742,\n            \"I was not afraid, but I did wish that Dr. Seward was in the next room-as Dr. Van Helsing said he would be-so that I might have called him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74946,\n            \"\\u201d He handed me a telegram:-\\u201cHave not heard from Seward for three days, and am terribly anxious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            124458,\n            \"I will undertake that if you will satisfy even me-a stranger, without prejudice, and with the habit of keeping an open mind-Dr. Seward will give you, at his own risk and on his own responsibility, the privilege you seek.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 14]\": [\n        [\n            144760,\n            \"Just as I had finished, Quincey and Godalming knocked at the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            158660,\n            \"In two or three minutes later Van Helsing was in the room in his dressing-gown, and Mr. Morris and Lord Godalming were with Dr. Seward at the door asking questions.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 15]\": [\n        [\n            61346,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur turned to him and said:-\\u201cIf you only knew how gladly I would die for her you would understand--\\u201dHe stopped, with a sort of choke in his voice.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61670,\n            \"When the Professor was satisfied he called Arthur into the room, and bade him strip off his coat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61690,\n            \"Then he added: \\u201cYou may take that one little kiss whiles I bring over the table.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61728,\n            \"Van Helsing turning to me, said: \\u201cHe is so young and strong and of blood so pure that we need not defibrinate it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61858,\n            \"But the Professor\\u2019s face was set, and he stood watch in hand and with his eyes fixed now on the patient and now on Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61938,\n            \"I dressed the wound and took his arm to bring him away, when Van Helsing spoke without turning round-the man seems to have eyes in the back of his head:-\\u201cThe brave lover, I think, deserve another kiss, which he shall have presently.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62059,\n            \"Arthur did not notice it, but I could hear the deep hiss of indrawn breath which is one of Van Helsing\\u2019s ways of betraying emotion.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62088,\n            \"He said nothing at the moment, but turned to me, saying: \\u201cNow take down our brave young lover, give him of the port wine, and let him lie down a while.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            63272,\n            \"I sent a short wire to Van Helsing and to Arthur, telling them of the excellent result of the operation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65593,\n            \"\\u201cNay, but they are not to take in a decoction or in nauseous form, so you need not snub that so charming nose, or I shall point out to my friend Arthur what woes he may have to endure in seeing so much beauty that he so loves so much distort.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65676,\n            \"I put him in your window, I make pretty wreath, and hang him round your neck, so that you sleep well.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76139,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cThat\\u2019s so,\\u201dI said, and he went on:-\\u201cI take it that both you and Van Helsing had done already what I did to-day.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77161,\n            \"Quincey went off to meet him at the station.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77321,\n            \"It was now nearly one o\\u2019clock, and he and Van Helsing are sitting with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79878,\n            \"Van Helsing was very kind to him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79886,\n            \"\\u201cCome, my child,\\u201dhe said;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80004,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur went off with him, casting back a longing look on Lucy\\u2019s face, which lay in her pillow, almost whiter than the lawn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80470,\n            \"Arthur had then fallen into a doze, and he mercifully let him sleep on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80739,\n            \"I assured him that Lucy was still asleep, but told him as gently as I could that both Van Helsing and I feared that the end was near.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80939,\n            \"\\u201d He was stooping to kiss her, when Van Helsing motioned him back.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81156,\n            \"but at that instant Van Helsing, who, like me, had been startled by her voice, swooped upon him, and catching him by the neck with both hands, dragged him back with a fury of strength which I never thought he could have possessed, and actually hurled him almost across the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81438,\n            \"Then he turned to Arthur, and said to him: \\u201cCome, my child, take her hand in yours, and kiss her on the forehead, and only once.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81492,\n            \"and Van Helsing, who had been watching closely, took Arthur\\u2019s arm, and drew him away.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84627,\n            \"The Professor noticed it, too, and motioned me to bring him upstairs.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85911,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur spoke out heartily, like his old self:-\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, you may do what you will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87751,\n            \"Arthur and Quincey went away together to the station, and Van Helsing and I came on here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103022,\n            \"he told us all that he wanted us to do, but especially addressing himself to Arthur, as if all our wills were centred in his.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103083,\n            \"You were doubtless surprised at my letter?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103467,\n            \"Then Arthur spoke out:-\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, I don\\u2019t quite like to \\u2018 buy a pig in a poke,\\u2019as they say in Scotland, and if it be anything in which my honour as a gentleman or my faith as a Christian is concerned, I cannot make such a promise.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103529,\n            \"If you can assure me that what you intend does not violate either of these two, then I give my consent at once;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103554,\n            \"though for the life of me, I cannot understand what you are driving at.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103570,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cI accept your limitation,\\u201dsaid Van Helsing, \\u201cand all I ask of you is that if you feel it necessary to condemn any act of mine, you will first consider it well and be satisfied that it does not violate your reservations.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103828,\n            \"but in this-this desecration of the grave-of one who--\\u201dHe fairly choked with indignation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103850,\n            \"The Professor looked pityingly at him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103857,\n            \"\\u201cIf I could spare you one pang, my poor friend,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cGod knows I would.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103909,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur looked up with set white face and said:-\\u201cTake care, sir, take care!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103950,\n            \"\\u201cAnd then you will at least know the limit of my purpose.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104215,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing, you try me too far.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104226,\n            \"What have I done to you that you should torture me so?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106399,\n            \"My own heart grew cold as ice, and I could hear the gasp of Arthur, as we recognised the features of Lucy Westenra.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            106926,\n            \"She was leaping for them, when Van Helsing sprang forward and held between them his little golden crucifix.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107167,\n            \"Van Helsing broke the silence by asking Arthur:-\\u201cAnswer me, oh my friend!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107193,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur threw himself on his knees, and hid his face in his hands, as he answered:-\\u201cDo as you will, friend;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107502,\n            \"\\u201d Coming close to Arthur, he said:-\\u201cMy friend Arthur, you have had a sore trial;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107641,\n            \"- A little before twelve o\\u2019clock we three-Arthur, Quincey Morris, and myself-called for the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107889,\n            \"When he again lifted the lid off Lucy\\u2019s coffin we all looked-Arthur trembling like an aspen-and saw that the body lay there in all its death-beauty.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107966,\n            \"Presently he said to Van Helsing:-\\u201cIs this really Lucy\\u2019s body, or only a demon in her shape?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108796,\n            \"he stepped forward and said bravely, though his hand trembled, and his face was as pale as snow:-\\u201cMy true friend, from the bottom of my broken heart I thank you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108848,\n            \"\\u201d Van Helsing laid a hand on his shoulder, and said:-\\u201cBrave lad!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109606,\n            \"Van Helsing came and laid his hand on Arthur\\u2019s shoulder, and said to him:-\\u201cAnd now, Arthur my friend, dear lad, am I not forgiven?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109641,\n            \"\\u201d The reaction of the terrible strain came as he took the old man\\u2019s hand in his, and raising it to his lips, pressed it, and said:-\\u201cForgiven!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109678,\n            \"God bless you that you have given my dear one her soul again, and me peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109696,\n            \"\\u201d He put his hands on the Professor\\u2019s shoulder, and laying his head on his breast, cried for a while silently, whilst we stood unmoving.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109727,\n            \"When he raised his head Van Helsing said to him:-\\u201cAnd now, my child, you may kiss her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109892,\n            \"When the Professor locked the door he gave the key to Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144901,\n            \"Van Helsing said gravely:-\\u201cGo on, friend Arthur.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 16]\": [\n        [\n            57004,\n            \"He came on with me to Hillingham, and found that, by Lucy\\u2019s discretion, her mother was lunching out, so that we were alone with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59320,\n            \"I took advantage of the opportunity, and told her that my old master, Van Helsing, the great specialist, was coming to stay with me, and that I would put her in his charge conjointly with myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59535,\n            \"I wrote him a letter simply telling him that you were coming, as Miss Westenra was not so well, and that I should let him know if need be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60001,\n            \"I have sown my corn, and Nature has her work to do in making it sprout;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            60528,\n            \"Van Helsing and I were shown up to Lucy\\u2019s room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61553,\n            \"Then he mixed a narcotic, and coming over to the bed, said cheerily:-\\u201cNow, little miss, here is your medicine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61590,\n            \"See, I lift you so that to swallow is easy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61716,\n            \"\\u201d So neither of us looked whilst he bent over her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61858,\n            \"But the Professor\\u2019s face was set, and he stood watch in hand and with his eyes fixed now on the patient and now on Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61918,\n            \"I will look to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61991,\n            \"\\u201d And as he had now finished his operation, he adjusted the pillow to the patient\\u2019s head.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62012,\n            \"As he did so the narrow black velvet band which she seems always to wear round her throat, buckled with an old diamond buckle which her lover had given her, was dragged a little up, and showed a red mark on her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62280,\n            \"By the bedside sat Van Helsing, looking at her intently.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62301,\n            \"I asked the Professor in a whisper:-\\u201cWhat do you make of that mark on her throat?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62653,\n            \"He came back a moment later and put his head inside the door and said with warning finger held up:-\\u201cRemember, she is your charge.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62777,\n            \"When I told Mrs. Westenra that Dr. Van Helsing had directed that I should sit up with her she almost pooh-poohed the idea, pointing out her daughter\\u2019s renewed strength and excellent spirits.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64267,\n            \"He felt her heart, and after a few moments of agonising suspense said:-\\u201cIt is not too late.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64437,\n            \"\\u201cDo not stir,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cbut I fear that with growing strength she may wake;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            64652,\n            \"\\u201d When we stopped the operation, he attended to Lucy, whilst I applied digital pressure to my own incision.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65261,\n            \"I stay here to-night, and I shall sit up with little miss myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65493,\n            \"Found Van Helsing in excellent spirits, and Lucy much better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            65747,\n            \"\\u201d Whilst he was speaking, Lucy had been examining the flowers and smelling them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66240,\n            \"\\u201d he answered quietly as he began to make the wreath which Lucy was to wear round her neck.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66260,\n            \"We then waited whilst Lucy made her toilet for the night, and when she was in bed he came and himself fixed the wreath of garlic round her neck.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66291,\n            \"The last words he said to her were:-\\u201cTake care you do not disturb it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73815,\n            \"Without a word the Professor bent over the bed, his head almost touching poor Lucy\\u2019s breast;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            73950,\n            \"He rubbed the brandy, as on another occasion, on her lips and gums and on her wrists and the palms of her hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74358,\n            \"He answered me in a way that I did not understand, but with the sternest look that his face could wear:-\\u201cIf that were all, I would stop here where we are now, and let her fade away into peace, for I see no light in life over her horizon.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74473,\n            \"Van Helsing\\u2019s face almost beamed, and as we lifted her from the bath and rolled her in a hot sheet to dry her he said to me:-\\u201cThe first gain is ours!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74548,\n            \"I noticed that Van Helsing tied a soft silk handkerchief round her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            74585,\n            \"Van Helsing called in one of the women, and told her to stay with her and not to take her eyes off her till we returned, and then beckoned me out of the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75340,\n            \"He handed me the paper saying only: \\u201cIt dropped from Lucy\\u2019s breast when we carried her to the bath.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75566,\n            \"I know, and you know, and the other doctor who attended her knows, that Mrs. Westenra had disease of the heart, and we can certify that she died of it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75666,\n            \"One, two, three, all open their veins for her, besides one old man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75747,\n            \"and that Van Helsing and I were with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75869,\n            \"She was still sleeping, and the Professor seemingly had not moved from his seat at her side.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75888,\n            \"From his putting his finger to his lips, I gathered that he expected her to wake before long and was afraid of forestalling nature.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76662,\n            \"\\u201d When she woke late in the afternoon, Lucy\\u2019s first movement was to feel in her breast, and, to my surprise, produced the paper which Van Helsing had given me to read.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76701,\n            \"The careful Professor had replaced it where it had come from, lest on waking she should be alarmed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76721,\n            \"Her eye then lit on Van Helsing and on me too, and gladdened.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76880,\n            \"Van Helsing stepped over and took the pieces from her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76975,\n            \"The Professor and I took it in turns to watch, and we never left her for a moment unattended.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77061,\n            \"At times she slept, and both Van Helsing and I noticed the difference in her, between sleeping and waking.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77321,\n            \"It was now nearly one o\\u2019clock, and he and Van Helsing are sitting with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79809,\n            \"I duly relieved Van Helsing in his watch over Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80004,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur went off with him, casting back a longing look on Lucy\\u2019s face, which lay in her pillow, almost whiter than the lawn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80080,\n            \"the whole of the window-sashes reeked with it, and round Lucy\\u2019s neck, over the silk handkerchief which Van Helsing made her keep on, was a rough chaplet of the same odorous flowers.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80486,\n            \"When he saw Lucy\\u2019s face I could hear the sissing indraw of his breath, and he said to me in a sharp whisper: \\u201cDraw up the blind;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80523,\n            \"\\u201d Then he bent down, and, with his face almost touching Lucy\\u2019s, examined her carefully.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80739,\n            \"I assured him that Lucy was still asleep, but told him as gently as I could that both Van Helsing and I feared that the end was near.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80847,\n            \"\\u201d When we came into Lucy\\u2019s room I could see that Van Helsing had, with his usual forethought, been putting matters straight and making everything look as pleasing as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80882,\n            \"He had even brushed Lucy\\u2019s hair, so that it lay on the pillow in its usual sunny ripples.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81288,\n            \"I kept my eyes fixed on Lucy, as did Van Helsing, and we saw a spasm as of rage flit like a shadow over her face;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81589,\n            \"I went back to the room, and found Van Helsing looking at poor Lucy, and his face was sterner than ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81699,\n            \"\\u201d I stood beside Van Helsing, and said:-\\u201cAh, well, poor girl, there is peace for her at last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82007,\n            \"He insisted upon looking over Lucy\\u2019s papers himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82115,\n            \"\\u201d As he spoke he took from his pocket-book the memorandum which had been in Lucy\\u2019s breast, and which she had torn in her sleep.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82175,\n            \"For me, I watch here in the room and in Miss Lucy\\u2019s old room all night, and I myself search for what may be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87342,\n            \"and now a telegram from Van Helsing, whoever he may be:-\\u201cYou will be grieved to hear that Mrs. Westenra died five days ago, and that Lucy died the day before yesterday.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90684,\n            \"and as he attended poor dear Lucy in her last illness, he can tell me all about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90803,\n            \"She must have told him of her sleep-walking adventure on the cliff, and that I knew all about it;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90826,\n            \"and now he wants me to tell him what she knows, so that he may understand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91030,\n            \"I am so glad I have type-written out my own journal, so that, in case he asks about Lucy, I can hand it to him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91260,\n            \"Dr. Van Helsing must be a good man as well as a clever one if he is Arthur\\u2019s friend and Dr. Seward\\u2019s, and if they brought him all the way from Holland to look after Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91869,\n            \"I know that you were with her at Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92254,\n            \"but I had been thinking that it was of dear Lucy that you wished to ask, and so that you might not have time to wait-not on my account, but because I know your time must be precious-I have written it out on the typewriter for you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97655,\n            \"He threw himself with a despairing gesture into a chair, and placed his elbows on the table, covering his face with his hands as he spoke:-\\u201cThey were made by Miss Lucy!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            97713,\n            \"it was as if he had during her life struck Lucy on the face.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            100896,\n            \"Van Helsing walked over to Lucy\\u2019s coffin, and I followed.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101300,\n            \"She was bitten by the vampire when she was in a trance, sleep-walking-oh, you start;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103982,\n            \"After a pause Van Helsing went on, evidently with an effort:-\\u201cMiss Lucy is dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104239,\n            \"What did that poor, sweet girl do that you should want to cast such dishonour on her grave?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107924,\n            \"But there was no love in my own heart, nothing but loathing for the foul Thing which had taken Lucy\\u2019s shape without her soul.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107966,\n            \"Presently he said to Van Helsing:-\\u201cIs this really Lucy\\u2019s body, or only a demon in her shape?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109678,\n            \"God bless you that you have given my dear one her soul again, and me peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109727,\n            \"When he raised his head Van Helsing said to him:-\\u201cAnd now, my child, you may kiss her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110327,\n            \"\\u201cAh, that wonderful Madam Mina,\\u201dhe said, \\u201cpearl among women!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110344,\n            \"She arrive, but I cannot stay.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110395,\n            \"over it he told me of a diary kept by Jonathan Harker when abroad, and gave me a typewritten copy of it, as also of Mrs. Harker\\u2019s diary at Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115592,\n            \"Of course they had heard Lucy speak of me, and it seemed that Dr. Van Helsing, too, has been quite \\u201cblowing my trumpet,\\u201das Mr. Morris expressed it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115916,\n            \"Besides, I know you loved my poor Lucy-\\u201d Here he turned away and covered his face with his hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116093,\n            \"I said to him, for I could see that his heart was breaking:-\\u201cI loved dear Lucy, and I know what she was to you, and what you were to her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116138,\n            \"and now she is gone, will you not let me be like a sister to you in your trouble?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116176,\n            \"If sympathy and pity can help in your affliction, won\\u2019t you let me be of some little service-for Lucy\\u2019s sake?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            116562,\n            \"You will let me be like a brother, will you not, for all our lives-for dear Lucy\\u2019s sake?\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[5, 17]\": [\n        [\n            90646,\n            \"- I cannot help feeling terribly excited as the time draws near for the visit of Dr. Van Helsing, for somehow I expect that it will throw some light upon Jonathan\\u2019s sad experience;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            91322,\n            \"When he comes to-morrow I shall ask him about Jonathan;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            92855,\n            \"\\u201d I saw here an opening to ask him about Jonathan, so I said:-\\u201cHe was almost recovered, but he has been greatly upset by Mr. Hawkins\\u2019 s death.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93042,\n            \"I suppose I was hysterical, for I threw myself on my knees and held up my hands to him, and implored him to make my husband well again.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93269,\n            \"for if your husband suffer, he suffer within the range of my study and experience.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93286,\n            \"I promise you that I will gladly do all for him that I can-all to make his life strong and manly, and your life a happy one.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93426,\n            \"And then, too, you will tell me of husband Jonathan\\u2019s trouble so far as you can, but not yet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93463,\n            \"\\u201d After lunch, when we went back to the drawing-room, he said to me:-\\u201cAnd now tell me all about him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93492,\n            \"\\u201d When it came to speaking to this great learned man, I began to fear that he would think me a weak fool, and Jonathan a madman-that journal is all so strange-and I hesitated to go on.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93536,\n            \"But he was so sweet and kind, and he had promised to help, and I trusted him, so I said:-\\u201cDr. Van Helsing, what I have to tell you is so queer that you must not laugh at me or at my husband.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93860,\n            \"\\u201cI shall in the morning, so soon as I can, come to see you and your husband, if I may.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            93929,\n            \"\\u201d He was surprised at my knowledge of the trains off-hand, but he does not know that I have made up all the trains to and from Exeter, so that I may help Jonathan in case he is in a hurry.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94022,\n            \"\\u201cDear Madam Mina,-\\u201cI have read your husband\\u2019s so wonderful diary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94088,\n            \"and let me tell you from experience of men, that one who would do as he did in going down that wall and to that room-ay, and going a second time-is not one to be injured in permanence by a shock.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94145,\n            \"this I swear, before I have even seen him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            94161,\n            \"I shall have much to ask him of other things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            110395,\n            \"over it he told me of a diary kept by Jonathan Harker when abroad, and gave me a typewritten copy of it, as also of Mrs. Harker\\u2019s diary at Whitby.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            112538,\n            \"Jonathan and I have been working day and night since Professor Van Helsing saw us.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120222,\n            \"\\u201d Whilst he was speaking, Jonathan had taken my hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            120307,\n            \"When the Professor had done speaking my husband looked in my eyes, and I in his;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143767,\n            \"I must wake him!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            143772,\n            \"\\u201d He dipped the end of a towel in cold water and with it began to flick him on the face, his wife all the while holding her face between her hands and sobbing in a way that was heart-breaking to hear.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144601,\n            \"After a while her sobs became less frequent and more faint, and then he said to me, speaking with a studied calmness which I felt tried his nervous power to the utmost:-\\u201cAnd now, Dr. Seward, tell me all about it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144666,\n            \"\\u201d I told him exactly what had happened, and he listened with seeming impassiveness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144682,\n            \"but his nostrils twitched and his eyes blazed as I told how the ruthless hands of the Count had held his wife in that terrible and horrid position, with her mouth to the open wound in his breast.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166073,\n            \"You can ask Dr. Van Helsing if I am not right;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            166086,\n            \"if he disagrees you may do as you will.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173762,\n            \"See I read here what Jonathan have written:-\\u201cThat other of his race who, in a later age, again and again, brought his forces over The Great River into Turkey Land;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180705,\n            \") He was silent awhile, and during his silence Dr. Van Helsing spoke:-\\u201cFriend Jonathan, this is to you for twice reasons.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180864,\n            \"Now let me say that what I would is this: while you, my Lord Godalming and friend Jonathan go in your so swift little steamboat up the river, and whilst John and Quincey guard the bank where perchance he might be landed, I will take Madam Mina right into the heart of the enemy\\u2019s country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181060,\n            \"\\u201d Here Jonathan interrupted him hotly:-\\u201cDo you mean to say, Professor Van Helsing, that you would bring Mina, in her sad case and tainted as she is with that devil\\u2019s illness, right into the jaws of his death-trap?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181122,\n            \"\\u201d He became almost speechless for a minute, and then went on:-\\u201cDo you know what the place is?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181248,\n            \"The Professor\\u2019s voice, as he spoke in clear, sweet tones, which seemed to vibrate in the air, calmed us all:-\\u201cOh, my friend, it is because I would save Madam Mina from that awful place that I would go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181363,\n            \"If the Count escape us this time-and he is strong and subtle and cunning-he may choose to sleep him for a century, and then in time our dear one \\\"-he took my hand-\\\" would come to him to keep him company, and would be as those others that you, Jonathan, saw.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181463,\n            \"Forgive me that I make you so much pain, but it is necessary.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            181524,\n            \"\\u201d \\u201cDo as you will,\\u201dsaid Jonathan, with a sob that shook him all over, \\u201cwe are in the hands of God!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            189865,\n            \"- It was late in the afternoon when the Professor and I took our way towards the east whence I knew Jonathan was coming.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190169,\n            \"In a little while the Professor signalled to me, so I got up and joined him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190213,\n            \"He took me by the hand and drew me in: \\u201cSee!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190253,\n            \"\\u201d He brought in our furs, and made a snug nest for me, and got out some provisions and forced them upon me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190285,\n            \"to even try to do so was repulsive to me, and, much as I would have liked to please him, I could not bring myself to the attempt.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190317,\n            \"He looked very sad, but did not reproach me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190369,\n            \"\\u201d I sprang up and stood beside him on the rock;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190381,\n            \"he handed me his glasses and pointed.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 7]\": [\n        [\n            314,\n            \"it had struck me that some foreknowledge of the country could hardly fail to have some importance in dealing with a nobleman of that country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            340,\n            \"I find that the district he named is in the extreme east of the country, just on the borders of three states, Transylvania, Moldavia and Bukovina, in the midst of the Carpathian mountains;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            428,\n            \"but I found that Bistritz, the post town named by Count Dracula, is a fairly well-known place.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            603,\n            \", I must ask the Count all about them.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1283,\n            \"Count Dracula had directed me to go to the Golden Krone Hotel, which I found, to my great delight, to be thoroughly old-fashioned, for of course I wanted to see all I could of the ways of the country.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1450,\n            \"I am anxiously expecting you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1483,\n            \"At the Borgo Pass my carriage will await you and will bring you to me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1499,\n            \"I trust that your journey from London has been a happy one, and that you will enjoy your stay in my beautiful land.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1535,\n            \"- I found that my landlord had got a letter from the Count, directing him to secure the best place on the coach for me;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            1657,\n            \"When I asked him if he knew Count Dracula, and could tell me anything of his castle, both he and his wife crossed themselves, and, saying that they knew nothing at all, simply refused to speak further.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2668,\n            \", I must ask the Count about these superstitions) When we started, the crowd round the inn door, which had by this time swelled to a considerable size, all made the sign of the cross and pointed two fingers towards me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            2759,\n            \"This was not very pleasant for me, just starting for an unknown place to meet an unknown man;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            4360,\n            \"I was now myself looking out for the conveyance which was to take me to the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            5075,\n            \"but a cloak was thrown over my shoulders, and a rug across my knees, and the driver said in excellent German:-\\u201cThe night is chill, mein Herr, and my master the Count bade me take all care of you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7339,\n            \"The old man motioned me in with his right hand with a courtly gesture, saying in excellent English, but with a strange intonation:-\\u201cWelcome to my house!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7380,\n            \"\\u201d He made no motion of stepping to meet me, but stood like a statue, as though his gesture of welcome had fixed him into stone.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7409,\n            \"The instant, however, that I had stepped over the threshold, he moved impulsively forward, and holding out his hand grasped mine with a strength which made me wince, an effect which was not lessened by the fact that it seemed as cold as ice-more like the hand of a dead than a living man.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7497,\n            \"\\u201d The strength of the handshake was so much akin to that which I had noticed in the driver, whose face I had not seen, that for a moment I doubted if it were not the same person to whom I was speaking;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7543,\n            \"so to make sure, I said interrogatively:-\\u201cCount Dracula?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7574,\n            \"and I bid you welcome, Mr. Harker, to my house.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7606,\n            \"\\u201d As he was speaking, he put the lamp on a bracket on the wall, and stepping out, took my luggage;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7631,\n            \"he had carried it in before I could forestall him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7642,\n            \"I protested but he insisted:-\\u201cNay, sir, you are my guest.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7670,\n            \"Let me see to your comfort myself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7678,\n            \"\\u201d He insisted on carrying my traps along the passage, and then up a great winding stair, and along another great passage, on whose stone floor our steps rang heavily.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            7712,\n            \"At the end of this he threw open a heavy door, and I rejoiced to see within a well-lit room in which a table was spread for supper, and on whose mighty hearth a great fire of logs, freshly replenished, flamed and flared.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 8]\": [\n        [\n            173495,\n            \"\\u201d I thought that the Professor was going to break down and have hysterics, just as he had when Lucy died, but with a great effort he controlled himself and was at perfect nervous poise when Mrs. Harker tripped into the room, bright and happy-looking and, in the doing of work, seemingly forgetful of her misery.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 9]\": [\n        [\n            171483,\n            \"his hands are cold as ice, and an hour ago I found him whetting the edge of the great Ghoorka knife which he now always carries with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            171979,\n            \"\\u201d I was about to ask him more, but Harker just then came in, and he held up a warning hand.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173495,\n            \"\\u201d I thought that the Professor was going to break down and have hysterics, just as he had when Lucy died, but with a great effort he controlled himself and was at perfect nervous poise when Mrs. Harker tripped into the room, bright and happy-looking and, in the doing of work, seemingly forgetful of her misery.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 11]\": [\n        [\n            113800,\n            \"He thinks that in the meantime I should see Renfield, as hitherto he has been a sort of index to the coming and going of the Count.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            113964,\n            \"I believe that, had I not had the chat with Harker and read the letters and the dates of his outbursts, I should have been prepared to sign for him after a brief time of observation.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 12]\": [\n        [\n            139064,\n            \"To-day Harker is out following up his clue, and Art and Quincey are looking after horses.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            175632,\n            \"Quincey raised his eyebrows slightly and looked at her intently, whilst Harker\\u2019s hand instinctively closed round the hilt of his Kukri.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 13]\": [\n        [\n            111578,\n            \"\\u201d By this time my mind was made up that the diary of a doctor who attended Lucy might have something to add to the sum of our knowledge of that terrible Being, and I said boldly:-\\u201cThen, Dr. Seward, you had better let me copy it out for you on my typewriter.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 14]\": [\n        [\n            117056,\n            \"- I got home at five o\\u2019clock, and found that Godalming and Morris had not only arrived, but had already studied the transcript of the various diaries and letters which Harker and his wonderful wife had made and arranged.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157754,\n            \"When they had retired, Quincey, Godalming, and I arranged that we should sit up, dividing the night between us, and watch over the safety of the poor stricken lady.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 16]\": [\n        [\n            110743,\n            \"\\u201cI knew you from the description of poor dear Lucy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            115916,\n            \"Besides, I know you loved my poor Lucy-\\u201d Here he turned away and covered his face with his hands.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[6, 17]\": [\n        [\n            94309,\n            \"I have this moment, whilst writing, had a wire from Jonathan, saying that he leaves by the 6: 25 to-night from Launceston and will be here at 10: 18, so that I shall have no fear to-night.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157147,\n            \"I know that you must fight-that you must destroy even as you destroyed the false Lucy so that the true Lucy might live hereafter;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157246,\n            \"\\u201d As she spoke I could see her husband\\u2019s face darken and draw together, as though the passion in him were shrivelling his being to its core.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157429,\n            \"Just think, my dear-I have been thinking all this long, long day of it-that.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[7, 16]\": [\n        [\n            118924,\n            \"\\u201d he said, \\u201cfor then we might have reached him in time to save poor Lucy.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[7, 17]\": [\n        [\n            180926,\n            \"Whilst the old fox is tied in his box, floating on the running stream whence he cannot escape to land-where he dares not raise the lid of his coffin-box lest his Slovak carriers should in fear leave him to perish-we shall go in the track where Jonathan went,-from Bistritz over the Borgo, and find our way to the Castle of Dracula.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 9]\": [\n        [\n            118562,\n            \"Madam Mina is with you?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118690,\n            \"Friend John, up to now fortune has made that woman of help to us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118832,\n            \"You tell me she has wrote all, then she must consult with us;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            172808,\n            \"and it will not matter when the sun set, since I am here with Madam to make report.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173495,\n            \"\\u201d I thought that the Professor was going to break down and have hysterics, just as he had when Lucy died, but with a great effort he controlled himself and was at perfect nervous poise when Mrs. Harker tripped into the room, bright and happy-looking and, in the doing of work, seemingly forgetful of her misery.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            173591,\n            \"Then holding the pages between his finger and thumb he said:-\\u201cFriend John, to you with so much of experience already-and you, too, dear Madam Mina, that are young-here is a lesson: do not fear ever to think.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[8, 17]\": [\n        [\n            185293,\n            \"\\u201cOf course I know it,\\u201dshe answer, and with a pause, add: \\u201cHave not my Jonathan travelled it and wrote of his travel?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            187503,\n            \"and as their laugh came through the silence of the night, they twined their arms and pointed to her, and said in those so sweet tingling tones that Jonathan said were of the intolerable sweetness of the water-glasses:-\\u201cCome, sister.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 12]\": [\n        [\n            118576,\n            \"And Arthur and my friend Quincey, they are with you, too?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            190858,\n            \"It must be Quincey and John.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 14]\": [\n        [\n            170745,\n            \"Morris and Godalming and I shall prevent interference, even if we have to use the arms which we shall have ready.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 15]\": [\n        [\n            61272,\n            \"John was to give his blood, as he is the more young and strong than me \\\"-here Arthur took my hand and wrung it hard in silence-\\\" but, now you are here, you are more good than us, old or young, who toil much in the world of thought.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79835,\n            \"It was only when I told him that we should want him to help us during the day, and that we must not all break down for want of rest, lest Lucy should suffer, that he agreed to go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80695,\n            \"\\u201d I went to the dining-room and waked him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80739,\n            \"I assured him that Lucy was still asleep, but told him as gently as I could that both Van Helsing and I feared that the end was near.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80809,\n            \"I took him by the hand and raised him up.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80820,\n            \"\\u201cCome,\\u201dI said, \\u201cmy dear old fellow, summon all your fortitude: it will be best and easiest for her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81082,\n            \"In a sort of sleep-waking, vague, unconscious way she opened her eyes, which were now dull and hard at once, and said in a soft, voluptuous voice, such as I had never heard from her lips:-\\u201cArthur!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81156,\n            \"but at that instant Van Helsing, who, like me, had been startled by her voice, swooped upon him, and catching him by the neck with both hands, dragged him back with a fury of strength which I never thought he could have possessed, and actually hurled him almost across the room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81546,\n            \"\\u201d I took Arthur by the arm, and led him away to the drawing-room, where he sat down, and covered his face with his hands, sobbing in a way that nearly broke me down to see.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 16]\": [\n        [\n            59303,\n            \"Mrs. Westenra was naturally anxious concerning Lucy, and has consulted me professionally about her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            59320,\n            \"I took advantage of the opportunity, and told her that my old master, Van Helsing, the great specialist, was coming to stay with me, and that I would put her in his charge conjointly with myself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            66905,\n            \"She greeted us warmly and said:-\\u201cYou will be glad to know that Lucy is better.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79549,\n            \"Forgive me, dear, if I worry you with my troubles in the midst of your own happiness;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79569,\n            \"but, Lucy dear, I must tell some one, for the strain of keeping up a brave and cheerful appearance to Jonathan tries me, and I have no one here that I can confide in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79664,\n            \"I shall try to run over to see you, dearest, if only for a few minutes.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79683,\n            \"Forgive me for troubling you.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79809,\n            \"I duly relieved Van Helsing in his watch over Lucy.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79835,\n            \"It was only when I told him that we should want him to help us during the day, and that we must not all break down for want of rest, lest Lucy should suffer, that he agreed to go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80278,\n            \"When I came back to my seat, I found that Lucy had moved slightly, and had torn away the garlic flowers from her throat.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80486,\n            \"When he saw Lucy\\u2019s face I could hear the sissing indraw of his breath, and he said to me in a sharp whisper: \\u201cDraw up the blind;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80739,\n            \"I assured him that Lucy was still asleep, but told him as gently as I could that both Van Helsing and I feared that the end was near.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80847,\n            \"\\u201d When we came into Lucy\\u2019s room I could see that Van Helsing had, with his usual forethought, been putting matters straight and making everything look as pleasing as possible.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81288,\n            \"I kept my eyes fixed on Lucy, as did Van Helsing, and we saw a spasm as of rage flit like a shadow over her face;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81589,\n            \"I went back to the room, and found Van Helsing looking at poor Lucy, and his face was sterner than ever.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            81699,\n            \"\\u201d I stood beside Van Helsing, and said:-\\u201cAh, well, poor girl, there is peace for her at last.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82588,\n            \"All Lucy\\u2019s loveliness had come back to her in death, and the hours that had passed, instead of leaving traces of \\u201cdecay\\u2019s effacing fingers,\\u201dhad but restored the beauty of life, till positively I could not believe my eyes that I was looking at a corpse.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            82902,\n            \"Oh, but I must not forget, my dear friend John, that you loved her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101300,\n            \"She was bitten by the vampire when she was in a trance, sleep-walking-oh, you start;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[9, 17]\": [\n        [\n            79452,\n            \"I try to cheer him up, and my belief in him helps him to have a belief in himself.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79569,\n            \"but, Lucy dear, I must tell some one, for the strain of keeping up a brave and cheerful appearance to Jonathan tries me, and I have no one here that I can confide in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            89825,\n            \"I am so glad that he has plenty of work to do, for that keeps his mind off the terrible things;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            180864,\n            \"Now let me say that what I would is this: while you, my Lord Godalming and friend Jonathan go in your so swift little steamboat up the river, and whilst John and Quincey guard the bank where perchance he might be landed, I will take Madam Mina right into the heart of the enemy\\u2019s country.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 11]\": [\n        [\n            78264,\n            \"As he passed the window of Renfield\\u2019s room, the patient began to rate him from within, and called him all the foul names he could lay his tongue to.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78298,\n            \"The man, who seemed a decent fellow enough, contented himself by telling him to \\u201cshut up for a foul-mouthed beggar,\\u201dwhereon our man accused him of robbing him and wanting to murder him and said that he would hinder him if he were to swing for it.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78418,\n            \"I pity ye and the guv\\u2019nor for havin\\u2019to live in the house with a wild beast like that.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78463,\n            \"he went away, followed by threats and curses and revilings from our man.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 15]\": [\n        [\n            77530,\n            \"After dinner Mr. Hawkins said:-\\u201c\\u2018 My dears, I want to drink your health and prosperity;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 16]\": [\n        [\n            77616,\n            \"\\u2019 I cried, Lucy dear, as Jonathan and the old man clasped hands.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[10, 17]\": [\n        [\n            77616,\n            \"\\u2019 I cried, Lucy dear, as Jonathan and the old man clasped hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77732,\n            \"Jonathan and Mr. Hawkins are busy all day;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77742,\n            \"for, now that Jonathan is a partner, Mr. Hawkins wants to tell him all about the clients.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[11, 12]\": [\n        [\n            140323,\n            \"When Quincey saw the attitude and state of the patient, and noted the horrible pool on the floor, he said softly:-\\u201cMy God!\"\n        ],\n        [\n            140363,\n            \"\\u201d I told him briefly, and added that we expected he would recover consciousness after the operation-for a short time, at all events.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            141037,\n            \"I dreamed \\\"-he stopped and seemed fainting, I called quietly to Quincey-\\\" The brandy-it is in my study-quick!\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[11, 13]\": [\n        [\n            124458,\n            \"I will undertake that if you will satisfy even me-a stranger, without prejudice, and with the habit of keeping an open mind-Dr. Seward will give you, at his own risk and on his own responsibility, the privilege you seek.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[11, 14]\": [\n        [\n            145050,\n            \"I looked into Renfield\\u2019s room;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[11, 15]\": [\n        [\n            145082,\n            \"so he bowed his head and moistening his lips with his tongue, added: \\u201cexcept that the poor fellow is dead.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[11, 17]\": [\n        [\n            115318,\n            \"It is, I suppose, the reaction from the haunting fear which I have had: that this terrible affair and the reopening of his old wound might act detrimentally on Jonathan.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[12, 14]\": [\n        [\n            140391,\n            \"He went at once and sat down on the edge of the bed, with Godalming beside him;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            144760,\n            \"Just as I had finished, Quincey and Godalming knocked at the door.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155464,\n            \"Godalming behind and Quincey in front stood just out of sight ready to move in front of the window.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157754,\n            \"When they had retired, Quincey, Godalming, and I arranged that we should sit up, dividing the night between us, and watch over the safety of the poor stricken lady.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[12, 15]\": [\n        [\n            75710,\n            \"\\u201d In the hall I met Quincey Morris, with a telegram for Arthur telling him that Mrs. Westenra was dead;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75757,\n            \"I told him where I was going, and he hurried me out, but as I was going said:-\\u201cWhen you come back, Jack, may I have two words with you all to ourselves?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75955,\n            \"When we were alone, he said to me:-\\u201cJack Seward, I don\\u2019t want to shove myself in anywhere where I\\u2019ve no right to be;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87461,\n            \"Arthur has gone back to Ring, and has taken Quincey Morris with him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87751,\n            \"Arthur and Quincey went away together to the station, and Van Helsing and I came on here.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            95699,\n            \"Quincey wrote me a line too, and from him I hear that Arthur is beginning to recover something of his old buoyancy;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102999,\n            \"Last night, at a little before ten o\\u2019clock, Arthur and Quincey came into Van Helsing\\u2019s room;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            105894,\n            \"Arthur and Quincey drew near also, as they too were curious.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107245,\n            \"Quincey and I simultaneously moved towards him, and took his arms.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107592,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur and Quincey came home with me, and we tried to cheer each other on the way.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107641,\n            \"- A little before twelve o\\u2019clock we three-Arthur, Quincey Morris, and myself-called for the Professor.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108214,\n            \"To me, a doctor\\u2019s preparations for work of any kind are stimulating and bracing, but the effect of these things on both Arthur and Quincey was to cause them a sort of consternation.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109817,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur bent and kissed her, and then we sent him and Quincey out of the tomb;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            118576,\n            \"And Arthur and my friend Quincey, they are with you, too?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            155343,\n            \"In all our hunting parties and adventures in different parts of the world, Quincey Morris had always been the one to arrange the plan of action, and Arthur and I had been accustomed to obey him implicitly.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[12, 16]\": [\n        [\n            75847,\n            \"I told him I would see him as soon as I knew about Lucy, and went up to her room.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87483,\n            \"I believe in my heart of hearts that he suffered as much about Lucy\\u2019s death as any of us;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[12, 17]\": [\n        [\n            180864,\n            \"Now let me say that what I would is this: while you, my Lord Godalming and friend Jonathan go in your so swift little steamboat up the river, and whilst John and Quincey guard the bank where perchance he might be landed, I will take Madam Mina right into the heart of the enemy\\u2019s country.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[13, 16]\": [\n        [\n            111291,\n            \"and as it is entirely-almost entirely-about my cases, it may be awkward-that is, I mean--\\u201dHe stopped, and I tried to help him out of his embarrassment:-\\u201cYou helped to attend dear Lucy at the end.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111373,\n            \"\\u201d To my surprise, he answered, with a horrorstruck look in his face:-\\u201cTell you of her death?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111842,\n            \"poor dear Lucy was right about him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            111918,\n            \"I know that Lucy told you of me;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[13, 17]\": [\n        [\n            113319,\n            \"Before I left him I remembered what Jonathan put in his diary of the Professor\\u2019s perturbation at reading something in an evening paper at the station at Exeter;\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[14, 15]\": [\n        [\n            145020,\n            \"\\u201d His face lit for a moment, but fell again as he went on: \\u201cI ran downstairs then, but could see no sign of him.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[14, 17]\": [\n        [\n            181708,\n            \"and now Lord Godalming and Jonathan have a lovely steam launch, with steam up ready to start at a moment\\u2019s notice.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[15, 16]\": [\n        [\n            61022,\n            \"\\u201cYou are to help her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61196,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur looked bewildered, and the Professor went on by explaining in a kindly way:-\\u201cYoung miss is bad, very bad.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61771,\n            \"As the transfusion went on something like life seemed to come back to poor Lucy\\u2019s cheeks, and through Arthur\\u2019s growing pallor the joy of his face seemed absolutely to shine.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61832,\n            \"It gave me an idea of what a terrible strain Lucy\\u2019s system must have undergone that what weakened Arthur only partially restored her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            61858,\n            \"But the Professor\\u2019s face was set, and he stood watch in hand and with his eyes fixed now on the patient and now on Arthur.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            62126,\n            \"He must then go home and rest, sleep much and eat much, that he may be recruited of what he has so given to his love.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            75996,\n            \"You know I loved that girl and wanted to marry her;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            76476,\n            \"Then I guess, Jack Seward, that that poor pretty creature that we all love has had put into her veins within that time the blood of four strong men.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77147,\n            \"In the afternoon she asked for Arthur, and we telegraphed for him.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77209,\n            \"When he saw her, Arthur was simply choking with emotion, and none of us could speak.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77279,\n            \"she rallied a little, and spoke to him more brightly than she had done since we arrived.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77321,\n            \"It was now nearly one o\\u2019clock, and he and Van Helsing are sitting with her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79835,\n            \"It was only when I told him that we should want him to help us during the day, and that we must not all break down for want of rest, lest Lucy should suffer, that he agreed to go.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80004,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur went off with him, casting back a longing look on Lucy\\u2019s face, which lay in her pillow, almost whiter than the lawn.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            80739,\n            \"I assured him that Lucy was still asleep, but told him as gently as I could that both Van Helsing and I feared that the end was near.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            83248,\n            \"Were you not amazed, nay horrified, when I would not let Arthur kiss his love-though she was dying-and snatched him away by all my strength?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            84946,\n            \"At last, after a long pause, he said to me in a faint whisper:-\\u201cJack, is she really dead?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85044,\n            \"It seemed to quite do away with any doubt, and, after kneeling beside the couch for a while and looking at her lovingly and long, he turned aside.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85181,\n            \"When he came out of the room again I told him of Arthur\\u2019s question, and he replied:-\\u201cI am not surprised.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            85366,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur held out his hand, and took the old man\\u2019s warmly.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            87652,\n            \"When it was all over, we were standing beside Arthur, who, poor fellow, was speaking of his part in the operation where his blood had been transfused to his Lucy\\u2019s veins;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101934,\n            \"He doubted me when I took him from her kiss when she was dying.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            101975,\n            \"and he may think that in some more mistaken idea this woman was buried alive;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102003,\n            \"He will then argue back that it is we, mistaken ones, that have killed her by our ideas;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            102048,\n            \"And he will sometimes think that she he loved was buried alive, and that will paint his dreams with horrors of what she must have suffered;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            103675,\n            \"\\u201d Arthur\\u2019s face fell as he said in an amazed sort of way:-\\u201cWhere poor Lucy is buried?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104018,\n            \"But if she be not dead--\\u201dArthur jumped to his feet.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            104198,\n            \"\\u201cNot for the wide world will I consent to any mutilation of her dead body.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            107966,\n            \"Presently he said to Van Helsing:-\\u201cIs this really Lucy\\u2019s body, or only a demon in her shape?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108397,\n            \"Friend Arthur, if you had met that kiss which you know of before poor Lucy die;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108415,\n            \"or again, last night when you open your arms to her, you would in time, when you had died, have become nosferatu, as they call it in Eastern Europe, and would all time make more of those Un-Deads that so have fill us with horror.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108635,\n            \"So that, my friend, it will be a blessed hand for her that shall strike the blow that sets her free.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            108758,\n            \"He saw, too, what we all did, the infinite kindness which suggested that his should be the hand which would restore Lucy to us as a holy, and not an unholy, memory;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109470,\n            \"There, in the coffin lay no longer the foul Thing that we had so dreaded and grown to hate that the work of her destruction was yielded as a privilege to the one best entitled to it, but Lucy as we had seen her in her life, with her face of unequalled sweetness and purity.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109678,\n            \"God bless you that you have given my dear one her soul again, and me peace.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109727,\n            \"When he raised his head Van Helsing said to him:-\\u201cAnd now, my child, you may kiss her.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            109751,\n            \"Kiss her dead lips if you will, as she would have you to, if for her to choose.\"\n        ]\n    ],\n    \"[16, 17]\": [\n        [\n            28816,\n            \"No, I don\\u2019t, for there was Mr. Morris telling us his stories, and Arthur never told any, and yet-- My dear, I am somewhat previous.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            36216,\n            \"I am unhappy about Lucy and about Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            47326,\n            \"I told her how anxious I was about Jonathan, and then she tried to comfort me.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            48490,\n            \"No news from Jonathan, and Lucy seems to be growing weaker, whilst her mother\\u2019s hours are numbering to a close.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52443,\n            \"She is a sweet, good soul, and the next day, when she saw I was troubled, she opened up the subject again, and after saying that she could never mention what my poor dear raved about, added: \\u2018 I can tell you this much, my dear: that it was not about anything which he has done wrong himself;\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52555,\n            \"\\u2019 I do believe the dear soul thought I might be jealous lest my poor dear should have fallen in love with any other girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52667,\n            \"I asked Sister Agatha, and she brought all his things.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52750,\n            \"Then he called me back, and when I came he had his hand over the note-book, and he said to me very solemnly:-\\u201c\\u2018 Wilhelmina\\u2019- I knew then that he was in deadly earnest, for he has never called me by that name since he asked me to marry him-\\u2018 you know, dear, my ideas of the trust between husband and wife: there should be no secret, no concealment.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            52939,\n            \"\\u2018 Are you willing, Wilhelmina, to share my ignorance?\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53204,\n            \"When the chaplain and the sisters had left me alone with my husband-oh, Lucy, it is the first time I have written the words \\u2018 my husband\\u2019- left me alone with my husband, I took the book from under his pillow, and wrapped it up in white paper, and tied it with a little bit of pale blue ribbon which was round my neck, and sealed it over the knot with sealing-wax, and for my seal I used my wedding ring.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            53364,\n            \"Then he took my hand in his, and oh, Lucy, it was the first time he took his wife\\u2019s hand, and said that it was the dearest thing in all the wide world, and that he would go through all the past again to win it, if need be.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            77616,\n            \"\\u2019 I cried, Lucy dear, as Jonathan and the old man clasped hands.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            78002,\n            \"and so, as you love me, and he loves me, and I love you with all the moods and tenses of the verb, I send you simply his \\u2018 love\\u2019instead.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            79569,\n            \"but, Lucy dear, I must tell some one, for the strain of keeping up a brave and cheerful appearance to Jonathan tries me, and I have no one here that I can confide in.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            86608,\n            \"He was very pale, and his eyes seemed bulging out as, half in terror and half in amazement, he gazed at a tall, thin man, with a beaky nose and black moustache and pointed beard, who was also observing the pretty girl.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            90712,\n            \"it is concerning Lucy and her sleep-walking, and not about Jonathan.\"\n        ],\n        [\n            157147,\n            \"I know that you must fight-that you must destroy even as you destroyed the false Lucy so that the true Lucy might live hereafter;\"\n        ]\n    ]\n}"